<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua     06-08 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels And Government Less Pessimistic At End Of Second Day Of
Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with end of talks, status of
talks; picks up 9th graf pvs: About the; Recasts 15th graf pvs,
``Information minister...'' to conform; picks up 16th pvs: Under
the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist government and U.S.-backed
rebels ended a second day of cease-fire talks late Wednesday,
softening earlier statements that disagreements were threatening
the negotiations.
   ``We discussed some substantial issues,'' rebel spokesman Bosco
Matamoros said at the end of the day-long talks. Asked if advances
had been made, he replied, ``I didn't say that.''
   Manuel Espinoza, the Sandinista government's information
minister, told reporters after the talks ended that the rebels
``recognized advances had been made.''
   Espinoza had painted a rosy picture of Tuesday's talks, only to
have his remarks disputed by the rebels. By midday Wednesday both
sides acknowledged problems.
   ``It has deterioriated, but it is pre-planned on the part of the
(Reagan) administration and the Contras,'' Deputy Foreign Minister
Victor Hugo Tinoco told journalists.
   He said there was a ``conspiracy to rupture the talks'' and
blame the breakdown on the Sandinista government.
   The rebels, known as Contras, accused the Sandinistas of being
evasive about when promised democratic reforms would be enacted.
   Meanwhile, police briefly detained 14 of about 30 members of
opposition political parties who held a march in downtown Managua,
the Interior Ministry said. Tinoco described the march as a
``provocation and violation of the law.''
   The Contras said no further talks on details of the cease-fire
plan signed March 23 would be held unless there is agreement in the
current, fourth round of talks.
   About the Contra charge of evasiveness on democratic reform,
Paul Reichler, a U.S. lawyer negotiating for the Sandinistas said:
``That's simply a lie and I won't be diplomatic about it.''
   He said the Contras were ``engaging in tactics'' to make it
appear the Sandinistas were unwilling to compromise and then to
seek U.S. military aid.
   On Tuesday, both sides reported headway on a government pledge
of democratic reforms, including freedom of the press, political
liberties, an end to Sandinista party control of the army, the
right to strike and changes in the electoral system.
   Contra delegate Roberto Ferrey said Wednesday, however: ``It is
not possible to continue a process in which one of the parts, the
Sandinista Front, has demonstrated that it does not have the
minimum desire to really seek a peaceful solution to the Nicaraguan
crisis.''
   Tension and mistrust have marked all the talks on ending the
war, which has lasted nearly seven years and taken almost 27,000
lives. Among the main snags are how to define democracy and the
timetable and mechanics of disarmament.
   Espinoza said Wednesday the government agreed to a Contra
request that humanitarian aid be delivered to the rebels in safe
areas by the Pan American Development Foundation, an agency of the
Organization of American States.
   Under the March 23 cease-fire agreement, aid can be delivered
after an independent verification commission certifies the rebels
have moved into seven designated zones. Representatives of the
Roman Catholic Church and OAS make up the commission.
   Espinoza said the government was sticking to its demand that the
rebel disarmament and return to civilian life be completed by the
end of September, but the Contras want that extended until the end
of January.
   Reichler claimed the Contra timetable was linked to the U.S.
election and inauguration of a new president to ``preserve a
military option.'' He called it ``one last role of the dice on a
Bush victory,'' referring to Vice President George Bush, the likely
Republican nominee.
   The demonstration Wednesday was called to protest a law that has
enabled the Sandinistats to close radio stations for broadcasting
what the government declares to be misingformation or unconfirmed
news about the war or military draft.
   Among those detained were Erick Ramirez, president of the Social
Christian Party.
</TEXT>
