<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BigFlag     06-08 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Big Flag,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge 13-Star Flag Unfurled As Celebration Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an unproven legend that Betsy Ross made
the nation's first official flag. But there was little disbelief
among children at her house to start the celebration of the 211th
anniversary of the flag's adoption by Congress.
   A 22-by-45-foot replica of the 13-star flag was unfurled Tuesday
down the side of a building as 30 schoolchildren watched, waving
smaller versions of the flag.
   Just who was Betsy Ross?
   ``She was the one that made the first American flag,'' said Paul
Sherlock, 11, from St. Charles Borromeo School in Cinnaminson, N.J.
   ``By making the first American flag she was like the first real
American,'' said classmate Matthew Kozlowski, 11.
   Ross has received popular credit as the seamstress who made the
13-star flag that was adopted by the Continental Congress on June
14, 1777. The anniversary will be celebrated with a ceremony next
Tuesday _ Flag Day _ in front of the house in which Mrs. Ross
supposedly sewed the banner.
   William Kingsley, director of the house near Independence Hall,
feels there is enough evidence to give Ross credit for the flag. In
any case, he said, she remains an important woman in the nation's
history.
   ``We know she made flags for the Pennsylvania Navy and musket
balls for the Continental Army. She was involved in the life of her
country,'' Kingsley said. ``I think if you took away the incident
of the flag, she'd still be worth knowing.''
   Kingsley said the huge flag was made three years ago in the
courtyard of the house by employees of Humphry's Flag Co., located
across the street.
   On Monday, Greg Scott, a descendant of Mrs. Ross, will
participate in a wreath-laying ceremony at the tomb of Mrs. Ross
and her third husband, John Claypoole, at a park next to the house.
</TEXT>
