<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DelawareStorm 1stLd-Writethru a0881 06-08 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Storm, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0881,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede Dover</HEAD>
<HEAD>High Winds, Rain, Rip Through Delaware</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE number of injured, most evacuees
returning. Picks up 11th graf pvs ``The Boondocks...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe storm packing 75-mph winds ripped
through Delaware Tuesday, downing trees, forcing the evacuation of
more than 500 people from a subdivision and causing power outages,
authorities said.
   At least 31 people were treated for mostly minor storm-related
injuries, Kent General Hospital in Dover reported.
   The storm swept through Cecil County in northeast Maryland,
before hitting Delaware between 4 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. It then headed
out to the Delaware Bay and the Atlantic Ocean, said the National
Weather Service.
   The heaviest damage appeared to be in the Smyrna and Woodland
Beach areas, just north of Dover, where residents say they saw a
tornado. Jim Saunders, a meteorologist with the weather service at
the Greater Wilmington Airport, said there were 75 mph winds, but
tornado reports could not be confirmed before Wednesday.
   Authorities evacuated resident from about 200 homes in the
Greenmeadows subdivision here because of concerns of electrical
fires from exposed wires in damaged homes. A majority of the homes
suffered some kind of damage, said Smyrna Mayor George Wright.
   All but about a dozen families were allowed to return by late
Tuesday night, said Herm Bruce, spokesman for the Delaware Division
of Emergency Planning and Operations.
   In addition, at least one trailer was blown away and others were
damaged in the rural areas east of Smyrna.
   At Kent General Hospital, one person was admitted in fair
condition with injuries suffered in an auto accident during the
storm, said Jean Bochnowski, hospital spokeswoman.
   ``We have primarily minor injuries, lacerations, bumps and
bruises. There are no major injuries,'' said Robert Groom, another
hospital spokesman.
   The Boondocks restaurant near Smyrna had from $150,000 to
$200,000 in damages, according to owner Jack Keeler, who had been
fishing when the storm hit.
   ``Me and my friend were on the beach loading the boat into the
truck when we saw a big black twister,'' said Keeler.
   ``It was a great big cloud just twisting. And then all hell broke
lose. Everything was destroyed _ gone. The roof blew off (my
restaurant) and the windows blew out.''
   In Maryland, an inch of hail fell in Cecil County, said the
National Weather Service. But the state police in neighboring Kent
County, Md., which also borders Delaware near Smyrna, said they had
no reports of a storm.
   A police dispatcher in North East, Md., said trees were uprooted
throughout Cecil County and the way the trees were knocked to one
side near the Chesapeake and Delaware Canal may indicate a small
twister.
   The National Weather Service planned to survey the path of
destruction Wednesday to determine if it was a tornado, a spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
