<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-08 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe the pig fled the bright footlights,
but a friendly farmer brought home the bacon after he found the
porcine cast member of a summer production wandering on his spread.
   The pig has been given a featured role in Grandview State Park's
annual outdoor production of the historical drama ``Hatfields and
McCoys.'' Joe will play the pig that sparked the legendary feud
between the mountain families along the West Virginia-Kentucky
border in the 1880s and 1890s.
   But on Sunday, the 5-week-old, 30-pound pig broke out of his pen
at the park and apparently began a trek to nearby Mossy, where he
was born and raised, Theater West Virginia prop manager Paul
Willard said.
   ``He missed his mother,'' Willard said.
   The crew was frantic, because Joe had no understudy and his role
was essential _ the Hatfield-McCoy feud began over ownershop of a
pig.
   ``We were in planning to hold auditions all next week,'' said
the theater's technical director, Tony Nye.
   On Monday, however, Bill Scott, a farmer who lives about half a
mile from the park, found Joe and started looking for the owner. He
read a newspaper article about the escape and contacted the theater.
   By Tuesday, Joe was back in the wings, awaiting rehearsals for
the show, which opens June 17.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They almost ran out of gas and were pulled over for
speeding, but an expectant mother's race against time ended happily
when she gave birth to a screaming baby boy on the side of the road.
   ``The officer at first didn't think it was that critical,'' said
Judith Castro, 22. ``But if he hadn't pulled us over, I would have
had it on the highway on the way to the hospital, right there in
the front seat.''
   Ms. Castro gave birth at 5 a.m. Tuesday to 6-pound, 4-ounce
Michael Robert Fitzgerald in the back of a parked Palm Beach County
fire-rescue ambulance.
   The ordeal began at 4:30, when Ms. Castro was awakened by labor
pains. She woke her husband, John Fitzgerald, who dressed the
couple's two other children and then remembered their car was low
on gasoline.
   The hospital is only 6 miles north of their Lake Worth home, but
Fitzgerald drove 4 miles west, to the only service station he could
find open.
   ``Here I am going to have this baby and he's pumping gas,'' Ms.
Castro said. Fitzgerald sped away with a full tank, and the deputy
stopped them minutes later.
   No ticket was issued.
</TEXT>
