<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FuelEconomy     06-08 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Economy,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Lower Auto Fuel Economy Standards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators complied with Congress' intent when
they sought to spare the automotive industry economic hardship by
lowering fuel-economy standards, a federal appeals court says.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia issued
that ruling Tuesday in turning down a petition attacking the lower
1986 standards. The petition was filed by the state of California,
the cities of New York and Los Angeles, and four public issues
groups.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration's
``consideration of the likelihood of economic hardship within its
assessment of `economic practicability' must be given due weight,''
the court said in an opinion by Judge Ruth Ginsburg.
   The agency's decision was based on an analysis that concluded
the higher standard would have severe economic effects throughout
the auto industry, and therefore was not arbitrary or capricious as
the petitioners alleged, the court said.
   NHTSA lowered the corporate average fuel economy, or CAFE,
standard automakers must meet in 1986 from the 27.5 mpg set by
Congress to 26 mpg. Standards for 1987 and 1988 were also lowered
to 26 mpg.
   Petitions also have been filed asking for review of the 1987 and
1988 standards. Con Hitchcock, an attorney for the public issues
groups, said they would reevaluate the petitions for 1987 and 1988
in light of the court's ruling.
   Although Congress set the standard at the higher level, it also
allowed NHTSA to set lower standards after considering economic
practicality, technological feasibility, the effect of other motor
vehicle standards, and the nation's need to conserve energy.
   The court rejected the petitioners' assertion that NHTSA failed
to consider energy conservation in adopting the lower standards.
   The agency had weighed increased fuel consumption against
economic harm under broad guidelines set by Congress.
   ``Had Congress offered a more precise balancing formula for the
agency to apply, ... we could more confidently discern the agency's
compliance with the congressional mandate,'' the court said.
   Lacking precise standards, NHTSA properly accommodated
conflicting policies in lowering the standard, the court said.
   Judge Abner Mikva joined Judge Ginsbug in the majority. Judge
Lawrence Silberman dissented in part.
   Public issues groups joining in the petition were Public
Citizen, the Center for Auto Safety, the Union of Concerned
Scientists and the Environmental Policy Institute.
</TEXT>
