<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSNurses     06-08 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Nurses,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Nurses Honored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's No. 2 health official
has selected 14 nurses for special recognition as a way to honor
the thousands who care for AIDS patients.
   In announcing his plans Tuesday, Dr. Robert E. Windom, the
assistant health and human services secretary for health, said
nurses ``have been the unsung heroes'' of the AIDS epidemic.
   He noted that physicians and research scientists, unlike nurses,
frequently come to public attention.
   Windom and other federal officials asked the American Journal of
Nursing and a number of local organizations to help select
individuals to represent nurses who care for AIDS patients.
   Although both private and public health officials say health
care workers who refuse to take care of AIDS patients are the
exception, they acknowledge that there are some nurses and others
who try to avoid AIDS patients _ apparently for fear of catching
the virus.
   ``I feel very strongly that nurses who are giving selfless,
dedicated care to people with AIDS have not received the
recognition they have merited,'' Windom said in a letter to the 14
nurses.
   Windom said each of the 14 has accepted an invitation to an
awards ceremony and luncheon in Washington on July 14.
   They are: Carol Price, Visiting Nurse Association of Brooklyn;
Mary Boland, director of AIDS nursing at Children's Hospital of New
Jersey, Newark, N.J.; Barbara Russell, Baptist Hospital, Miami,
Fla.; Tracey Castleman, Kansas University Medical Center, Kansas
City, Kan.; Christine Grady, National Institutes of Health,
Rockville, Md.; Nancy L. Sears, National Institutes of Health,
Rockville, Md.; Rose V. Thomas, National Institutes of Health,
Rockville, Md.; Terry Miles, St. Claire's Hospital, New York, N.Y.;
JoAnne Bennett, St. Vincent's Hospital, New York, N.Y.; Dorothy
Ward-Wimmer, Children's Hospital National Medical Center,
Washington; Brenda L. Staton, D.C. General Hospital, Washington;
Clifford L. Morrison, Robert Wood Johnson AIDS Health Services
Program, San Francisco; Helen Merie Miramontes, San Jose, Calif.;
and Helen K. Schietinger, California Nurses Association, San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
