<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan Bjt   06-08 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Threatens to Delay Soviet Pullout If Pakistan Continues Aid
To Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Najib, one name, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib of Afghanistan, in his
United Nations debut, threatened to seek a delay in the Soviet troop
withdrawal from his country if Pakistan continues its vigorous
support of anti-communist guerrillas.
   Najib also told a news conference Tuesday that more than 34,000
Soviet soldiers have left Afghanistan since May 15 under a
U.N.-mediated agreement calling for a complete Red Army pullout over
nine months.
   But Najib said his Marxist government could have the pace of
withdrawal slowed if neighboring Pakistan does not stop what he
called interference in Afghanistan's internal affairs.
   ``We want to visualize an optimistic situation,'' he said. ``But
should such violations acquire a permanent character ... in such a
case, we would certainly renew our consideration on the schedule of
withdrawal and take proper reactions, together with the Soviet
Union.''
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979. More
than 100,000 had until last month helped friendly governments fight
guerrillas backed by the United States, Pakistan and China.
   The guerrillas have repudiated the settlement signed April 14 in
Geneva. They reject Najib's government, refuse to join a coalition
government and vow to continue fighting Soviet and Afghan army
forces.
   On Tuesday, Western diplomats in Pakistan said Soviet troops are
delaying their pullout from Kandahar, Afghanistan's second largest
city, which has been under siege by guerrillas.
   Najib, asked about Kandahar, indicated developments there have
not necessarily changed the withdrawal timetable, to which he said
his government is determined to adhere.
   In a bid to win legitimacy for his embattled government, Najib
delivered a 30-minute speech in the Dari language Tuesday to a
special General Assembly session on disarmament.
   Pakistan boycotted the speech and the United States, which does
not recognize the Kabul government, sent a young Foreign Service
intern instead of a ranking diplomat. Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze and a high-level Soviet delegation attended.
   Asked about U.S. arms and support for the rebels, Najib noted
that the United States is a co-guarantor of the Geneva agreement.
   ``We expect the U.S.A., as a great, civilized and advanced
country to guarantee this internationally prestigious agreement and
not to destroy and spoil it,'' he said.
   In his speech, Najib said: ``In violation of the accords, camps
and centers for training of the extremist Afghan opposition still
exist on the territory of Pakistan. Huge amounts of arms are being
transported for subversion and terrorist activities in Afghanistan.''
   Najib told reporters that after Soviet troops withdraw, ``If the
interference from Pakistan is totally stopped, not only would the
(Afghan) armed forces resist but they would be able to give a rebuff
to the extremist forces of the opposition.''
   He said he seeks a broad coalition government, including Afghans
both within the nation and outside. Such a coalition would be viable
even without participation of the seven-party insurgents alliance,
which views the world ``through the barrel of a gun,'' he said.
   Najib declined, in answer to a question, to say whether he might
step down in an effort to achieve national reconciliation. He said
he had been elected by a traditional council of the Afghan people.
   Najib called on the international community, lending institutions
and the United Nations to contribute to economic reconstruction and
rehabilitation of Afghanistan.
   Afghanistan's state-run Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad,
Pakistan, said Prime Minister Mohammad Hasan Sharq announced his
24-member Cabinet on Tuesday.
   Sharq replaced Sultan Ali Keshtmand on May 26. The time gap
between his appointment and formation of a government fueled
speculation that Najib faced a deep split within the governing
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   Najib is trying to hold together his Parcham faction, divided
between loyalty to him and to former President Babrak Karmal.
   Sharq's Cabinet returns Sayed Mohammad Gulabzoi, leader of the
party's opposition Khalq wing, to the Interior Ministry. Diplomatic
reports said Najib has been trying to push Gulabzoi out of the
government.
</TEXT>
