<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArabSummit     06-08 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab Summit,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hussein Strongly Urges Support for Palestinian Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein of Jordan has made an
unprecedented appeal to Arab summit members to support the
Palestinian uprising in Israel, comparing the riots and bloodshed
to Algeria's war of independence with France.
   Hussein, often accused by Arab hardliners of opposing the
Palestine Liberation Organization, called the 6-month-old uprising
in the Israeli-occupied lands ``the path to liberation and
dignity.''
   ``We extended to our Algerian brothers all the support that we
could as they struggled heroically ... to grasp their freedom from
ugly colonial occupation,'' he said after the emergency meeting of
Arab leaders opened Tuesday.
   ``Just as the Algerian revolution united Arabs, the Palestinian
revolution on the occupied Palestinian soil is uniting our
feelings,'' he declared.
   Algeria won independence in 1962 after seven years of bitter
struggle.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat in his remarks to the summit vowed to
keep up the uprising and inspire more riots until victory.
   He reiterated the PLO's traditional demands, ``the right to
return (to Palestine), the right to self-determination and right to
create an independent state with Jerusalem as its capital.''
   The three-day meeting of the 21-nation Arab League was convened
to support the Palestinian insurrection.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the June 1967 Six-Day War. Since anti-Israeli riots began
on Dec. 8, more than 200 Palestinians and two Israelis have been
killed.
   Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid adjourned the meeting, which
was to resume today behind closed doors. As the Arab League's
secretary-general, Benjedid is summit chairman.
   Hussein met before the summit with Arafat, who also met with
Saudi Arabia's King Fahd.
   A Palestinian source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Hussein-Arafat meeting ``was very warm and exceptionally
friendly.'' Their relations became strained after Hussein suspended
his efforts to work jointly with the PLO for a settlement with
Israel in February 1986.
   Bendjedid opened the summit by saying recognition of the PLO was
``the key to any settlement of the Middle East problem.''
   The United States and Israel both refuse to recognize the PLO as
spokesman for the Palestinians. Israel regards the PLO as a
terrorist organization.
   Summit sources said Arab leaders were discussing financial
support for the uprising in the range of $300 million to $400
million to compensate for loss of income caused by strikes.
   Other subjects likely to be raised at the summit include the
nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war and the return of Egypt to Arab
League. Egypt was expelled after signing a peace agreement with
Israel, brokered by then-President Carter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
