<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission     06-08 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Panel Endorses Chairman's Recommendations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the White House AIDS
commission says he senses momentum building in Congress for passage
of a federal law protecting people infected with the AIDS virus.
   Retired Navy Adm. James D. Watkins made that observation Tuesday
night as the panel tentatively endorsed most of the 579
recommendations he presented last week _ including the linchpin
call for anti-discrimination legislation.
   He said he has received encouraging letters from ``both sides of
the aisle.''
   ``There is a feeling of momentum in Congress,'' he said, adding
that passage of anti-discrimination legislation ``is something that
can be done in this session of Congress. I don't know that it will
be.''
   Watkins' comments came as he urged the commission to agree with
his plan to give top priority to the anti-discrimination issue in
the introduction of the final report due at the White House June
24. The Reagan administration has opposed such legislation.
   Among the other recommendations the panel agreed to emphasize at
the forefront of its final report:
   _That all of those infected with the AIDS virus _ an estimated
1.5 million Americans compared to less than 70,000 actually
diagnosed with the full-blown illness _ should be considered part
of the epidemic.
   _That intravenous drug abuse is a national emergency that must
be successfully dealt with if the AIDS epidemic is to be curtailed.
   _That the fight against the disease will require private as well
as government resources.
   _That compassion for those with AIDS should be emphasized at all
levels.
   Just as Watkins' prediction last week that most of his
recommendations reflected the full panel's consensus proved true,
so did his guess that his final chapter _ which he emphasized had
not undergone advance discussion _ would run into opposition.
   That was where he called for legislation to vest sweeping new
powers in the surgeon general _ currently Dr. C. Everett Koop _ to
deal with national medical emergencies.
   Watkins said immediately after approval of such legislation,
President Reagan should proclaim AIDS such an emergency and put
Koop in charge of dealing with it.
   The commission did not reject those suggestions outright, but it
was clear they do not have broad backing.
   The issue of what _ if anything _ to recommend in the way of
administrative changes to deal with AIDS, as well as future
epidemics, was put off to next week when the commission meets
Thursday and Friday.
</TEXT>
