<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Duarte     06-08 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Duarte,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran President's Has Operation; Cancer Called Terminal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte will
probably undergo chemotherapy to treat the cancer that has spread
from his stomach to his liver, but Duarte's personal physician says
the malignancy is terminal.
   Duarte underwent three hours of cancer surgery Tuesday at Walter
Reed Army Medical Center in which doctors removed a portion of his
stomach but left his diseased liver alone.
   ``There was metastatic disease present in both lobes of the
liver, and this was not removed,'' a hospital statement said.
   ``That is going to end the life of President Duarte,'' said Dr.
Benjamin Interiano, Duarte's personal physician. He said the
average life expectancy for someone in Duarte's condition is six
months, but some patients live longer, others shorter.
   Following Duarte's recuperation from surgery, ``this disease
will probably be treated with chemotherapy,'' the hospital
statement said.
   Duarte, 62, ``tolerated the surgery well,'' it said, describing
the operation as ``uneventful.''
   The Salvadoran leader, who was hospitalized here May 31, will
remain in intensive care for a few days before returning to his
regular hospital room for convalescence. Duarte's family members
were at the hospital.
   Duarte, one of the United States' staunchest allies in Latin
America, is in the final year of a five-year presidential term.
   Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount is serving as acting
president of El Salvador in Duarte's absence.
</TEXT>
