<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OperationHeartbreak     06-08 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Operation Heartbreak,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motives of South African Children Lobby Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocacy group is calling on members of
Congress to do more to help black South African children, saying
they will be hurt by stronger U.S. economic sanctions against the
segregated nation.
   The Wake Up America Coalition dramatized its ``Operation
Heartbreak'' campaign on Tuesday by arranging for groups of black
children to visit congressional offices.
   Some supporters of tougher sanctions, intended to pressure the
white minority government in Pretoria into granting more freedoms
to blacks, expressed skepticism about the group's motives.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., called the campaign a ``a front
for one of the many South African supported and funded groups.
There is no question in my mind that this is designed to develop
opposition to the (sanctions) bill.''
   But the Rev. Kenneth Frazier, chairman of the coalition, said,
``No matter what political side you're on, anti-sanctions,
pro-sanctions, anti-sanctions, it doesn't matter.
   ``We are here in the interest of millions of suffering black
South African children who are already the poorest and the most
helpless and the most vulnerable in South Africa (who will) be
further harassed ... and suffer all the more with a further round
of U.S. sanctions,'' he said.
   ``We are tired of seeing black and brown children the world over
always carrying the political burdens and consequences of these
irrational struggles for power among politicians East and West.''
   Fraizer maintained that the campaign was not inspired by the
vote on the Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act of 1988 scheduled for
the end of June. He said his position is based on his own trips to
South Africa.
   ``They are caught between apartheid and U.S. sanctions which
represent another form of hostility and oppression,'' he said of
the country's blacks.
   The coalition is delivering dolls of black children to
congressional offices, accompanied by letters appealing for
contributions to help feed and clothe black South African children.
   The letters ask recipients to donate $300 a year each to
``personally sponsor a child's food and clothing for as long as
U.S. sanctions legislation is in effect or until apartheid is
totally dismantled.''
   The letters also ask for a statement of support by June 21 ``so
that we can brief your constituents on where you stand.''
   Dymally said such tactics constitute political intimidation.
   ``This is designed to intimidate liberals and to solidify the
opposition of the right,'' he said.
</TEXT>
