<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     06-08 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tony Ratings Victim of `Short Circuit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a boffo year for Broadway ticket
sales, but television viewers were apparently unimpressed, giving
the annual Tony Awards show its lowest TV rating yet, according to
the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   NBC put ``Short Circuit,'' a sci-fi comedy movie, opposite
Sunday night's two-hour live Tonys show and racked up a top-10
performance. The Tonys ranked 42nd.
   Last year, the Tonys had a rating of 11.9 and a 23 share, barely
above the 1977 all-time-low of 11.3. But this year's show had only
a 9.5 rating and a 17 share.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's estimated 88.6
million households with televisions. The share is a percentage of
sets in use.
   Other first-run specials also failed to draw big ratings even
though viewers had little original programming to choose from.
   The only other non-repeat in the top 20, except for ``60
Minutes,'' was the National Basketball Association playoff game
between Boston and Detroit on CBS. It tied for 20th. The Los
Angeles-Dallas game tied for 36th.
   CBS also had the American Film Institute salute to Jack Lemmon,
with a 10.5 rating and 19 share. It ranked 31st. ``Liza Minnelli: A
Triple Play'' on ABC ranked 44th with a rating of 9.2 and a 16
share.
   NBC, which had the top seven shows, won the week that ended
Sunday with a 12.9 average rating; CBS rated 9.8; ABC 9.3. The
three-network share was only 59, compared with the season-to-date
average of 70, typical of the summer months. NBC's season-to-date
average rating is 15.7, ABC 13.2, and CBS 13.1.
   In news, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' extended its winning
streak to six weeks. Its average rating last week was 9.2 and
earned a 20 share. The ``CBS Evening News'' remained in second, at
8.5 and 19. ``NBC Nightly News,'' which has trailed since the fall,
had 8.3 and 18.
   The week's top 10 prime-time shows were: ``Night Court,'' ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``Cheers,'' ``A Different World,'' Short Circuit,''
``L.A. Law,'' and Stranded,'' all on NBC, followed by ``Who's the
Boss?'' ABC, ``The High Price of Passion'' NBC and ``Perfect
Strangers Special,'' ABC.
   ``Stranded'' and ``The High Price of Passion'' were repeats of
made-for-TV movies.
   ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd'' are numbered on NBC after
the show dropped into the bottom 10. Rock star David Bowie doesn't
appear to have a future in network television after his first-run
special on ABC was in the bottom five.
   The bottom 10 shows of the week were: ``West 57th,'' ``Perfect
Strangers,'' a Lyndon LaRouche paid political message, ``Ohara,''
``Molly Dodd,'' ``The Incredible Ida Early,'' ``David Bowie's Glass
Spider Tour,'' ``Probe,'' ``The Liberators, Part One,'' ``Dark
Crystal.''
</TEXT>
