<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Defector     06-08 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Defector,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defector Says He Was Ordered To Get Fake U.S. Dollars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean official said today he
defected because he could not fulfill government orders to obtain
counterfeit American dollars for clandestine operations.
   Kim Chong Min, 44, told a news conference he was ordered to
obtain $500,000 in bogus bills for use in foreign operations. Kim
said he never found out what the money was for and was censured
when he tried to ask.
   Kim also said he defected because he failed to meet an order to
raise $2 million in real American currency to finance North Korean
government construction projects.
   South Korean officials said Kim was head of the state-run
Taeyang Trading Co. Kim said previously he served in the Ministry
of Public Security for 19 years and rose to the rank of lieutenant
colonel.
   The ministry is responsible for state security and espionage
operations in the communist north. The two Koreas, divided since
1945, are bitter foes.
   Kim said his company was ordered to raise foreign currency by
buying cobalt and other minerals in Zaire and Nigeria to be resold
for profit in East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Poland.
   Unable to make profits or obtain bogus bills, Kim said he
defected because he feared he would be jailed as punishment for
failing. Kim said he was afraid his family would be punished
because he defected.
   On April 25, when he arrived in an unidentified European nation
from Moscow via Berlin, Kim said he telephoned the local South
Korean Embassy and asked to defect. He arrived in Seoul May 1.
   Kim said the $2 million he was ordered to raise was to be used
to construct a commercial center in preparation for the 13th World
Youth Festival scheduled for September 1989 in Pyongyang, the North
Korean capital.
   He said the north, faced with a drastic shortage of hard
currency, was frantic about earning dollars to help finance various
development projects, particularly to modernize its economy.
   Kim also said the father of a self-confessed North Korean woman
agent involved in the Nov. 29 bombing of a South Korean airliner
was recalled from a diplomatic assignment in Angola.
   The woman, Kim Hyon Hui, who was captured and brought to Seoul
after the plane was lost with all 115 people aboard, confessed in a
news conference that the plane was destroyed to disrupt the Olympic
Games, scheduled to begin in Seoul in September. North Korea is
demanding to co-host the Games.
   Kim said the recall made him think the bombing was the work of
the north, although it has denied any involvement in the incident.
   Kim denied he defected because he had been offered money to do
so. The Seoul government traditionally awards large sums to
defectors from the communist north.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
