<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-EddieHaskell     06-08 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Eddie Haskell,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Grants Police Pension to Former `Leave It To Beaver' Actor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth C. Osmond, who played wiseguy Eddie
Haskell on the ``Leave It to Beaver'' TV series, was granted a
police department disability pension by a state court.
   Superior Court Judge Kurt Lewin on Tuesday ordered the Board of
Pension Commissioners to reverse itself and grant the 46-year-old
Osmond a service-connecteddisability pension retroactive to his
last day of service.
   Osmond played the Beaver's nemesis on the show from 1957 to
1963. He reprised Eddie for a CBS movie in 1983 and for a revival
of the series on the Disney Channel before doing ``The New Leave It
to Beaver,'' which is relayed by Atlanta superstation WTBS to more
than 10,000 cable systems.
   The former motorcycle officer contended that he suffered deep
depression after being shot three times by a suspect he was
pursuing in September 1980. His bulletproof vest stopped two slugs
and a third ricocheted off his belt buckle.
   ``All of the psychiatrists agree that (Osmond's) condition is a
real and disabling psychiatric condition,'' Lewin said in his
ruling. ``Nowhere in the administrative record is it suggested that
(he) has feigned his symptoms.'' The board had ruled Osmond was not
disabled.
   Osmond contended his condition improved when he was released
from duty between September 1981 and March 1982, but that it
worsened when he went back to work. He said he began drinking
excessively to relieve the stress.
   Lewin said he believed that if Osmond returned even to light
duty, he would have another relapse.
   Deputy City Attorney Eudon Ferrell argued the board's finding
was correct. He said Osmond had expressed disenchantment with the
criminal justice system, the police department and law enforcement
in general.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
