<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0410 06-08 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0410,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wraps It Up, Says Real Race Is Starting</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 6 grafs, speech delivered, additional comment;
picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng: Looking ahead</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, who clinched the delegates he
needed to lock in the Democratic presidential nomination Tuesday
night, proclaimed: ``Tomorrow, the race to the finish line begins.''
   Victories in the four final primaries of the season gave the
Massachusetts governor a mathematical lock on more than the 2,081
delegates he needs to ensure his nomination at the party's
convention next month.
   Dukakis won races in California, New Jersey, Montana and New
Mexico.
   ``My friends, California has put us over the top,'' Dukakis told
a late-night victory rally in Los Angeles.
   Dukakis told supporters, though, that ``someone is missing'' _
his wife Kitty, who is in a Boston hospital following spinal surgery
last week. His comment echoed that of his wife earlier in the
evening.
   ``I wish I was somewhere else,'' Mrs. Dukakis said from her
hospital bed.
   Looking ahead to the confrontation with Vice President George
Bush, the certain Republican nominee, Dukakis said he hoped to avoid
a negative campaign.
   ``Every day between now and November, the American people will
want to hear how we intend to build a strong and vibrant future for
our country,'' he said. ``They aren't interested in slashing
attacks.''
   Underscoring the point, he warned the Republicans not to engage
in ``mudslinging and name-calling.''
   ``The American people are not interested in what Mr. Bush thinks
of me or what I think of him,'' he said.
   In his speech, the Democratic nominee-to-be paid tribute to his
most durable Democratic competitor, Jesse Jackson.
   ``I know I speak with pride for every American when I speak about
this race: a son of immigrants from Massachusetts and a black man
who grew up poor in South Carolina are the two finalists for the
Democratic nomination for the presidency of the United States,'' he
said.
   Dukakis, who has been engaged in delicate maneuverings aimed at
keeping Jackson's constituency without agreeing to all of his
rival's demands, said earlier Tuesday that he agreed with Jackson
that it was up to the nominee to choose his running mate.
   Jackson, however, was saying that an offer of the No. 2 spot to
him was ``an option my constituency has earned.''
   ``We may have a floor fight or two'' at the convention next
month, Dukakis said. ``There may be some issues that go to the
floor. I don't see any great divisions within our party. We're going
to have ourselves a great convention.''
   Dukakis and Jackson held a private, 90-minute meeting that broke
up in the early morning hours Tuesday.
   Dukakis said they had not discussed the No. 2 spot on the ticket
_ a position Jackson gave increasing signals that he had an interest
in. Dukakis said the two ``talked in general terms'' about a Jackson
role in a Dukakis administration, but he declined to elaborate.
   Jackson told reporters separately they discussed South Africa,
party rules and convention delegates.
   Dukakis contended he had no differences with Jackson on South
Africa, the issue Jackson has cited as one he may take to the
convention floor in Atlanta. But at the same time Dukakis refused to
meet Jackson's insistence that he agree to label South Africa a
terrorist nation.
   ``I don't see the importance of labels here,'' Dukakis said.
   He repeated his support for a bill applying tougher sanctions
against the racially separated nation, and he blasted ``naked
military aggression by South Africa against its neighbors.''
   ``I don't see any great divisions on this or any other issue,''
Dukakis said.
   Dukakis and Bush met briefly between appearances before the TV
group and discussed what Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said were
``general pleasantries.''
   Dukakis planned to return to Massachusetts early Wednesday. He
planned a stop in St. Louis on the way, where defeated Democratic
presidential rival Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., planned to endorse
his candidacy. Another former candidate, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.,
planned to offer his support in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
