<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Nuclear     06-08 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Nuclear,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Offers Compromise On Nuclear Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has resolved a crisis
in its relationship with NATO by ruling that alliance warships will
be allowed to visit Denmark without revealing if they're carrying
nuclear weapons.
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter said Tuesday that his government
will notify the diplomatic missions of its NATO allies of Denmark's
peacetime ban on nuclear weapons. Visiting vessels, however, will
receive no such notice.
   A dispute over toughening Denmark's longstanding nuclear weapons
ban triggered an unscheduled election May 10 that ended in a
political stalemate and Schlueter returned as prime minister in a
minority coalition last week.
   Before the elections, the socialist opposition pushed a
resolution through the Folketing, or parliament, that obliged the
government to remind visiting warships of Denmark's nuclear policy.
   Although the resolution of April 14 stands, the new center-right
government will send a note to the diplomatic missions of NATO
countries concerned rather than to each naval vessel, Schlueter
said.
   There is no mention of nuclear weapons in the note.
   But the sentence, ``The visit of the vessel is on condition that
it takes place according regulations set down by the Danish
government,'' will be inserted in the Foreign Ministry's standard
notice.
   Since 1976, Denmark has required all foreign warships wishing to
pass through its waters or dock at its ports to seek permission via
diplomatic channels.
   ``It is the government's view that this procedure repects our
allies' policy of neither to confirm nor to deny the presence of
nuclear weapons on board their naval vessels,'' Schlueter said.
   ``The government has been in touch with allied governments which
share this view,'' he added.
   The United States and Britain, two nuclear powers whose warships
make frequent visits in Danish ports, had objected strongly to the
resolution.
   Its implementation by means of a letter to naval captains could
have prevented allied ships from participating in NATO sea
exercises in Danish waters and undermine the alliance's nuclear
deterrence strategy, they said.
   The new cabinet, the third non-socialist administration headed
by Schlueter since 1982, was announced last Friday.
   Svend Auken, leader of the main opposition Social Democratic
party that sponsored the resolution, called the government's move
``a weak signal to the outside world about Denmark's nuclear
policy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fiji     06-08 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Foreign Minister Freed, Mara's Relative Charged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former foreign minister of Fiji was
released from police custody today two days after he was arrested
for allegedly smuggling arms from the Middle East.
   Krishna Datt, a Fiji Indian, was one of about 50 people rounded
up this week following seizures of Soviet-made AK47 rifles, rocket
launchers and grenades believed shipped into the country in April
from North Yemen.
   Datt was Fiji's foreign minister in an Indian-dominated
coalition goverment. A coup led by ethnic Fijians ousted the
coalition government 13 months ago.
   Authorities meanwhile said a brother-in-law of interim Prime
Minister Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara was among 15 people charged with
conspiring to illegally import the weapons.
   Ratu Mosese Tuisawau, 67, half brother of Mara's wife, Adi Lady
Lala Mara, is also the only ethnic Fijian charged in the gun
running case.
   The group was refused bail Tuesday in Lautoka Magistrate's
Court, pending a June 20 court appearance.
   Tuisawau, a senior chief in Fiji's traditional tribal hierachy,
is a known supporter of Timoci Bavadra, whose Indian-dominated
government was overthrown in the May 14, 1987 coup.
   Datt, foreign minister in the Bavadra government, said today
that police interrogations had been difficult.
   ``It is clear they were trying to implicate me (in the gun
running),'' he told reporters.
   Security forces found caches of buried arms on Monday and
Tuesday. The seizures came one week after customs officers in
Australia intercepted a huge arms shipment also bound for Fiji.
   Australian officials said there were enough arms to start a
small war.
   Coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka has claimed the arms shipments were
part of a foreign plot to destabilize the nation. But he has not
specifically accused any country, group or organization.
   Rabuka staged two coups last year, claiming he was protecting
the political rights of ethnic Fijians, who are outnumbered by
Indians in the 715,000 population.
   Rabuka has since handed power to an interim government headed by
Mara while a new constitution is drafted that will guarantee Fijian
dominance in a future parliament.
   He remains head of the army and appointed himself minister for
home affairs in charge of national security.
</TEXT>
