<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NJ--PayneProfile     06-08 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NJ--Payne Profile,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After 14 Years, Grant Gets A Chance To Be State's First Black
Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Councilman Donald Payne has wanted to be
New Jersey's first black congressman for the past 14 years, but
always faced a major obstacle: Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J.
   Rodino, who turned 79 on Tuesday, was first elected in 1948 to
represent the 10th District and was re-elected to 20 consecutive
terms, even after the district got a black majority in 1972.
   This year, Rodino announced his retirement, under increasing
pressure to let the district be represented by the state's first
black congressman.
   That gave Payne, 53, his first serious chance at Congress since
1974, when he declared his candidacy for a proposed new district
that never was created.
   ``I feel like I have earned the right to represent this district.
I have earned the right to succeed Peter Rodino,'' said Payne, vice
president of a computer forms company.
   Tuesday night, Payne handily defeated his Democratic opponent,
fellow councilman Ralph T. Grant, Jr. to win the nomination, which
is tantamount to a general election in the heavily Democratic
district.
   ``It gives our delegation the fairness its been lacking for many
years. I can speak from a true urban perspective,'' Payne said.
   Payne, softspoken, often shy in crowds and uncomfortable in front
of the camera, began his public service career working with the
YMCA. He became the national organization's first black president in
1970.
   In 1972, he was elected to the Essex County Board of Chosen
Freeolders _ roughy equivalent to a county commissioner, and served
for six years.
   Payne announced in 1974 that he would be a candidate for Congress
should a redistricting open up a new district. The plan fell through
in the Legislature and Payne turned to Newark city politics.
   In the 1986 primary, Payne contended that it was time a minority
candidate represented the largely inner-city district. Payne's
campaign was boosted by a number of personal appearances by Jesse
Jackson.
   Rodino captured about 60 percent of the vote, but felt enough
pressure to during the primary to hint that his 20th term would be
his last.
</TEXT>
