<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CalPrimary 3rdLd-Writethru a0478 06-08 1005</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cal Primary, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0478,1026</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with AIDS measure defeated, Dukakis
winning, O'Conner elected, new vote totals. Picks up 17th graf, `The
AIDS...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>McCarthy to Face Wilson in Senate Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy trounced three political
unknowns in the Democratic Senate primary Tuesday to win the right
to face Republican Sen. Pete Wilson, whose seat has ``jinxed''
incumbents for 30 years.
   California voters also rejected a proposition that potentially
could have quarantined AIDS victims, and early returns Tuesday
showed voters opposing the relaxation of government spending limits
and favoring a $1 billion transportation bond.
   With 4,267 of 23,606 precincts reporting, 18 percent of the
total, McCarthy had 433,135 votes or 83 percent against his
little-known opponents. John Hancock Abbott of Santa Clara gathered
38,651 votes or 7 percent, Robert Banuelos of Orange had 25,084
votes or 5 percent and Charles Greene of Los Angeles had 25,272
votes or 5 percent.
   In the presidential primaries, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
swept to an easy victory over Jesse Jackson, netting the fraction of
the state's Democratic delegates needed to clinch his party's
nomination, while Vice President George Bush won the state's
Republican primary, where 175 delegates were being awarded.
   San Diego Mayor Maureen O'Connor won election to a full four-year
term by gaining a majority of the vote in a nonpartisan primary in
the nation's seventh-largest city.
   With 8 percent of precincts reporting, she had 15,145 votes or
57.3 percent and her nearest rival, former City Councilman Floyd
Morrow, had 9,242 votes or 35 percent.
   Among ballot measures, with about 21 percent of precincts
reporting, voters were opposing Proposition 71 by 53 percent to 47
percent. The measure would ease the spending limits Californians
placed on their state government in a 1979 voter initiative,
permitting an estimated $700 million annual increase in state
spending and reducing by an equal amount the funds likely to be
earmarked for future tax rebates.
   Proposition 72, which would also change the spending limit but
with almost exactly the opposite effect, was trailing 61 percent to
39 percent in early returns. It would reduce the limit for most
state programs by an estimated $725 million annually by earmarking
those funds exclusively for highways.
   With 21 percent of the vote counted, the tally against a proposal
backed by extremist Lyndon LaRouche to declare AIDS a communicable
disease, subjecting victims to potential quarantine, was soundly
rejected by 747,702 votes or 67 percent to 369,934 percent or 33
percent.
   Meanwhile, a $1 billion bond measure sponsored by Gov. George
Deukmejian to fund highway construction and improvement, part of a
record-breaking $3.2 billion in bonds, was being narrowly favored 51
percent to 49 percent.
   In Sacramento County, with 20 percent of the total tallied, a
measure seeking closure of the Rancho Seco nuclear power plant
trailed by 29,238 votes or 49 percent to 31,087 votes or 52 percent.
It could mark the first time in history that voters directly ordered
closure of a nuclear plant.
   A proposal to carve out a new Mojave County from the eastern,
desert portions of San Bernardino County, the nation's largest, was
trailing by nearly 2-1 in returns from absentee voters. Other issues
included competing proposals to limit campaign spending.
   Voters in seven Southern California communities were being asked
to adopt initiatives designed to slow growth or make developers pay
for it. In northern and western Los Angeles County, Supervisor Mike
Antonovich was challenged by candidates who said he has allowed
developers to make their lives miserable.
   Antonovich got just 50.4 percent of the absentee vote in a field
of 10 candidates. If he fails to win more than 50 percent of the
vote in the non-partisan contest, he would be forced into a fall
runoff with the other top vote-getter.
   The one congressional incumbent with a serious primary challenge
was freshman Republican Ernest Konnyu, an outspoken conservative
from the San Jose suburb of Saratoga. With 52 percent of the vote
counted, he was trailing Stanford University Professor Tom Campbell,
a moderate, by 2,188 votes to 2,820.
   Campbell was supported by Konnyu's two Republican predecessors,
former Reps. Pete McCloskey and Ed Zschau.
   In two heavily Republican Los Angeles-area congressional
districts, two former White House aides were leading in races for
GOP nominations to replace retiring incumbents. Both of their
campaigns had featured appearences by indicted former White House
national security aide Oliver North.
   With some absentee ballots counted, Christopher Cox of Santa Ana
was building a substantal lead, collecting 2,278 votes to 1,419 for
his closest competition, David Baker, in the 13-candidate 40th
District primary.
   The other former aide, Dana Rohrabacker of Los Angeles, was
leading eight Republicans with 1,829 votes to 1,505 for Harriet
Wieder.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS proposition was opposed by the California Medical
Association and the leadership of both major parties. It was almost
identical to a measure sponsored by LaRouche's organization which
was defeated by a 2-1 margin by Californians in 1986.
   The two spending limit propositions were both indirectly linked
to the Proposition 13 tax cut initiative approved by voters 10 years
ago, as each sought to amend the spending limits imposed in a
followup initiative to 13.
   Twenty-six local tax measures were also linked to Proposition 13,
which required voter approval for any tax increase above the
ceilings it set in 1978. Eleven counties were asking voters to
approve sales tax hikes for libraries, highways, jails or other
local programs, and 15 other jurisdictions sought additional
property or hotel taxes.
   In the Senate primary, both Wilson and McCarthy concentrated on
fund-raising and laying the groundwork for their November faceoff.
   Wilson's success at avoiding even token opposition was evidence
of how succcessfully the moderate former San Diego mayor has
neutralized his once-vocal critics from the conservative wing of the
GOP.
   Wilson has led McCarthy in fund-raising and the polls, but has to
contend with a political jinx _ no one has been re-elected to his
Senate seat in more than 30 years.

</TEXT>
