<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0436 06-08 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0436,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Congratulates Dukakis For Clinching Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 4 grafs to insert prepared remarks to supporters,
pick up 4th graf pvs, ``Michael Dukakis''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson congratulated Michael Dukakis
Tuesday night for clinching the Democratic presidential nomination
on the last night of their four-month primary duel, and repeated his
contention that he deserves ``serious consideration'' to be Dukakis'
running mate.
   ``I believe we have shown it is possible to compete without
conflict, differ without division,'' Jackson said in remarks
prepared for delivery to supporters gathered at a Los Angeles hotel.
He said he had built a ``mighty coalition'' and ``we have made
America better.
   Jackson pledged to go to the Democratic National Convention as
``the new Democratic majority _ to set the agenda for our nation and
our party.''
   Earlier, in an interview on ABC, he said: ``We'll have to work
together.''
   ``Michael Dukakis is due very special congratulations,'' Jackson
said in the interview, just after the Massachusetts governor scored
victories in the final races in California, New Jersey, Montana and
New Mexico.
   But Jackson noted that ``in a technical sense, the race is not
over'' until the Democratic National Convention next month. Dukakis
has now earned enough delegates to be assured of a first-ballot
victory there.
   Earlier Tuesday, as voters were going to the polls, Jackson
pledged to keep campaigning for delegates until the Democratic
National Convention.
   Dukakis claimed enough delegates to sew up the presidential
nomination in the final primaries on Tuesday. But Jackson told
reporters he had no intention of throwing in the towel, arguing that
many delegates will still be uncommitted until the convention in
mid-July.
   He said at one point that his supporters deserve the option of
having him on the ticket, a contention that seemed to go beyond his
previous statements that he merely deserves consideration for the
vice presidential spot if he doesn't win the presidential nomination.
   But under questioning later, he declined to pursue that, saying
it would be up to the convention to determine the nominee and his
running mate.
   The presidential nominee, he said, ``recommends'' to the
convention, which then selects his running mate.
   ``Suffice it to say, we're going to keep our campaign alive to
July, at the convention,'' he said. ``(Ted) Kennedy did it in 1980,
(Gary) Hart did it in 1984, I will do it in 1988.''
   He said he will be contacting at-large delegates and ``super
delegates,'' trying to persuade them to support him instead of
Dukakis.
   ``The commitments made by at-large and super delegates are
non-binding until convention time, and so it's appropriate to make
appeals to delegates based upon friendship, based upon constituent
considerations,'' he said.
   Jackson spent election day in California speaking to an ABC
convention and to two rallies in the Los Angeles area.
   He said he and Dukakis did not discuss the vice presidency or any
adminstration role for Jackson in their late-night meeting on Monday.
   He called it a ``good meeting, an effective meeting,'' covering a
wide range of issues including South Africa, the Soviet Union, the
party platform and universal voter registration.
   Jackson, who has repeatedly said Dukakis is too conservative and
cautious, said he will keep the pressure on the front-runner in
future meetings to espouse more progressive positions.
   ``It's all right for him to be conservative because that's the
way he feels; it's his basic approach. But balance would be in the
progressive dirction,'' Jackson said.
   He said he wants to keep ``an open dialogue'' with Dukakis.
   Earlier, in a panel interview before a meeting of ABC affiliates,
Jackson said it would be Dukakis' option whether to offer him a spot
on the ticket, if Dukakis wins the nomination.
   But he then added, ``It is an option my constituency has earned.''
   ``The constituency I represent has earned its place at the top
level of American politics,'' he said.
   In a reflective tone that he has adopted in the last days of the
primary campaign, Jackson also said he has achieved key objectives
of his presidential campaign.
   ``The three objectives of my campaign have in some measure been
addressed _ expand the party, build a viable converging interest
coalition and change national priorities,'' he said.
   ``To that extent we now have a tremendous sense of hope about the
country,'' which he said, ``is changing for the better.''
</TEXT>
