<DOCNO> AP880608-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Journalism     06-08 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Journalism,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Say Government Bungling Probes Of Reporter Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists are complaining that the
government is mishandling its investigations of the killings of
reporters, 25 of whom have been slain in Mexico in the past six
years.
   On Tuesday, a group of journalists boycotted a luncheon to mark
Mexico's ``Freedom of the Press Day.''
   President Miguel de la Madrid presented the National Journalism
Awards and attended the luncheon as his last official activity
before departing for New York, where he is to address the U.N.
General Assembly.
   Fernando Pineda, president of the liberal Union of Democratic
Journalists, said he did not attend the luncheon because ``on this
June 7, there is nothing to celebrate.''
   The union and other journalists' associations in Mexico complain
that the government has bungled investigations into the slayings of
the 25 journalists killed during the past six years.
   Most recently, columnist Hector Felix Miranda of the outspoken
weekly Zeta in the northwestern border city of Tijuana was fatally
shot April 20. Police believe the man arrested May 1 may have been
a triggerman acting for others.
   The Interior Department on Friday issued an unusually detailed
80-page report on the cases.
   The report says de la Madrid had ``put into practice the actions
needed to guarantee free exercise, without any restriction of the
freedom of the press'' throughout his six-year term, starting in
December 1982.
   De la Madrid told journalists on Tuesday that he ordered the
Interior Department to pursue its investigations into cases of
violence against Mexican reporters ``to better protect the life and
patrimony of journalists and the rights of the press.''
   The president's remarks were carried by the government news
agency Notimex.

</TEXT>
