<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-08 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Off in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened in trading against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo Wednesday, and stock prices also fell.
   After opening the day at 125.27 yen, the dollar edged up and
closed at 125.32 yen, 0.45 yen lower than its close Tuesday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 28.92-point loser Tuesday, dropped another 54.67
points, or 0.19 percent, to end the day's trading at 27,912.65.
   ``Profit-taking and a sense among investors that the market was
rising too high eased share prices a little,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama
of Wako Securities.
   But the market, being led mainly by capital-intensive steel
stocks, maintains its bullish trend with a strong buying mood among
all participants, including foreign, corporate and individual
investors, Yoneyama said.
   A foreign exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo
said the dollar early weakness was a carryover from its performance
Tuesday in other currency markets.
   The early activity was said to be confined mostly to the Japanese
trading houses, dealers said.
</TEXT>
