<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Cronkite     06-08 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Cronkite,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Rejects Cronkite's Proposal for Kennedy Special</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS has rejected Walter Cronkite's proposal to
anchor a prime-time special report this fall on the 25th
anniversary of the assassination of President John F. Kennedy.
   The project was Cronkite's first proposal in an effort to find a
more meaningful role at CBS, The New York Times reported today,
quoting people associated with the project.
   CBS is negotiating to keep Cronkite from leaving the network.
   ``I thought it was a pretty good idea and I still think it is a
good idea,'' Cronkite said. ``I hope that others can get it on
somewhere else.''
   Cronkite, who is leaving for a monthlong trip overseas, said his
representative, Ron Konecky, will continue to negotiate with CBS on
his behalf.
   Gene Jankowski, president of the CBS Broadcast Group, declined
to comment.
   When Cronkite left as anchor of the ``CBS Evening News'' in 1981
after 14 years as the top-rated network newscaster, he was made a
special correspondent with an annual salary of about $1 million.
   Two former CBS News presidents, Van Gordon Sauter and Edward M.
Joyce, acknowledged that Cronkite was shut out from the ``CBS
Evening News'' to ensure that his successor, Dan Rather, would not
be uncomfortable, the Times said.
   Cronkite, a member of the CBS board, has occasionally criticized
Rather's broadcast style as being too soft.
   Cronkite has recently said he may leave the network when the
first phase of his contract expires on Nov. 4, his 72nd birthday.
That phase binds him exclusively to CBS.
   According to the contract, Cronkite will be paid $150,000 a year
for the next 10 years as a network consultant. The current
negotiations began this spring after Cronkite told CBS that he did
not consider that agreement to be exclusive and that he intended to
consider other offers.
   Cronkite's performance as chief anchor during the four-day
nonstop coverage of the Nov. 22, 1963, Kennedy assassination is
regarded as the foundation of his near-mythical status as a
broadcaster. Public opinion polls found that he was ``the most
trusted man in America.''
</TEXT>
