<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConstructionFire     06-08 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Construction Fire,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$6 Million Fire At Apartment Complex Under Construction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire razed an apartment complex under
construction and jumped to neighboring buildings, sending up smoke
that could be seen 60 miles away and causing $6 million in damage,
authorities said.
   The 204-unit apartment, at the wood-framing stage of
construction, burned to the ground in less than hour after it broke
out at 5:45 p.m. Tuesday, said fire department spokeswoman Sharon
Frank.
   ``This is what you call a cooker,'' Ms. Frank said. ``It's a
construction fire so you've got piles of lumber everywhere, all
kinds of flammable materials.''
   Flames jumped to a neighboring Victorian house and several
business storefronts, Ms. Frank added. The house sustained severe
damage before firefighters contained the fast-moving blaze at about
8 p.m., she said.
   The house was occupied, but nobody was inside when it ignited,
Ms. Frank said.
   Flames also leaped to the roof of a nearby two-story building
owned by the Salvation Army, she said.
   A huge pillar of smoke rose over Orange County and could be seen
as far away as Malibu, 60 miles away.
   One firefighter was treated for heat exhaustion and released.
   No other injuries were reported in the blaze, which caused an
estimated $6 million damage, Ms. Frank said.
   Investigators were waiting for the charred rubble to cool before
searching for clues to the cause of the fire, Ms. Frank said.
</TEXT>
