<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-08 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Ordered to Grant Visas to Four Barred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered the government to
grant visas to Nicaragua's interior minister and three others
barred from entering the country because of their membership in
communist or communist-affiliated groups.
   U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene reversed an earlier finding
that had been set aside by a federal appeals court, ruling on
Tuesday that Nicaraguan Interior Minister Tomas Borge, two Cuban
officials and a former Italian senator should be admitted to accept
speaking engagements at the invitation of U.S. citizens.
   Greene said the State Department had violated the 1952
Immigration and Nationality Act by denying the four visas simply
because the applicants were members of communist or
communist-affiliated organizations.
   The American Civil Liberties Union argued that to bar someone,
the law requires the State Department to determine that an alien's
proposed activities during the visit _ as opposed to political
affiliations _ would endanger U.S. interests.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amtrak Chairman Confident Railroad Will Survive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak Chairman W. Graham Claytor says he
expects to expand the rail system's capacity under the next
president, Democrat or Republican, after weathering years of
attacks by the Reagan administration on federal subsidies.
   ``Congress has rejected ... proposals to terminate Amtrak for
four successive years,'' W. Graham Claytor told reporters on
Tuesday.
   He said he hopes both the Democratic and Republican parties will
go on record in favor of federal support for the national passenger
rail system. ``I'm optimistic this will be the position of a new
administration, whether Republican or Democratic,'' he said.
   Claytor said that after fighting for survival, Amtrak's main
goal now is expanding services.
   ``The principal problem we see ahead is capacity. ... On
weekends and holidays we don't have the equipment to accommodate
peak loads on our unreserved Northeast Corridor trains'' between
Boston and Washington, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs No-New-Starts Water Projects Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee has followed the House
in approving a spending bill for energy and water development that
includes no money to begin construction of water projects next year.
   Chairman Bennett Johnston, D-La., said the Appropriations energy
and water development subcommittee rejected requests on Tuesday for
nearly three dozen new dams, irrigation systems and harbor
improvements.
   ``If we make any exceptions, the dam is broken and the flood
starts,'' said Johnston.
   The appropriations legislation for fiscal 1989, which begins
Oct. 1, contains $18.05 billion but nothing for new starts by the
Army Corps of Engineers or the Interior Department's Bureau of
Reclamation.
   The House last month approved a $17.8 billion version of the
bill that also included plans for no new construction starts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jail Suicides Nine Times Higher Than Rate for General Populace,</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Study Shows
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suicide is the leading cause of death in
the nation's jails, where the suicide rate for inmates is nine
times that of the general population, according to a new study.
   The federally financed study also said that more than half the
inmates who commit suicide kill themselves in the first day after
they are arrested and many are in jail because of alcohol or drug
problems.
   ``Although the average length of stay in jail is approximately 6
to 11 days, 51 percent of all jail suicide victims were dead within
the first 24 hours of incarceration and 29 percent committed
suicide within the first three hours,'' the National Center on
Institutions and Alternatives said.
   Lindsay M. Hayes directed the project, which was supported
through a grant from the National Institute of Corrections in the
Department of Justice. Hayes said the suicide rate in detention
facilities was found to be 107 per 100,000 inmates. Census Bureau
studies show the rate is 12.5 per 100,000 in the general
population, he said.
</TEXT>
