<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cholesterol     06-08 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cholesterol,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cholesterol Screening Gets People To Doctor, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half those who were informed in
community screening programs that their cholesterol levels were
high contacted a doctor within two months, an encouraging sign for
such programs, a study says.
   That showed ``very good followup for the amount of time that had
passed,'' said Reagan Bradford, director of the Oklahoma Lipid
Research Clinic in Oklahoma City.
   Bradford spoke Tuesday at a symposium on cholesterol sponsored
by the American Medical Association.
   His results came from about 13,000 people who went through
pin-prick blood tests for cholesterol at shopping malls, schools
and other public places.
   About 70 percent of those who had seen a doctor received
confirmation that their levels were high, and had started a diet
prescribed by the physician, Bradford said.
   Other studies suggest that perhaps 40 percent of those who go
through such screening will be told to see a doctor, he said.
   Also at the symposium, George Gallup Jr. said a new poll found
that 31 percent of adolescents said they were greatly concerned
about heart disease or a heart attack. But their eating habits were
about the same as those who did not express such concern, the
pollster said.
   Apparently they believe other things are more important in life
than controlling cholesterol intake, he said. And adolescents
appear to have only limited knowledge about how to avoid
cholesterol in the diet, he said.
   His organization polled 375 adolescents, ages 12 to 17, from
March 28 to April 10. Findings should be accurate within 5
percentage points, the organization said.
   Among its findings about the youths:
   _ Seventy percent knew that diet can reduce blood cholesterol
levels. Ninety-three percent said it was ``very'' or ``fairly''
important for young people to control their cholesterol intake.
   _ About 90 percent correctly identified fried foods and butter
as contributing to high cholesterol levels. Only 31 percent
correctly put ice cream in that category.
   _ Some 24 percent said they avoid fried foods. Of those who said
they avoid some foods because of cholesterol, about half cited
fried foods, and 30 percent named butter.
   _ Twenty-three percent overall said they eat eggs, which contain
cholesterol, for breakfast three or more times a week.
   _ Fifty-nine percent said they eat a good deal of beef.
   The poll was commissioned by the pharmaceutical company Merck
Sharpe and Dohme.
</TEXT>
