<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TimesHeraldSale     06-08 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Times Herald Sale,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Announce Sale of Dallas Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second sale in as many years at the Dallas
Times Herald won't spell any drastic changes for the newspaper as
it battles in one of the country's most competitive markets, the
new editor says.
   ``I think it's been a quality paper for the last couple of
years,'' Roy Bode said Tuesday. ``I'm sure there are things we can
do to improve it, but I have no plans for major changes.''
   MediaNews Holdings Inc., controlled by Times Herald Chairman
William Dean Singleton, is selling the paper to DTH Media Inc., a
new corporation controlled by MediaNews stockholder John Buzzetta,
a longtime business partner of Singleton.
   Rumors had been circulating for weeks about the pending sale of
the Times Herald, which has had marginal profits in the face of a
weak state economy and is locked in battle with the larger Dallas
Morning News.
   Buzzetta, 38, will become publisher of the Times Herald,
replacing Art Wible. Bode, a former associate editor of the paper,
is replacing C. David Burgin.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but in a story today the
Times Herald quoted sources as saying Buzzetta and two partners in
the venture _ Equitable Capital Management and Dillon, Read & Co. _
paid $110 million to $120 million to acquire the newspaper.
   Buzzetta said in a statement, ``A substantial amount of cash and
stock was involved in the transaction.''
   Singleton and a partner, Richard B. Scudder, acquired the Times
Herald, the second-largest paper in Dallas, in late 1986 for $110
million from Times Mirror Co. of Los Angeles. As part of the deal,
they received $7 million that the newspaper had in the bank, as
well as a $20 million discount for paying early, bringing their
total cost to $83 million.
   Buzzetta said DTH Media Inc. will have a controlling interest
while MediaNews will retain a financial interest in the newspaper
and will remain a stockholder.
   Burgin, general manager Robert Hollingsworth and senior vice
president and chief financial officer Richard L. Jacobs will join
MediaNews Group.
   Singleton, 37, who was in Denver on Tuesday in meetings at The
Denver Post, which he also owns, said in a statement that proceeds
from the transaction will go toward retiring debt and for new
acquisitions.
   ``The proposal was attractive enough financially that it had to
be considered seriously,'' he said.
   Bode, 39, worked at the Times Herald from 1977 to 1986 before
leaving to become editor and vice president of The North Jersey
Herald & News, which is part of Singleton's privately held
MediaNews Group. He recently left that post.
   No layoffs are expected in the Times Herald newsroom, Bode and
Buzzetta said.
   ``This will be a stable ownership and we agree too many changes
aren't good for a paper and this paper shouldn't be seeing too many
more,'' Bode said. ``We're here to stay.''
   Two weeks ago, the Morning News and the Times Herald agreed to
drop lawsuits filed against each other concerning paid circulation
figures.
   The latest figures released through the Audit Bureau of
Circulation for the six months ended Sept. 30, 1986, showed the
Times Herald's daily circulation was 246,370 and the Morning News'
was 390,987. On Sunday, the Times Herald's reported paid
circulation was 338,963, and the Morning News reported 531,417.
   Last year, the Times Herald had an operating profit of about $9
million on total revenue of about $120 million, sources told the
newspaper, but earnings and sales have slumped in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
