<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NJPrimary     06-08 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NJ Primary,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NJ Voters Choose Lautenberg, Payne In Primary Races</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-term Sen. Frank Lautenberg looked
forward to a costly re-election bid after his overwhelming
Democratic primary victory, and a congressional primary assured New
Jersey of its first black congressman.
   ``We are spending more on this race than we ever have before,''
Lautenberg, 64, said after an overwhelming victory Tuesday. ``The
race is one that people are looking at, but I don't know what it
will cost.''
   Donald Payne, a Democratic Newark city councilman, won the
heavily Democratic 10th District primary, virtually assuring him of
becoming the state's first black member in Congress.
   In the Democratic presidential primary, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis won most of the state's 109 convention delegates;
Vice President George Bush was unopposed for 64 delegates.
   Lautenberg, seen by Republicans as one of the Senate's most
vulnerable Democrats, will face retired Army Gen. Peter Dawkins,
who ran unopposed for the GOP's nomination, and has popular Gov.
Thomas H. Kean as his campaign chairman.
   The two candidates expect to spend a combined total of $14
million.
   With 5,794 of 5,825 precincts, or 99 percent, reporting,
Lautenberg had 319,395 votes, or 77.6 percent; Elnardo Webster, a
state Corrections official, had 50,801 votes, or 12.3 percent; and
theology student Harold Young, a self-styled ``conservative radical
Democrat,'' had 41,157 votes, or 10 percent.
   Lautenberg founded and built Automatic Data Processing Corp.
into a worldwide company. He spent more than $3 million of his own
money in 1982 _ then thought an incredible amount _ to beat
pipe-smoking Rep. Millicent Fenwick.
   He and Dawkins went on the offensive after Tuesday's primary
votes were counted.
   ``There will be a very clear and distinct difference between
myself and Frank Lautenberg,'' said Dawkins, 50, a Heisman trophy
winner, war hero and Rhodes scholar who has never held public
office.
   Dawkins has proposed a 10-point plan against drug abuse and says
he will campaign on themes that include the environment, education
and the federal budget deficit.
   Rodino said during the 1986 campaign that he would retire when
President Reagan left office in January 1989. Minority officials in
the district, including Payne, held Rodino to that promise.
   ``It's been a trip that we've been waging for many years,''
Payne told cheering supporters after defeating a fellow Newark
councilman, Ralph T. Grant, who also is black. ``We have ended one
step of this trip,''
   ``There are really no more impossible dreams,'' Payne said.
   With 98 percent of 328 precincts reporting, Payne had 39,681
votes, or 73 percent, to 14,576 votes, or 27 percent, for Grant.
   The candidates have focused on the same platform: fight drugs,
house the homeless, help the elderly and bring in jobs.
   Third District voters chose former state Assemblyman Joseph
Azzolina from five Republicans to vie against Democratic state Sen.
Frank J. Pallone Jr. for the seat left vacant by the March 25 death
of Democratic Rep. James Howard.
   Voters also chose Azzolina to meet Pallone in a special November
contest to fill the two months that will remain in Howard's term.
With 100 percent of the precincts reporting, Azzolina had 68
percent of the vote in the five-way race.
   Pallone was unopposed in both primaries.
   In addition to the 3rd and 10th districts, 12 incumbents in the
House will seek re-election in November. Only two faced primary
opposition and won handily.
</TEXT>
