<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TelescopeMirror     06-08 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Telescope Mirror,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Telescope Mirror Wows Astronomers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11{-foot-wide honeycombed piece of glass
got rave reviews from engineers and an astronomer who hope a new
casting process will produce the next generation of cheaper, more
powerful telescopes.
   ``It is perfect,'' engineer Edward Mannery said Tuesday after
the lid was taken off a special furnace and he examined the glass
blank, which will be ground and polished into a telescope mirror.
   ``It couldn't be better at this point,'' said astronomer Roger
Angel, who heads the Steward Observatory Mirror Laboratory at the
University of Arizona and devised the new process.
   The blank was spun-cast six weeks ago using centrifugal force,
then gradually cooled until the furnace was shut off last weekend.
At 3.5 meters (about 11{ feet) wide, it is the largest made with
the new method.
   The finished mirror will go into a telescope being built in the
Sacramento Mountains near Sun Spot, N.M., by the Astrophysical
Research Consortium.
   Consortium members are the University of Chicago, the University
of Washington, Princeton University, New Mexico State University
and Washington State University.
   Mannery, a University of Washington engineer representing the
consortium, measured the thickness of the blank's surface with an
electronic device as others inspected the glass for bubbles or
other flaws.
   ``If nothing went wrong, we expected the face plate thickness to
be 1.75 inches,'' Mannery said. ``It's just the thickness it was
supposed to be.''
   He said the glass also appears to have an exceptionally low
number of the bubbles that form during casting.
   ``In the next two or three weeks, we'll gradually unmold this
glass, and I would say probably in about three weeks we'll have
gotten right deep into it and I think we'll know really what we've
got there,'' Angel said.
   The blank's surface, which will be ground and polished by a
Tucson optical company, is nearly half an inch over the thickness
needed.
   In about a week, a special crane called a Whiffletree will lift
the blank from the furnace, and about 4,000 pounds of molding
material used to create the hollow honeycomb support structure will
be removed, Angel said.
   ``The mirror is very fragile at this point,'' he said,
explaining that small cracks caused by the mold have the potential
for becoming a big crack.
   Many astronomers hope the process can be used to build strong,
lightweight mirrors that are more powerful because they have more
deeply curved surfaces.
   This translates to great savings in time and money because the
new telescopes can be housed in smaller buildings, Angel and other
proponents say.
   Angel said another 3.5-meter mirror will be cast for another
consortium later this year.
   Other commitments include two mirrors 26 feet wide for a
binocular-like telescope called the Columbus Project. That project
involves Arizona and Chicago universities, Ohio State University
and Italian astronomers.
</TEXT>
