<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PresserTrial     06-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser Trial,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors: Cancer-Stricken Teamsters President May Die In Six Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President Jackie Presser may never go
on trial on federal racketeering and embezzlement charges, say
doctors who predict he will die of brain cancer within six months.
   U.S. District Judge George White on Tuesday postponed Presser's
trial indefinitely after reviewing letters from four doctors and
talking to a surgeon at the Phoenix, Ariz., hospital where Presser
is hospitalized.
   White ruled that two co-defendants will stand trial July 12.
   Presser, 61, has been receiving radiation treatment at the
Barrow Neurological Institute following removal of a cancerous
lesion from his brain May 17.
   Dr. Robert Spetzler, director of the hospital, told White by
telephone that Presser showed some improvement Monday.
   ``I don't believe Presser will ever be free of this disease,''
said Spetzler.
   He said Presser is being treated with radiation for another
brain lesion and may have two others. Spetzler said the cancer
started in a lung, spread to the brain and could develop elsewhere.
   Dr. Leslie Sheeler of the Cleveland Clinic wrote on May 26 that
the prognosis for the type of cancer Presser has ``is in general
very poor. The expected survival is something like six months.
   ``Mr. Presser is quite impaired mentally,'' Sheeler wrote. ``He
has virtually no short-term memory.''
   Spetzler, responding to questions from Lynch, confirmed
Sheeler's diagnosis. He said, however, that if Presser continues
his slow improvement, a review in four to six months may show him
competent to stand trial.
   White called Spetzler at the request of prosecutor William Lynch.
   Presser, Anthony Hughes and Harold Friedman are accused of
participating in a $700,000 payroll padding scheme at Teamsters
Local 507 in Cleveland, where Presser is secretary-treasurer.
   Presser last month relinquished his presidential post for four
months because of his health problems. National Secretary-Treasurer
Weldon Mathis is serving as president.
   Friedman is Local 507's president and an international vice
president. Hughes is the local's secretary.
   Presser's attorney, John Climaco, said Presser wanted the trial
to continue and wants to testify.
   Climaco said Presser is innocent and was an FBI informant who
was authorized to hire ``ghost employees,'' people on the payroll
who performed no work.
</TEXT>
