<1ST_LINE>u p PM-NMPrimary     06-08 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NM Primary,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valentine Wins GOP Primary Race for U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican state senator and former
Albuquerque dentist says he will use Sen. Jeff Bingaman's record to
thwart the Democrat's run for a second term in the U.S. Senate.
   ``Throughout this campaign, we'll talk about Jeff Bingaman's
record,'' said Bill Valentine after topping a four-man GOP field in
Tuesday's primary election.
   ``How he fell in line with the East Coast liberals ... how he's
been canceling out (New Mexico Republican Sen.) Pete Domenici's
vote over 500 times since he's been there,'' Bingaman said.
   Vice President George Bush won his party's presidential primary
and picked up all 26 GOP convention delegates. Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis beat Jesse Jackson in Democratic voting and claimed
16 of 24 delegates.
   With 97 percent, or 1,270 of 1,307 precincts reporting,
Valentine had 33,672 votes, or 42.9 percent, while former U.S.
Interior Department official Rick Montoya had 22,37314 votes, or
28.5 percent.
   GOP activist Corky Morris had 15,716 votes, or 20 percent, and
state Sen. Joe Carraro had 6,668 votes, or 8.5 percent.
   The 1st Congressional District races were still undecided early
today as vote returns trickled in from Bernalillo County, the
state's most populous county.
   Albuquerque insurance executive Edward Lujan, bidding to succeed
his brother Manuel who is retiring after 20 years in Congress, led
the three-man Republican race by about 800 votes with 54 percent of
precincts reporting.
   Former state District Judge Patricia Madrid of Albuquerque and
former Assistant U.S. Attorney Tom Udall were locked in a tight
battle at the head of the eight-person field in the 1st District's
Democratic primary.
   Bingaman is ``for big labor, big government and big spending on
the part of Washington,'' said Valentine, 43.
   Bingaman, 44, said he knew little about Valentine and would run
a positive, issue-oriented campaign.
   ``We've done it before in New Mexico and we'll do that again
this year,'' said Bingaman, who beat incumbent GOP Sen. Harrison
``Jack'' Schmitt six years ago and was unopposed this year.
   Bingaman said he believed there would be three main issues in
the general election campaign _ the economy, education and
disadvantaged children.
   Montoya, 41, left the Reagan administration as assistant
secretary of interior for terriorities and international affairs to
return to New Mexico and seek elective office for the first time.
   Morris, 52, owns trucking and warehousing companies in
Albuquerque, and Carraro, 43, owns and operates two Italian
restaurants in Albuquerque.
</TEXT>
