<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms Over Much Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in California mountains and widely scattered showers
dampened the mid-Atlantic Coast and the Southeast early today after
thunderstorms produced large hail and damaging winds in many areas.
   A heat wave in the Northern Plains was expected to continue.
   Gusts up to 75 mph ripped through Delaware on Tuesday, downing
trees, forcing the evacuation of more than 500 people from a
subdivision and causing power outages, authorities said. At least
31 people were treated for mostly minor storm-related injuries,
Kent General Hospital in Dover reported.
   The heaviest damage appeared to be just north of Dover, where
residents reported a tornado. However, the weather service said the
report could not be confirmed immediately.
   The thunderstorms Tuesday also struck Florida, Alabama,
Maryland, Pennsylvania and Montana. The storms weakened during the
evening, and by early today lingered primarily over southern
Florida and central Iowa.
   Heavier rainfall for the six hours that ended at 2 a.m. EDT
included an inch at West Palm Beach, Fla., three-quarters of an
inch at Miami and two-thirds of an inch at Orlando, Fla.
   Snow fell in higher elevations of Northern California early
today. On Tuesday, at least 10 hikers were reported missing
temporarily and some mountain highways were closed or restricted as
snow drifted up to 2{ feet high. Hail up to a half-inch in diameter
fell on Fresno.
   Elsewhere, many cities hit record highs for the date as a heat
wave continued in much of the nation.
   Baltimore reached 94 degrees, topping the 93-degree mark set in
1980; Bismarck, N.D., reached 101, beating the 95-degree record of
1977; Cape Hatteras, N.C., hit 90, a degree more than the 1975
record; Galveston, Texas, reached 91, beating the 89-degree mark of
1880; and Goodland, Kansas, topped out at 97, a degree more than
the 1963 record.
   The nation's high was 110 degrees at Glendive, Mont.
   For today, rainshowers were forecast for northern Maine, and
from central Montana across the northern third of the Pacific
Coast; and showers and thunderstorms in Florida. Sunny skies were
forecast for much of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 50s and 60s from the
Great Lakes across New England; in the 60s from the northern half
of the Pacific Coast across Idaho and northern Nevada; the 90s over
eastern Montana, from the Carolinas across Florida, the Gulf of
Mexico states, the Tennessee Valley, the lower half of the
Mississippi Valley, the southern two-thirds of the Plains and the
desert Southwest; and 100 in southwest Texas. Highs elsewhere
generally were expected reach the 70s and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33 at
Meacham, Ore., to 82 at Minot, N.D.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 partly cloudy; Boston 57 fair; Buffalo 51
fair; Charleston, S.C., 75 fair; Cincinnati 65 fair; Cleveland 61
fair; Detroit 60 fair; Miami 74 rain; New York 63 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 59 cloudy; Pittsburgh 69 partly cloudy; Portland,
Maine, 46 partly cloudy; Washington 70 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 75 fair; Chicago 73 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 fair; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 67 thunderstorms; Indianapolis
68 fair; Kansas City 77 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 72 fair;
Nashville 67 fair; New Orleans 71 foggy; St. Louis 72 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 73 fair; Anchorage 56 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 67 fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 81 fair; Salt Lake City
60 fair; San Diego 58 fair; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 51
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 48 fair.
