<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Politburo     06-08 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Politburo,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Special Politburo Session Calls For Grassroots Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo has called on local Communist
Party committees to submit grassroots proposals to this month's
crucial national party conference, the official Tass news agency
reported today.
   The move apparently aims to sidestep middle-level bureaucrats
who oppose Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ambitious program for economic
and social reform.
   The Soviet leader seeks through reform to limit the power and
privilege of the entrenched bureaucracy.
   The first national Communist Party conference in 47 years, to
begin on June 28, is expected to consolidate political changes
backed by Gorbachev, including limits on terms for party officials.
   The Politburo, in a special Monday meeting, instructed local
party organizations to collect ``incoming proposals from the
grassroots to make sure they will be taken into account when the
conference discusses the issues on its agenda and be reflected in
its decisions,'' Tass said.
   The 13-member ruling body, in a communique carried by Tass, said
most of those suggestions focus on ways of ``continuing to
democratize party and public affairs, and broadening glasnost,''
Gorbachev's term for greater openness on selected topics.
   During the election process for delegates to the 19th Party
Conference, proponents of Gorbachev's reform program charged that
middle-echelon bureaucrats were trying to seat more conservative
party members.
   By ensuring that grassroots proposals make it onto the
conference agenda, the Politburo, which includes Gorbachev and
other top Kremlin leaders, may limit the influence of party
apparatchiks at the session.
   The communique was published two days after the special meeting
of the Politburo, which usually convenes on Thursdays.
   No reason was given for the delay.
   At its Monday session, the Politburo also ``expressed complete
approval for the work done by Mikhail Gorbachev'' during the summit
with President Reagan last week, the statement said.
   Politburo members ``expressed the conviction that the Moscow
talks have augmented possibilites for improving the overall
atmosphere in the Soviet-American relationship and helped foster a
favorable political climate in international relations in general.''
</TEXT>
