<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UMWProtest     06-08 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UMW Protest,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UMW Calls Walkouts In Three States To Protest Rules Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers union ordered one-day walkouts by about
7,000 miners in Alabama, Kentucky and Tennessee to protest proposed
changes in federal safety rules that one official says would
``cause big amounts of blood.''
   ``They're going to have more trouble out of us than they ever
thought of before they get this thing through,'' UMW District 19
President Joe Phipps of Middlesboro, Ky., said Tuesday.
   The union called a one-day ``memorial period'' in each state
this week so union members could attend hearings called by the
federal Mine Safety and Health Administration on the rule changes,
which the UMW says would increase fire hazards in underground mines.
   One of the most controversial changes proposed by agency would
eliminate the requirement that mines be evacuated when ventilation
fans stop operating.
   Another proposal would allow mine operators to let conveyor belt
passageways double as ventilation tunnels. Regulations now require
that the two be separated to reduce the chances of fire.
   Special ventilation processes are needed in underground mines to
disperse methane, an explosive gas found in coal seams that
accumulates as the coal is mined.
   ``It's like wearing a plastic bag over your head and carrying a
stick of dynamite in your back pocket with a 3-foot fuse on it,''
said miner Morgan Bayless of Tackett Creek, Tenn. ``That's the
position we're in.''
   ``If this goes into effect, it's going to cause big amounts of
blood,'' Phipps said.
   Kentucky and Tennessee miners observed their memorial period
Tuesday, when the agency held its hearing in Lexington, Ky. The
memorial period for Alabama miners is scheduled for Thursday, when
the agency will hold a hearing in Birmingham.
   ``(Union) members are justifiably worried about the proposed
changes since the agency has failed to address needed improvement
in federal mine safety standards,'' UMW President Richard Trumka
said Tuesday.
   Trumka also indicated that the union will consider calling
additional memorial periods on a case-by-case basis to coincide
with hearings in Indiana, Colorado and West Virginia later this
month.
   The agency says the revisions, developed by the safety
committees of three coal industry organizations representing the
operators, would update, clarify and simplify its ventilation
standards.
   But Joe Main, the UMW's safety director, said the proposed rule
changes ``save the mine operators over $7 million annually at the
loss of safety protection for miners.''
</TEXT>
