<2ND_LINE>PM-Montana Primary,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Cites Good Old Days; Stephens Calls It Yesteryear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KRONHOLM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former two-term Gov. Thomas Judge beat five
Democratic rivals to win his party's nomination for governor, and
Democratic Sen. John Melcher's bid for a third term is opposed by
Gordon Burns, a Republican county commissioner.
   ``People remember we had eight good years,'' Judge said after
Tuesday's victory. ``While they remember the past, they also wanted
to know our plans for the future. ... We put forth a program that
the people of this state have been waiting for.''
   In the presidential primary contest, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis easily beat Jesse Jackson for 19 Democratic delegates while
Vice President George Bush walked away in the Republican contest.
   Judge will face Republican Stan Stephens in November in his run
for the office he held eight years until his ouster by his own
lieutenant governor in the 1980 Democratic primary. Two-term Gov.
Ted Schwinden is retiring.
   Melcher quashed a token challenge from Billings lawyer Robert
Kelleher; Burns, a county commissioner from Billings, beat Thomas
Faranda, a Minnesotan who quit an absentee race though his name
stayed on the GOP ballot.
   Stephens, a former state senator from Havre who edged Rep. Cal
Winslow for the GOP nomination, says memories also may hurt Judge.
He said the former governor ``represents an administration from
yesteryear.''
   With 977 of 982 precincts reporting, or 99 percent, Judge had
46,274 votes, or 39 percent.
   Former Supreme Court Justice Frank Morrison Jr. had 31,868 votes
or 27 percent, and Attorney General Mike Greely had 26,742 votes or
23 percent.
   State Sen. Ted Neuman got 6 percent of the vote; Martin ``Red''
Beckman, a tax protester, got 3 percent and Emmett ``Curly''
Thornton, an ex-drug addict turned evangelist, took 2 percent.
   In the Republican gubernatorial race, with 99 percent of
precincts reporting, Stephens had 43,684 votes or 50 percent to
Winslow's 37,585 votes or 43 percent.
   In the Democratic Senate primary, with 977 of 982 precincts
reporting, or 99 percent, Melcher had 87,498 votes or 75 percent,
compared with 29,766 votes or 25 percent for Kelleher.
   On the Republican side, Burns, a county commissioner from
Billings, defeated Thomas Faranda, a Minnesotan who filed for the
GOP nomination but gave up his absentee quest in April, tough his
name remained on the ballot.
   With 99 percent of precincts reporting, Burns had 63,007 votes
or 85 percent, compared with 11,419 votes, or 15 percent, for
Faranda.
   Melcher said the difference between him and Burns is experience.
   ``I think it's pretty obvious I've been here awhile,'' Melcher
said in a telephone interview from his suburban Washington, D.C.,
home. ``He's going to try and say that's a disadvantage, but I
don't really think it is.
   ``The longer you're here, the more chances you have to get bills
passed ... that will benefit Montana,'' Melcher said.
</TEXT>
