<2ND_LINE>PM-Elvis-Auction,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elvis Presley Jewelry Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jewel-encrusted brooch depicting bees was one
of the whimsical gifts from Elvis Presley to a former girlfriend
that was auctioned.
   The 31 pieces of jewelry, which included lavish gold pendants,
rings and bracelets made of diamonds, emeralds or opals, fetched a
total $82,000 Tuesday, surpassing the presale estimate of $50,000.
   Many pieces sold for two to 10 times the estimate, said Robin
Ahrens, spokeswoman for Christie's, the auctioneer.
   An unidentified lawyer from Tuscaloosa, Ala., purchased nine
items for $28,000, including a 22-carat opal and diamond ring that
sold for $4,400.
   The ring was a gift from Presley to the unidentified woman in
1974. The entertainer believed opals possessed a magical quality,
said Mrs. Ahrens.
   The lawyer also spent $2,750 on a classic 1972 diamond pin
spelling the word ``Love,'' which was a Christmas gift.
   Two top lots that both sold for $5,270 were a black onyx,
diamond and gold choker and the bee brooch made of diamonds, rubies
and yellow gold. Both items were expected to bring in between
$2,000 and $2,500.
   Presley had presented the bee brooch as a ``whimsical gift,''
said Mrs. Ahrens.
   Bidders came from across the country as well as Europe and Asia.
   The Presley items were part of an ``important jewels'' auction
that brought a total of $5,169,527 for 355 lots. Prices included a
10 percent buyer's premium.
</TEXT>
