<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BookAuction     06-08 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Book Auction,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poe Book Once Purchased For $15 Is Sold For $198,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare book by Edgar Allen Poe that a
Massachusetts man picked up for $15 in a New Hampshire barn was
auctioned for $198,000, putting the seller in a ``dream world,'' an
auction house official said.
   The first-edition copy of ``Tamerlane and Other Poems,'' only
the 12th known copy of Poe's first book published in 1827, was sold
at Sotheby's auction house Tuesday to a rare book dealer for less
than expected.
   Even so, the Massachusetts seller was `extremely happy,''
Sotheby's Vice President David Redden said. ``He's still in, I
think, a sort of dream world over the whole business.''
   The seller, who demanded anonymity said he found the book in an
antique barn in southern New Hampshire. The barn was not identified.
   Poe, who paid to have the book published by an obscure Boston
publisher, went on to write such classic poems and stories of
horror and romance as ``Annabel Lee,'' ``The Raven,'' and ``The
Tell-tale Heart.''
   ``It's the rarest book in American literature _ it's the most
famous book in American literature,'' said the buyer, Manhattan
book dealer James Cummins. ``It's the book that every rare book
seller hopes to get his hands on.''
   Cummins said he was buying the book for a ``serious book
collector'' from New York and was ``very pleased'' with the price,
which Sotheby's described as a record for a work of American
literature.
   Sotheby's had estimated the book's value at $200,000 to
$300,000. The $198,000 price includes the 10 percent commission
that goes to Sotheby's.
   The soft-cover book, which contains the long title poem and nine
shorter ones, bears no reference to Poe, listing the author only as
``a Bostonian.'' Although Poe was born in Boston, he lived there
only a few months before his parents moved to Richmond, Va. He
lived in Boston again for about eight weeks when ``Tamerlane'' was
published.
   The work had been written about five years earlier, when Poe was
12 or 13 years old. There is no indication that a single copy of
the book was ever sold, and it never has been highly regarded by
critics.
   Its value is considered historical more than literary, since it
is the first and rarest work by Poe.
   Of the 11 other known copies of ``Tamerlane,'' all but one are
owned by libraries or other institutions. The only other one in
private hands is on loan to the Pierpont Morgan Library in New York.
   Also sold Tuesday were four handwritten notebooks by Nobel
laureate Saul Bellow that comprised the rough draft of his 1970
novel, ``Mr. Sammler's Planet.''
   The notebooks, believed to be the first archive of a major
living author's published work to be auctioned during his life,
brought $66,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoSchools     06-08 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Schools,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Chicago's ``Worst'' Schools Best Place to Try Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's schools could point the way for others
to improve, says Education Secretary William Bennett, who has
called the city's school system America's worst.
   However, Bennett said Tuesday that his view hadn't changed much
from November, when he called the city's public schools an
``education meltdown.''
   ``If it's not the worst, it's too ... close to the worst,''
Bennett told reporters after a speech before the Chicago Council on
Foreign Relations.
   Although he said the city's educational system was ``sad'' and
``very destructive,'' Bennett expressed optimism about the future.
   ``There are radical proposals in the air. This may be a
revolutionary time,'' said Bennett, who reiterated his support for
a tuition voucher plan.
   Under the plan, a school system would issue a voucher to parents
for each child, and the parents could then choose a public or a
private school. The schools would redeem vouchers for government
money.
   Bennett said the system, which is aimed at encouraging
competition among schools, has not been tried on a large scale in
the United States. He predicted that if a major test comes, it
would be in Milwaukee or Chicago.
   ``If you tried it, tried it honestly and fairly, I would predict
it would improve things dramatically,'' he added.
   Whatever comes out of efforts to improve Chicago's
430,000-student system, ``may be able to point the way for other
school systems in the country,'' Bennett said.
   City schools Superintendent Manford Byrd Jr. called the plan
``just a diversion from funding the public school system the way it
should be funded.''
   ``It is intended to deny students now in the system, who tend to
be minority and poor, the type of funding they need to be served,''
Byrd said. ``I think (Bennett's) bashing of the public school
system was only intended to make the climate right for the
destruction of the system.''
   Bennett also called for redistributing power to give parents and
principals more say over school policies like curriculum and
personnel.
   He labeled the Chicago school burueaucracy ``the blob,'' and
accused teacher unions of blocking reform in a system plagued by
low test scores and high dropout rates.
   Statistics show nearly 45 percent of students who began school
with the class of 1985 dropped out before graduating. State figures
also show that half of Chicago's public high schools ranked in the
bottom 1 percent of U.S. schools for student scores on the American
College Test.
   Bennett called any reform that didn't redistribute power
``nonsense,'' and said unions interested only in ``getting more and
more for everyone'' may be hurt in the short run. But positive
changes in schools would help unions in the long run by raising the
professional esteem of teachers, he said.
   Bennett visited two Chicago schools in March at the request of
Chicago Teachers Union. He said afterward that ``intransigence of
special interests'' such as unions remain the biggest obstacle to
reform.
   Jacqueline Vaughn, president of the Chicago union, said then
that cutbacks in government funds were the real culprits.
</TEXT>
