<DOCNO> AP880608-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Lenin     06-08 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Lenin,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Journal Takes On Lenin in Unusual Glasnost-Era Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet founder Vladimir Lenin misguidedly approved
the use of terror and was also wrong to abolish all private
property and create a system of forced labor camps, a Soviet
literary journal says.
   Such criticism would have been forbidden before the era of
``glasnost,'' or greater openness, ushered in by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Still, the overall tone of the article in the monthly Novy Mir
is moderate, and it concludes that Lenin made the mistakes early
on, realized he was wrong and deserves praise.
   Vassily Selyunin, the author of the 30-page article, said that
in the first few years after the Bolsheviks took power in 1917,
Lenin favored overly harsh measures for putting the country's
economy back on track.
   Selyunin wrote in the May edition of Novy Mir that Lenin
considered using violent means to shore up the economy, as was done
in the French Revolution.
   In November 1917, Lenin declared that ``speculators'' were
``enemies of the people'' who should be shot when found, according
to Selyunin. Speculation then meant anything outside government
trade.
   Lenin also advocated another harsh measure, limiting peasant
families to only the bread they needed to make it to the next
harvest, Selyunin wrote. The penalty for violation was a minimum
10-year jail term.
   The author says Lenin might be excused for some of the harsh
measures because the country was suffering severe hunger and
destruction. But the measures actually exacerbated the problems,
Selyunin wrote.
   In January 1918, Lenin supported a decree that increased the
space for prisoners so that ``class enemies'' could be
incarcerated. Shortly thereafter, a system of labor camps was set
up, and many people accused of economic crimes were imprisoned
there, Selyunin wrote.
   The article says the founder of the Soviet secret police, Felix
A. Dzerzhinksy, also justified the use of labor camps.
   ``The need for self-defense was so great that we consciously
could close our eyes to a series of mistakes, if only to preserve
the republic,'' it says.
   The criticism of Dzerzhinsky also was unusual for the Soviet
press, which generally extolls him as a hero who helped defend the
country.
   Selyunin implied that Lenin sowed the seeds for the extreme
abuses of power for which his successor, Josef Stalin, has been
condemned.
   Gorbachev has encouraged historians to take a more honest look
at the country's past. The result has been numerous press articles,
books and films abhoring Stalin, who sent millions of people to
their death through purges, forced collectivization of agriculture
and other repressions.
   Gorbachev has sharply criticized Stalin's economic policies,
under which the central government tightly controlled production of
goods and services, allowing for little individual initiative.
   The criticism has extended to the ``era of stagnation'' under
Leonid I. Brezhnev, who was Communist Party chief from 1964 to 1982.
   But criticism of Lenin has been off-limits. He is still
generally portrayed as a far-sighted genius of unsurpassed wisdom.
   The Novy Mir article took advantage of glasnost to break new
ground in criticizing Lenin:
   ``The extremes of force, as we see, spread boundlessly: first it
is undertaken for repression of opponents of the revolution, then
it is turned against potential enemies (the Red Terror) and finally
it becomes a means for solving purely economic tasks,'' Selyunin
wrote.
   But Selunin said Lenin began to realize he was wrong, and he
quotes the leader as saying the use of force was backfiring,
increasing civil unrest.
   In March 1921, Lenin made a mid-course correction and did away
with a severe tax on peasants. Two months later, he launched his
New Economic Policy, which allowed greater freedom in agriculture,
industry and trade.
   Selyunin credits Lenin's flexibility and the new policy with
helping rid the country of bureaucracy, which Gorbachev has said is
stifling some of his reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
