<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Bernstein,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Named Laureate Conductor of Israeli Philharmonic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer Leonard Bernstein, speaking in
fractured Hebrew, accepted a scroll naming him Laureate Conductor
of the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra.
   ``Thank you very much, both members of the orchestra and
non-members of the orchestra. This is the biggest honor of my
life,'' Bernstein said Tuesday night in Hebrew after ex-Foreign
Minister Abba Eban chided him for not learning the language.
   Eban recalled that the white-haired, 70-year-old maestro
directed the orchestra in the newly captured town of Beersheba
during the war of independence in 1948.
   He returned frequently to conduct concerts, including the first
staged after the Six-Day war in 1967.
   ``He was the herald and messenger of all our great occasions,''
Eban said.
</TEXT>
