<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WanderingWoman     06-08 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wandering Woman,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alzheimer's Victim Found After A Week In The Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old Alzheimer's disease victim
was returned to her home after she was found by rescuers who had
searched for her the past seven days.
   Mary Margaret Rinkert was found near Liberty Reservoir, less
than a half mile away from Oakland Manor, the care center she had
walked away from on May 31.
   She left with only her clothes _ a navy blue skirt, blouse, navy
blue blazer, white knitted hat and pink slippers. When she was
found, Tuesday morning, she was barefoot, with cuts and bruises on
her legs and feet. Her jacket had been rolled up to cushion her
head. She was dehydrated, but she endured several nights of
temperatures in the 40s.
   ``It was an incredible moment,'' said Kathy Ash of Catonsville,
the woman's daughter and one of the first people to reach her.
``She was staring up at the sky. She was shaking badly. I just felt
that if she was tough enough to have lasted that long, she would
pull it off.''
   Mrs. Rinkert was resting Tuesday night at the Baltimore County
General Hospital in Randallstown. Mrs. Ash hopes that once her
mother is discharged she can return to Oakland Manor.
</TEXT>
