<DOCNO> AP880608-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea     06-08 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Forces On Alert To Stop March To North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government began deploying 60,000
riot police today to stop radical students marching to communist
North Korea. In Seoul, troopers firing tear gas broke up a rally.
   National Police Headquarters said tens of thousands of riot
police would block roads to the North Korean border to prevent the
march Friday. Riot police began surrounding colleges today in Seoul
as security forces went on top alert.
   Riot police in green combat fatigues and black, visored helmets
fired volleys of tear gas when several hundred students at Yonsei
University tried to march into the street after a rally for the
march.
   A few students hurled rocks and a handful of firebombs, but the
marchers were quickly driven back into the campus by the 4,000 riot
police surrounding the school.
   Students yelling anti-American slogans staged a rally at nearby
Mongji University to prepare for the march. Speakers denounced the
United States, claiming it enforces partition of the peninsula.
   ``Drive out Yankees who enforce the partition of our land,''
students shouted as they shot clenched fists into the air.
   Hundreds of riot police surrounded the school and plainclothes
police officers chased students trying to reach the campus for the
rally.
   Radical leaders have called for up to 40,000 students to rally
at Yonsei Thursday for an overnight vigil before the 30-mile march
to the border north of Seoul. Radicals deny they are pro-North
Korean, but insist on immediate reunification of the Korean people.
   Police said today the school would be completely surrounded to
stop the march. They also warned that campuses would be raided to
detain radical leaders before the march.
   Riot police also stepped up security around government buildings
and U.S. diplomatic facilities in case of student attacks if the
march is blocked. Hundreds of riot police guarded the U.S. Embassy.
   Yonsei University officials were considering installing nets to
stop students committing suicide by jumping off buildings. Some
students have threatened to kill themselves if the march is
blocked. There have been three anti-government protest suicides
since May 15.
   Radical students plan to march to the border truce site of
Panmunjom to meet with North Korean students and clear the way for
reunification of the peninsula, divided since 1945.
   The government has banned the march as a threat to national
security. Government officials say the radicals will play into the
hands of the communist north.
   President Roh Tae-woo met with top officials today to review
plans to stop the march, but no details were released. Unification
Minister Lee Hong-koo, in a meeting with student leaders, refused
to reconsider the ban on the march.
   Opposition leaders called on the students today to call off
plans for the march, saying it lacked national support. They urged
students and government officials to hold talks.
   ``There is no mature consensus on national reunfication,''
opposition leaders Kim Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam and Kim Jong-pil
said in a statement after meeting.
   Many South Koreans oppose the students, though most people
support reunification of the peninsula. But most people in the
south fear the hostile north is determined to conquer the whole
peninsula.
   The two Koreas are bitter foes and the north has often attacked
the south. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to trigger the
Korean War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
