<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-JetFighter     06-08 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Jet Fighter,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Corp. To Represent U.S. F-16 Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mitsubishi Corp., Japan's largest trading
company, has been selected to represent General Dynamics in plans
to develop a Japanese jet fighter, the company said today.
   General Dynamics manufactures the F-16 Eagle jet fighter, on
which the new Japanese plane, called the FSX, is to be based.
   Mitsubishi will handle sales in Japan of any components or
technology developed by General Dynamics in the FSX project, said a
company official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``We look forward to working with Mitsubishi Corp. on this
exciting new project,'' said Vernon A. Lee, General Dynamics' FSX
program director, in a statement.
   ``We are also very appreciative of the interest that was shown
by other highly qualified Japanese companies relative to providing
representation for the FSX program,'' he said.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci reached agreement in Tokyo
last week with Japanese defense officials on joint U.S.-Japanese
production of the new-generation fighter, with 35-45 percent of the
work to be conducted by the U.S. side. The Japanese side is to bear
the estimated $1.32 billion development costs.
   The private sector on the U.S. side will develop the engine,
while the Japanese will develop the new plane's radar system.
Private contractors have not been formally named, but since the FSX
will be based on the F-16, General Dynamics is likely to play a
major role.
</TEXT>
