<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Obit-Harty 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Harty, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0593,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Talk-Show Host Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf, `The former...' to CORRECT `him' to `her.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LEEDS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Russell Harty, a writer and broadcaster
who became one of Britain's top television talk-show hosts, died
early today, a hospital said. He was 54.
   Harty, who suffered from liver failure caused by hepatitis,
underwent surgery for internal bleeding when his condition
deteriorated over the weekend, said a statement from St. James
University Hospital.
   He underwent further surgery overnight and died at 4:30 a.m. in
the operating room, the statement said.
   Harty was rushed unconscious to the hospital in this northern
England city on May 3. He regained consciousness after five days in
a grade four coma, the deepest known, but remained in critical
condition.
   Harty immediately asked doctors to express his thanks to
thousands of his fans who had inundated the hospital with get-well
cards and messages of concern.
   Published reports said Harty apparently contracted hepatitis, an
inflammation of the liver, while making a television series on a
tour of Europe earlier this year. He was treated for hepatitis in
early April and discharged to convalesce.
   The former English and drama schoolteacher had a lugubrious and
disarming manner on television. His interview subjects ranged from
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to rock stars. American rock star
Grace Jones once struck him across the head because she thought he
was ignoring her during a TV interview.
   After success as a director and producer, Harty launched his own
hugely successful talk show, ``Russell Harty Plus,'' in 1973.
</TEXT>
