<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CalPrimary-Mojave     06-08 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cal Primary-Mojave,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effort to Create Nation's Biggest County Fails at Polls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters rejected an effort to carve
out a new county in the high desert of Southern California, but
desert dwellers vowed to continue their campaign for political
independence.
   The proposal to split a new Mojave County out of San Bernardino
County was foundering, 67 percent to 33 percent, with 88 percent of
precincts reporting.
   San Bernardino is the nation's biggest county in area, but
Mojave would have claimed that title with 18,160 square miles,
stretching from the edge of Los Angeles' eastern suburbs across the
Mojave Desert to the Arizona border.
   Residents of the area that would be Mojave County favored the
measure, 60 percent to 40 percent. County-wide, however, the vote
was 111,283 against, 54,709 in favor.
   Secessionists saw the vote as vindication of their frequent
complaints that the county government, dominated by representatives
of such rapidly urbanizing communities as San Bernardino, Fontana
and Ontario, doesn't understand their needs.
   ``The message is very clear,'' said Tom Pinard, president of
Mojave County Proponents. ``We don't have the representation. We
pay the taxes and the services aren't coming back.''
   ``If Mojave County can't squeak through this time, it's far from
dead,'' said Bob Sagona, secretary of the pro-county group.
   One-county backers said voters feared that separation would
leave both counties with insufficient tax base to support needed
services.
   The secession required both a simple majority vote of all county
residents, and a simple majority of residents of the region that
would become Mojave.
   Mojave, which would have been the state's first new county in 80
years, would have claimed 90 percent of the land in present-day San
Bernardino County. But with a population of 205,000, it would take
just one-fifth of the present county's residents.
   Left behind would have been the state's second-smallest county,
a narrow strip of the present county with a population of 1.1
million. That area is swelling with the overflow of population from
Los Angeles and beset by smog and a rising crime rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
