<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Protest     06-08 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Protest,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2,000 Winegrowers Protest Low Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 winegrowers blocked a main
street in a central Hungarian town to protest low prices, unsold
stocks and state purchases from abroad, newspapers said today.
   The protest Tuesday in Kisokoeroes was the first such
demonstration reported in the communist country.
   The trade union daily Nepszava and government daily Magyar
Hirlap said the winegrowers blocked the street with tractors,
trailers and mobile spraying units.
   The demonstrators dismantled the blockade only after the local
member of the national Parliament, Sandor Csipko, spoke on their
behalf to local and national farm officials, the newspapers said.
   The official MTI news agency quoted unidentified farmers as
saying at least 1 million gallons of unsold wine are stored in the
wine cellars of the fertile central Hungarian plain.
   Unidentified winegrowers were quoted as telling the newspapers
that wine sells at about 25 cents per quart when purchased by state
organizations.
   The farmers reportedly said that production costs are about 50
percent higher, while the wine sells in shops for four to eight
times more than the purchasing price.
   The newspapers said the farmers also protested the reported
purchase of 234,000 gallons of wine from abroad last year.
   MTI said officials from the national agriculture ministry
promised to speed up state purchases of their wines.
</TEXT>
