<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Self-Immolation     06-08 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Self-Immolation,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Doused Herself Near Kremlin Wall Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who doused herself with gasoline and set
herself on on fire by the Kremlin wall died after a difficult life
as an orphan and former mental patient, a newspaper reported today.
   Moscow News, a weekly paper, said Nadezhda Bannaya was burned
over 85 percent of her body and died Monday in a trauma institute.
   Soviet officials had confirmed the fire on Friday.
   The woman, who was 46, moved from city to city, frequently
changing jobs, the newspaper said.
   ``I heard an awful woman's scream,'' militiaman Oleg Zhmirya
told Moscow News, ``and immediately ran to her. On the way another
worker joined me. The woman was already burning.''
   The militiaman and the assistant put the woman on the lawn and
began to stamp out the fire with their jackets and hats during the
incident Friday, the newspaper said. A Kremlin worker brought an
overcoat and put out the flames. The woman was taken to a hospital.
   Maj. Valentin Kirsanov of the Red Square militia detachment told
Moscow News that a can, a pocketbook with a passport and work
record book and notepad with prayers and a letter were found near
the scene.
   Bannaya came from a family of seven whose mother died early. She
was brought up in an orphanage and lived mostly in the Ukraine
moving frequently and working as a maid and a cleaning woman, the
newspaper said.
   A militia lieutenant told The Associated Press on Friday the
reasons for the woman's action were not known. He said the incident
occurred on the cobble esplanade between St. Basil's Cathedral and
the red brick wall surrounding the Kremlin.
   Moscow News has been at the forefront of the Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for greater openness on social
issues and its report of this incident was in line with that policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Lanier     06-08 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Lanier,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired AP Writer Alfred Lanier Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred Sidney Lanier, a retired Associated
Press correspondent who covered major stories in South Carolina for
more than two decades, has died at age 64.
   Lanier died Tuesday after a long illness.
   Among the stories he reported or edited in Columbia, S.C., in
the 1960s and 1970s was the slaying of three blacks by state
troopers during a civil rights protest at South Carolina State
College in 1968. Twenty-seven other blacks were wounded.
   The Savannah native first worked at the Savannah Morning News,
rising from police reporter to managing editor from 1949 to 1952,
when he joined the AP in its Montgomery, Ala., bureau.
   He transferred to Detroit in 1952 and to Columbia in 1958. Five
years later, Lanier was appointed correspondent for South Carolina.
   He retired in 1981 to return to Savannah.
   Survivors include his wife, Lanier Jones Lanier.
   The funeral was scheduled for Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
