<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0837EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CalPrimary-AIDS     06-08 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cal Primary-AIDS,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Undaunted By Defeat of AIDS Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ballot proposal that could have led to the
quarantine of AIDS victims went down to overwhelming defeat after
being sponsored for a second time by political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche.
   ``The initiative makes no more sense today than it did two years
ago,'' said Ken Kizer, director of the state Department of Health
Services.
   With 96 percent of 22,718 precincts reporting early today,
3,481,311 voters or 68 percent disapproved Proposition 69, while
1,628,744 or 32 percent approved it.
   LaRouche, however, indicated he would not drop his crusade.
   ``AIDS is not going to go away,'' he said in a statement
released by his press spokeswoman Dana Scanlon, who said LaRouche
made the comments by phone from West Germany. ``If the voters vote
against me, then they're wrong. I'm right, deadly right on this.''
   It was the second time in 18 months that LaRouche's AIDS plan
failed at the ballot box. Proposition 69 was a clone of his
Proposition 64, which in November 1986 was defeated by a slightly
larger margin than Tuesday's vote.
   In contrast to the public controversy over Proposition 64, the
latest measure drew little debate and its defeat was widely
expected.
   If adopted, it would have required health officials to report to
the state health department the names of people with AIDS and those
testing positive for antibodies to the virus.
   The measure also would have added acquired immune deficiency
syndrome to the state's list of communicable diseases, making those
with the disease as well as carriers of the virus subject to
possible quarantine.
   The medical community and public health officials joined with
homosexual and civil rights groups to denounce the proposition.
They said it would force AIDS victims underground and discourage
them from seeking treatment.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to death from infections and cancer. It
is most often spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers or transfusion of infected blood or blood
products.
   As of May 30, AIDS had been diagnosed in 63,726 Americans, of
whom more than half, or 35,798, have died, according to the
national Centers for Disease Control.
</TEXT>
