<1ST_LINE>r i PM-StrangeMarriage 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Strange Marriage, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0597,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Marries Photograph Of Man Convicted In Gandhi Killing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 to CLARIFY that couples walk around fire. Pick
up 7th graf pvs: `In 1984..'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old Sikh woman married an
assassin of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi in a bizarre ceremony
during which a photograph stood in for the bridegroom, a newspaper
said today.
   The Statesman newspaper said Surinder Kaur was married May 2 to
a photograph of Satwant Singh in a village in Punjab state.
   Singh could not attend the wedding because he is in jail on
death row.
   The marriage rites were performed by a Sikh priest, the
newspaper said, but it was unclear on whether the ceremony had
legal or religious sanction.
   Mrs. Kaur garlanded a photograph of Satwant Singh and carried it
around a fire seven times, the newspaper said. The bride and groom
customarily walk around a fire in orthodox Sikh weddings.
   Singh and Mrs. Kaur had been engaged since 1983.
   In 1984, Singh was assigned to guard the prime minister. On Oct.
31, 1984, he and another Sikh bodyguard shot Mrs. Gandhi in the
garden of her residence in the capital.
   Singh, now 25, was convicted of murder and sentenced to be
hanged by a special court. An appeal is pending before the Supreme
Court.
   The Statesman said Mrs. Kaur went through with the marriage
despite opposition from her parents and Singh's parents.
   ``I tried everything I could do to stop her,'' Mrs. Kaur's
father, Wirsa Singh, was quoted as telling the newspaper, which
said the parents yielded after their daughter threatened to commit
suicide if not allowed to marry.
   Satwant Singh was informed of his marriage two weeks after the
ceremony when his parents visited him at New Delhi's central jail,
the paper said.
   It did not report his reaction.
   ``Whatever happens, I stand by my act of marrying him,'' The
Statesman quoted the bride as saying. ``If unhappiness is to be my
lot, then let it be so.''
   Satwant Singh is one of three people facing the death sentence
for the assassination, apparently carried out in revenge for the
government's decision to storm the Golden Temple, the holiest Sikh
shrine, in June 1984.
   At least 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, were killed when
soldiers stormed the temple in 1984. The shrine in Amritsar, 260
miles northwest of New Delhi, was being used as a base by Sikh
militants agitating for an independent homeland.
   Sikhs form just 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are
in a majority in Punjab. Dissident Sikhs claim discrimination by
the Hindus, who form 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CalPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0638 06-08 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cal Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0878</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with 100 percent returns in all races. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>McCarthy Beats Three To Face Republican Wilson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy easily won the right to
face Republican incumbent Sen. Pete Wilson this fall, while the
state's voters narrowly declined a chance to become the first to
directly order the closing of a nuclear plant.
   California voters on Tuesday also rejected propositions that
could have quarantined AIDS victims, split the nation's largest
county in two and relaxed government spending limits imposed by
California's 1979 tax revolt.
   McCarthy soundly defeated three political unknowns in the
Democratic Senate primary in Tuesday's voting.
   With 100 percent of the 23,596 precincts reporting, McCarthy
amassed 2,303,029 votes or 82 percent. John Hancock Abbott of Santa
Clara had 214,420 votes or 8 percent, Robert Banuelos of Orange had
159,610 votes or 6 percent and Charles Greene of Los Angeles had
142,520 votes or 5 percent.
   In the presidential primaries, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis swept to an easy victory over Jesse Jackson, netting the
fraction of the state's 314 Democratic delegates he needed to
clinch his party's nomination, while Vice President George Bush won
the state's Republican primary, where 175 delegates were being
awarded.
   San Diego Mayor Maureen O'Connor coasted to an easy re-election
victory over former City Councilman Floyd Morrow. With all the vote
counted, O'Conner pulled in 124,222 votes or 59.5 percent to
Morrow's 69,974 or 33.5 percent.
   Among a slew of ballot measures Tuesday was a $1 billion bond
measure sponsored by Gov. George Deukmejian to fund highway
construction and improvement. With all precincts reporting, the
proposal barely lost by 2,560,221 no votes to 2,559,394 in favor.
   Another that narrowly lost was Proposition 71, designed to relax
spending limits Californians placed on their state government in a
1979 voter initiative. The measure would have permitted an
estimated $700 million annual increase in state spending, reducing
by an equal amount the funds likely to be earmarked for future tax
rebates.
   With 100 percent of the precincts reporting, the vote total was
2,579,562 against, or 51 percent, to 2,472,003 in favor, or 49
percent.
   Proposition 72, which also would have changed the spending
limit, but with almost exactly the opposite effect, was defeated 38
percent to 61 percent, 3,167,414 votes to 1,980,987. It would have
reduced the limit for most state programs by an estimated $725
million annually by earmarking those funds exclusively for highways.
   A proposal backed by extremist Lyndon LaRouche to declare AIDS a
communicable disease was soundly defeated 3,605,580 to 1,691,300,
or 68 percent to 32 percent.
   The proposition was opposed by the California Medical
Association and the leadership of both major parties. It matched a
measure sponsored by LaRouche's organization that was beaten 2-1 in
1986.
   In Sacramento County, an initiative that sought to close the
troubled Rancho Seco nuclear power plant narrowly lost. With all of
880 precincts reporting, the measure was defeated by 125,768 votes,
or 50.4 percent, to 123,614 votes, or 49.6 percent. If passed, it
would have marked the first time in history that voters directly
ordered closure of a nuclear plant.
   However, a competing measure to continue operating the plant on
a trial basis for an additional 18 months passed by 129,929 votes,
or 51.6 percent, to 121,803 votes, or 48.4 percent.
   A proposal to carve out a new Mojave County from the desert
portions of San Bernardino County, the nation's largest, lost by
111,283 votes, or 67 percent, to 54,709, or 32.9 percent, with 707
of 804 precincts reporting.
   Proposition 68, which would impose contribution limits on
legislative races and create a system of public financing for
candidates who limit spending, was approved by 53 percent,
2,716,341, to 47 percent, 2,425,064.
   A competing proposition to limit contributions in all races and
prohibit public financing was approved by a 58 percent to 42
percent margin, with 3,044,034 votes in favor and 2,206,718 opposed.
   However, since Proposition 73 was favored by a wider margin than
Proposition 68, Proposition 73's provisions would supersede those
of the other.
   Only one congressional incumbent, freshman Republican Ernest
Konnyu of Saratoga, lost his seat. Stanford University Professor
Tom Campbell, a moderate supported by Konnyu's two Republican
predecessors, former Reps. Pete McCloskey and Ed Zschau, won by 58
percent to 42 percent with all the vote counted.
   In two heavily Republican Los Angeles-area congressional
districts in which the incumbents retired, the winners in the GOP
primaries were two former Reagan White House aides who campaigned
with the help of indicted former White House national security aide
Oliver North.
   Former deputy White House counsel Christopher Cox of Santa Ana
was the victor in the 13-candidate 40th District primary, while
former speechwriter Dana Rohrabacher of Los Angeles topped a field
of eight Republicans seeking the 42nd District nomination.
   In the Senate primary, both Wilson and McCarthy concentrated on
fund-raising and laying the groundwork for November.
   Wilson has led McCarthy in fund-raising and the polls, but has
to contend with a political jinx _ no one has been re-elected to
his Senate seat in more than 30 years.
</TEXT>
