<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0655,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Trying to Stop Arab Resignations After Arab Mayor Stabbed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with doctor saying Gaza teen-ager
died of wounds from beating. ADDS details. Trims. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli authorities today offered protection to
Arab officials in the occupied West Bank after an Israeli-appointed
Arab mayor was stabbed in the heart, apparently by Palestinian
militants.
   The army maintained a curfew on El Bireh and some areas in the
neighboring town of Ramallah as it continued to search for suspects
in the Tuesday stabbing of Hassan Tawil, 74, the El Bireh mayor.
   Tawil was in stable condition, said a doctor at Ramallah
hospital who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Israelis are trying to stop other Arab officials from
quitting under pressure from militants.
   The Israeli newspaper Maariv said the military government would
step up protection for the Arab officials, but it did not specify
what steps would be taken. An army spokesman refused comment.
   A 19-year-old man from the Gaza Strip refugee camp of Jebalya
died overnight from wounds he suffered when beaten by Israel
soldiers, Dr. Ahmed Yassih of Gaza City's Shifa Hospital said. The
army confirmed Hussein Jam'a Abu-Jallalah died but said said the
circumstances and cause of death were not clear.
   The death would raise the number of Arabs killed in the
six-month old Palestinian uprising to 202. Two Israelis have also
died in the unrest in lands Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   Israel radio today reported the army would prosecute an officer
and two soldiers for excessive use of force in Arura, a village
near Ramallah where two residents said they were buried under a
pile of rocks last month.
   Hanna Atrash, the elected Arab mayor of the West Bank town of
Beit Sahour, said eight soldiers in two jeeps offered to protect
him but he refused when they said he couldn't go anywhere without
them.
   ``I also told them they are hurting me more than they are
helping me,'' he said.
   Atrash was elected mayor in 1976, the last year Israel allowed
free elections in the territories.
   Tawil is one of about a dozen Arab mayors appointed by the
military government to replace Israeli officers who ran the towns
and cities after some mayors were deposed and elections were
banned. The heads of about 85 village councils also are appointed
by the military government.
   A senior military official said army representatives were
meeting with Arab officials to block resignations anticipated after
the stabbing and the appearance of a new underground leaflet
calling on Israeli-appointed officials to resign.
   Many Arab officials have received threats or had their homes
stoned or firebombed in recent weeks, said the official, also
speaking on condition on anonymity.
   But by this morning, ``not one person has resigned,'' said
Olivier Rafowicz, spokesman for the army administration.
   The mayor of the West Bank town of Qalqilya, Rahman Abu Sneineh,
condemned the stabbing and told Israeli army radio that he did not
want any protection because ``God will protect me.''
   Abu Sneineh, who is considered a moderate, said he had no reason
to fear because ``I do not cooperate with the military government,
I only cooperate with the residents of my town.''
   The army said there was no basis for the allegation that
esidents were buried under a pile of rocks in Arura. But the
officer and two soldiers would be tried for using force on suspects
after their arrest and allegedly shooting at the legs of protesters
without justification, Israel radio said.
   In a new leaflet issued Tuesday, the PLO-led United Leadership
of the Uprising called for a general strike Thursday.
   For the first time, underground leaders also called for arson
attacks on farmland, forests and industries inside Israel. The
directive declared June 22 ``a day to burn the enemy's agricultural
and industrial resources.''
</TEXT>
