<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CalPrimary-Nuclear     06-08 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cal Primary-Nuclear,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Narrowly Approve Extension for Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By a slender margin, voters rejected an
opportunity to become the first to approve the shutdown of a
nuclear power plant and decided to give the problem-plagued Rancho
Seco plant another chance.
   After an expensive and hard-fought campaign, area voters Tuesday
narrowly approved a ballot measure sponsored by Rancho Seco
managers to grant an 18-month trial run to the plant, which has one
of the worst performance records in the nation.
   With all precincts reporting from Sacramento County and a
1,000-vote section of Placer County, the unofficial totals were
129,929 votes, or 51.6 percent, in favor of the measure to 121,803
votes, or 48.4 percent, opposed.
   A second initiative that would have shut down Rancho Seco
permanently lost by a slight margin, receiving 123,614 votes or
49.6 percent in favor and 125,768, or 50.4 percent, against.
   The battle of the competing propositions was a victory for the
Sacramento Municipal Utility District, which operates Rancho Seco
and put the second measure on the ballot, and for the nuclear
industry, which heavily funded a $1.4 million campaign to save the
plant.
   Rancho Seco has operated at an average of only 40 percent of
capacity and has suffered more than 100 outages since it opened in
October 1984.
   ``We're happy that the community has given us an opportunity to
prove ourselves,'' said Dave Crespo of the Rancho Seco Political
Action Committee, a group of plant employees and contractors who
took part in the ballot campaign.
   ``We have a major chore ahead of us to demonstrate in physical
terms that the plant is safe and can operate reliably,'' he said.
   Harold Singer, president of the U.S. Council for Energy
Awareness, an industry group, noted that no state or local ballot
measure to shut down a nuclear power plant had ever passed.
Nationally, 14 measures to close or block nuclear plants had been
defeated in the last 13 years, he said.
   But opponents of Rancho Seco, who spent $400,000 in their
campaign, said the plant had won only a reprieve and not
vindication.
   ``The voters have placed Rancho Seco on probation, and they may
have only forestalled for a short time the inevitable closing of
the reactor, which is one of the worst in the country,'' said Ken
Bossong of Public Citizen, a Ralph Nader group that supported the
anti-Rancho Seco campaign.
   He said the vote was the closest in U.S. history on a measure to
close a nuclear plant.
   ``The issue is not going to go away,'' said Sacramento Mayor
Anne Rudin, a supporter of the closure proposal. ``People just
don't trust it (Rancho Seco) to work efficiently.''
   Rancho Seco, located 25 miles southeast of the state capital,
has one of the worst performance records in the country, according
to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   The movement to close the plant gained momentum following a
severe overcooling accident in December 1985 that idled the plant
for 27 months. It was restarted two months ago after a $400 million
overhaul.
   The approved measure provides for a second public vote on
continued operation of Rancho Seco in 18 months, and requires
closure of the plant any time after Dec. 31 if it fails to operate
at more than 50 percent capacity for four consecutive months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0100 </DOCNO>
