<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Mine-Memorial 1stLd-Writethru a0645 06-08 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Mine-Memorial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divers Join Serarch For Missing Miners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD divers joining search in flooded
shafts, dogs standing by, other details and color. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers searched flooded mine shafts
today for the last four men missing after an explosion killed at
least 47 men, and Christians and Moslems united in grief to pay
respects to the dead.
   The German and Turkish miners died when a powerful methane gas
explosion ripped through the Stolzenbach mine on June 1 in this
town 72 miles northeast of Frankfurt. Six men were rescued after
spending 65 hours trapped 500 feet underground.
   Peter-Carl Ruehland, spokesman for mine owner Preussen Elektra,
said the divers were sent into action today. He said the water was
five feet high in many parts of the mine.
   A total of 57 miners were trapped in the shaft after the
explosion.
   Specially trained dogs also were standing by to aid in the
search, the ZDF television network said. Officials said there was
little chance the four men were still alive, due to high levels of
deadly carbon monoxide.
   In the center of Borken, an estimated 3,000 mourners _ including
Turks and Germans _ filled the local community center for a joint
Christian-Moslem memorial service to the dead. Thirteen Turks were
among those killed in the blast.
   Niyazi Baloglu, the religious affairs counselor for the Turkish
embassy in Bonn, addressed the mourners in Turkish and called the
Turks who died in the blast ``heroes.''
   Tolay Guersel, 24, traveled from his home in Munich to attend
the service. The young man carried with him a picture of his uncle,
Ali Akser Akarsu, one of the Turks killed.
   A Lutheran pastor and a Roman Catholic priest read off the names
of all 47 miners confirmed dead, as well as the names of the four
missing.
   Roman Catholic Bishop Johannes Kapp of nearby Fulda also
celebrated the 75-minute service, in which a small group of miners
played solemn music.
   After the service, West German President Richard von Weizsaecker
talked to survivors' families, sitting in the front row.
   Town officials say $900,000 already has been collected to aid
the families of the victims.
</TEXT>
