<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0561 06-08 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0561,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says No One ``Due an Offer'' of No. 2 Spot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with Dukakis, Jackson comments; edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, fresh from a
nomination-clinching four-state primary sweep, said today neither
Jesse Jackson nor anyone else ``is due an offer'' to join him on
the Democratic ticket.
   Dukakis, who locked up the Democratic presidential nomination
with a four-primary sweep Tuesday, said he will review the possible
candidates within the next few days.
   Asked if Jackson, his closest opponent in the primaries,
deserved to be choice, Dukakis said, ``I don't think anyone is due
an offer.''
   ``But there are a great many people that are going to be
considered and he'll be one of them and I'm not going to rule
anybody in or out at this point,'' he said in an interview taped
earlier on ABC-TV.
   Jackson, interviewed on the same program, said, ``Consideration
does mean an offer; it does not mean just in passing. We have
earned consideration.''
   Today, following the final primary contests, Dukakis held a
majority of nominating delegates. His victory in the fight for the
nomination comes just under four months after his triumph in New
Hampshire set him on the winner's path.
   Jackson, the last of six rivals still contesting him in a race
where the suspense was long since spent, was beaten in each of the
four states holding primaries Tuesday _ New Jersey, New Mexico,
Montana and California.
   The Massachusetts governor was heading home today, stopping
along the way in St. Louis to receive the public endorsement of one
of those fallen rivals, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, and
another former foe was doing the same in Washington, Sen. Paul
Simon, D-Ill.
   Another former rival, Bruce Babbitt, said he too would bestow
his blessing today. ``I'll call him in the morning and tell him,''
the former Arizona governor said Tuesday night in San Francisco, as
Dukakis was scoring a lopsided victory in California.
   Dukakis staged a victory rally at the elegant ballroom of the
Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
   ``My friends, California has put us over the top,'' Dukakis
said. ``Now the coast-to-coast marathon has reached the Pacific,
and tomorrow the race to the finish line begins.''
   In a thematic victory speech, Dukakis savored his new position
as the party's nominee-to-be.
   ``My friends, what a golden opportunity this is for us,'' he
said of the nomination. ``And what quicksand for our opponents if
they waste this opportunity on mudslinging and name-calling.''
   Dukakis made little mention of Jackson and the uncertainty over
Jackson's intentions at the convention in Atlanta in July, where he
has threatened to lead a floor fight over South Africa policy.
   Jackson, speaking hours later, was conciliatory, saying: ``I
salute him for a fine campaign.''
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis had contended he saw no real
divisions within the party he will lead. But at the same time he
acknowledged he may have disputes with Jackson over the platform.
   ``We may have a floor fight or two,'' Dukakis said. ``There may
be some issues that go to the floor. I don't see any great
divisions within our party. We're going to have ourselves a great
convention.''
   As he had done across California in the final few days, Dukakis
recalled the start of his campaign nearly a year and a half ago
with an exploratory trip into Iowa in February 1987 _ a full year
before that state led off the 1988 delegate season.
   ``Fifteen months ago, in the snows of Iowa and New Hampshire, we
began our marathon run,'' he said. ``Along the way, our Democratic
rivals brought passion and substance to the competition, and I want
to pay special tribute to all of them.''
   Dukakis won his way to the nomination with a steady, methodical
_ some said plodding _ manner that proved successful despite
critics who said he needed more passion.
   Dukakis finished third in Iowa's first caucuses and rebounded to
win the primary in next-door New Hampshire.
   On Super Tuesday, the big regional primary in early March,
Dukakis did well enough. He surrounded the South by winning in New
England, Maryland, Florida and Texas _ the last two the biggest
prizes of that day and where he won without majorities.
   He stumbled with a third place finish in Illinois the next week
and was stunned by a two-to-one loss days later in Michigan's
caucuses.
   The twin setbacks raised questions about his abilities as a
campaigner, but Dukakis remained calm and changed his speeches but
not his style or tone.
   He rebounded in Wisconsin, and by the time New York's returns
were counted in mid-April, there was little doubt who would be the
Democratic nominee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
