<2ND_LINE>PM-Japanese Red Army, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0599,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MANILA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Alleged Japanese Terrorist Deported, Suspected Of Plotting
Olympics Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with arrival in Japan. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs: `Officials said...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged Japanese terrorist who authorities say
may have been involved in plotting attacks on the Olympic Games in
Seoul arrived today to heavy police guard after being deported from
the Philippines.
   About 100 police officers met the Japan Air Lines plane carrying
Hiroshi Sensui as it arrived at Tokyo's Narita airport, the Tokyo
Broadcasting Service said.
   The NPA official said police would start interrogating Sensui,
51, at Metropolitan Police headquarters tonight. The official spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Sensui was arrested Tuesday at a suburban Manila hotel and
hustled aboard a Japan Air Lines jet bound for Tokyo today.
   Officials said Sensui was a member of the leftist Japanese Red
Army and had been sought since 1977, when he was released from
prison in exchange for hostages aboard a JAL plane the terrorist
group had hijacked in Bangladesh.
   In Manila, Mirian Defensor-Santiago, the Philippine immigration
commissioner, told reporters Sensui had undergone plastic surgery
at the hospital where he was arrested and had to be identified by
fingerprints.
   She said the man had been living in the Philippines for several
years under the name Hiroshi Yamaguchi and had denied he was Sensui.
   Mrs. Defensor-Santiago said there were ``preliminary reports''
from regional security officials that ``the terrorists have
initiated activity expected to culminate in the Olympic Games.''
   She said evidence indicated the Japanese Red Army had planned to
use Manila as a base for operations during the Summer Olympic
Games, which begin Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   Western intelligence sources suspect the North Koreans may be
plotting to disrupt the games using Japanese and other
international terrorists.
   The Japanese Red Army, active during the 1960s and early 1970s,
has re-emerged as a terrorist force.
   In April, a bomb attack linked to the Red Army gutted a U.S.
military club in Naples, Italy. That same month, a Japanese man
suspected of being a Red Army member was arrested in New Jersey in
possession of explosives.
   ``There are reasonable grounds for believing there are a number
of his (Sensui's) colleagues remaining in the country,'' Mrs.
Defensor-Santiago said. ``We are redoubling our efforts so we can
make similar arrests.''
   Police had been searching for Sensui since he disappeared last
November from a Manila hotel where he had been under surveillance.
   Sensui was serving a prison term in Japan for murder and robbery
but was released in the hijack exchange.
   Japanese and Filipino officials said Sensui was the Red Army's
chief representative in the Philippines, where he was establishing
a base for operations throughout East Asia.
</TEXT>
