<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AudiSettlement     06-08 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Audi Settlement,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audi Agrees To Proposed Settlement In Sudden Acceleration Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi of America Inc. has offered to pay cash to
some current or former Audi 5000 owners who buy a new Audi to
settle a class-action suit charging that some of the cars were
subject to sudden and unintentional acceleration.
   The proposed settlement, reached last week, was made public
Tuesday. It proposes offering 300,000 owners of Audi 5000 sedans
with automatic transmissions payments of $300 to $2,000 if they buy
a new Audi between Sept. 1, 1988 and June 30, 1991.
   The deal would apply to Audi 5000 sedans built between 1978 and
1986.
   Audi spokesman Tom McDonald said the settlement would not be
approved until after a public hearing July 26 before Cook County
Circuit Judge Harold Siegan.
   McDonald said Audi made no admission of fault in the proposed
settlement.
   The proposed agreement, he said, states that car owners and
investigators have been unable to identify any defect common to the
vehicles that would cause unintended acceleration.
   Audi has been plagued with charges that its Audi 5000 sedans
with automatic transmissions sometimes accelerate on their own.
Despite several investigations, the cause of the problem has never
been pinpointed.
   The Center for Auto Safety, a consumer group based in
Washington, contends that at least 1,646 accidents resulting in 402
injuries and five deaths were linked to sudden acceleration when
the car was shifted from park into gear.
   The payments would be made on a sliding scale depending on the
model year of the car they owned and the date they buy a new Audi.
</TEXT>
