<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineSqueeze     06-08 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Squeeze,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Suppliers Drive Up Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian cocaine lords have cut back on
production to drive up prices, and one result may be a summer of
drug wars in the city, a prosecutor says.
   ``There won't be a lot of discussions, just boom, boom, boom,''
said Sterling Johnson, the city's special narcotics prosecutor.
``Gangs will be trying to stake out their turfs in a climate where
the supply of cocaine is decreased.''
   Johnson said the price of bulk cocaine had risen from $14,500
per kilogram to $20,000 in the past two weeks. A kilogram, or 2.2
pounds, converts to about 9,000 vials of crack that sell for up to
$10 each on the street.
   ``In one economically arrogant stroke they have created havoc,
and there are going to be a lot of innocent bystanders killed as a
result,'' Johnson said Tuesday at a forum held by a citizens
anti-crime group.
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau also said his
office was getting information that cocaine suppliers were holding
back on the narcotic.
   Andrew Maloney, U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, said that although
his office had not detected a crimp in the cocaine pipeline, he did
not dispute Johnson's information.
</TEXT>
