<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Students 2ndLd-Writethru   06-08 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Students, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0607,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Block Pro-Democracy Demonstration at Central Square</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with planned protest failing to
materialize. Pick up 5th graf pvs, `Police stood...' EDITS
thereafter to TRIM.
^By JIM ABRAMS</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student demonstration for more democracy, press
freedom and better treatment of intellectuals failed to materialize
today after armed police cordoned off Beijing's central Tiananmen
Square.
   Dozens of students gathered at the square at mid-afternoon,
apparently traveling from Beijing University and other schools, but
were thwarted by the heavy police presence and did not demonstrate
as planned.
   Police quickly intervened after a dozen students from Beijing
University gathered later at the nearby National Museum of Chinese
Revolution and complained their right of expression had been
violated.
   One person was seen being taken away by police, but the students
said he was not one of them. At dusk, police were continuing to
cordon off the square.
   Beijing authorities and the official media had warned students
that their planned 10-mile march from Beijing University to
Tiananmen was against the law and would undermine the stability
needed to carry out economic and political reform.
   Police stood at attention about 50 feet apart along the
perimeter of the 100-acre Tiananmen Square, which lies in front of
the Forbidden City, the former residence of China's emperors.
   Police reinforcements and vehicles were also deployed along side
streets around the square.
   Police, when asked about the closing said, ``We have a special
activity'' or ``I'm not sure.'' A few students sat in small groups
on the sidewalk, refusing to talk to reporters.
   Students at Beijing University, China's most prestigious center
of learning, announced plans at a late night campus rally Tuesday
for a protest march this afternoon from the campus to Tiananmen.
   It would have been the first major political protest by students
since nationwide student unrest in the winter of 1986-87.
   That outbreak of opposition to government policies prompted a
crackdown on Western liberal ideas. Hu Yaobang, a noted liberal,
was ousted as Communist Party chief for failing to take quick
action to quell the disturbances.
   The current unrest was prompted by the June 2 slaying of a
Beijing University student in an off-campus brawl.
   About 1,000 students staged an all-night march from the campus
to Tiananmen Square after the Chai Qingfeng, 22, was killed. Police
did not interfere with that demonstration, which focused on demands
for a quick resolution to the murder case and did not take up
sensitive political issues.
   Six non-students were arrested for the crime as police moved
quickly to satisfy student demands that the assailants be brought
to justice. But the protest has expanded to cover more general
complaints.
   The campus murder brought to the surface student unhappiness
over poor living conditions on campus and bleak economic prospects
after graduation for the nation's low-paid intellectuals.
   Since the killing, hundreds have gathered on the campus in the
evenings for impromptu debates on what broader lessons are to be
learned from the incident.
   Dozens of posters have been pasted up on bulletin boards
demanding democracy, a free press, an end to government corruption
and greater respect and higher salaries for intellectuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
