<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0672 06-08 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0672,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Offers Congratulations But Says His Campaign Is Still
Alive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new Jackson quotes on VP in top 6 grafs, picking
up in 5th graf pvs, But he</NOTE>
<HEAD>By RITA BEAMISH</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today his showing in the
Democratic primaries had earned him an offer of the vice
presidential spot, and not ``just in passing.''
   Jackson refused to say his presidential hopes were completely
gone, contending that ``It's not over till it's over in Atlanta''
at the Democratic National Convention. But in television interviews
he repeatedly spoke of having earned a vice presidential offer,
suggesting recognition that Dukakis had sewn up the presidential
nomination.
   ``I've earned an option to accept it or turn it down,'' Jackson
said of the No. 2 spot in an interview on CBS-TV, taped earlier.
   He added, on ABC-TV, ``Consideration does mean an offer; it does
not mean just in passing. We have earned consideration.'' He did
not say whether he would accept such an offer.
   Dukakis said on ABC, ``I don't think anyone is due an offer.''
He added, ``There are a great many people that are going to be
considered and he'll be one of them and I'm not going to rule
anybody in or out at this point.''
   Jackson said he had clearly stated his intentions regarding his
hopes for himself and demands for positions he wants the Democratic
Party to take.
   But he added, ``No one running in a process like this plays with
transparent cards. You have to have the wisdom to use your leverage
to maximize change.''
   In his concession speech Tuesday night, Jackson congratulated
Dukakis for a ``well managed and dignified campaign'' and said
their contest had been fought without rancor.
   But Jackson told supporters at an election night celebration
that the ``super delegates'' and at-large delegates are ``fluid
until they vote in Atlanta _ that's why we will continue until the
roll call in Atlanta.''
   He plans to continue traveling and making public appearances,
and said he will be contacting every super delegate and at-large
delegate for support.
   Jackson praised Dukakis, who on Tuesday gained enough delegates
to cinch the nomination, for staying ``above the fray, above the
attacks, above the meanness.''
   ``The governor has run a well-managed and dignified campaign ...
I believe that we have shown that it is possible to compete without
conflict, differ without division.''
   Jackson supporters said his losses by margins of more than
two-to-one in the California, Montana, New Jersey and New Mexico,
were expected.
   In California, where Jackson's campaign had placed heavy
resources and commitment, he had his best showing, hovering close
to 35 percent, with 69 percent of the vote counted.
   ``Anything over 30 percent is a very significant performance,''
said Bert Lance, a Jackson adviser and former confidant to
President Jimmy Carter.
   California campaign director Mike Murase said his results showed
Jackson did as expected in California and that he won several
cities in New Jersey, but was beaten badly in that state's rural
areas.
   CBS News tracking polls showed Jackson got 25 percent of the
white vote in California, one of his better showings among whites
across the nation, but only 9 percent of the white vote in New
Jersey.
   In his speech at the Los Angeles Hilton, Jackson chose to
emphasize the legacy of his campaign rather than dwell on his
continued march to the summer Democratic convention.
   He said he had successfully injected themes into the political
debate this year, most notably bringing the drug crisis to the top
of the political agenda.
   He said he has ``built a mighty coalition'' that will continue
to be heard.
   ``Together we have ushered in a new political era ... A new era
of citizen action, of concern and care, of hope and change is
beginning.''
   ``We have created a new permanent force in American politics ...
We're here to stay. Tonight is not a celebration. This is a
declaration,'' he said.
   Earlier in the day, Jackson was peppered with questions about
whether he agreed with some of his top advisers that Dukakis should
offer to make him his running mate.
   He repeated earlier statements that he deserves consideration.
But Jackson also said it's up to the convention to determine the
nominee and his running mate, hinting that would be one reason to
continue building delegate strength.
   ``The commitments made by at-large and super delegates are
non-binding until convention time, and so it's appropriate to make
appeals to delegates based upon friendship, based upon constituent
considerations,'' he told reporters.
   Jackson in recent days has increasingly stressed that the
presidential nomination process does not end with the last
primaries, but goes on to the politicking at the national
convention.
   Lance said he does not think it will be divisive for Jackson to
remain an active candidate. ``There's nothing wrong with courting
the super delegates,'' he said. ``I think Jesse Jackson has been
good for the party.''
   ``He's still got a message,'' said another supporter, former New
Mexico Gov. Toney Anaya.
   After months of a grueling breakneck campaign pace, Jackson
planned to head to San Diego today for a two-day vacation with his
family before returning home to Chicago.
</TEXT>
