<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CanadianConnection     06-08 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canadian Connection,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0712 to fix category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Large Heroin Haul in Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized 45 pounds of
heroin hidden in hollowed-out rocks coated to resemble jade and
arrested at least three people in the third-biggest drug haul in
Canadian history, authorities said.
   The street value of the haul was variously estimated by police
at $120 million and $154 million.
   Terry Langley, director of intelligence for Canada Customs, said
Tuesday that 20.5 kilograms _ more than 45 pounds _ of 87 percent
pure heroin was seized in Vancouver. Three people were arrested in
Windsor, Ontario, on Monday.
   ``It represents a tremendous amount of heroin in any man's
language, anywhere in the world,'' said Royal Canadian Mounted
Police Staff Sgt. Smokey Stovern.
   By comparison, the French Connection ring smuggled about 70
pounds of heroin into the United States from 1968 to 1971.
   Langley said customs agents in Vancouver became suspicious about
paperwork for a shipment listed as jade from Bangkok, Thailand, to
Montreal. The shipment, packed in wooden crates, was intercepted by
Canadian Customs in Vancouver May 9 after being trucked across the
border from Seattle, police said.
   The rocks turned out to be granite, not jade, and X-rays showed
a cavity in one. ``When they broke one of the rocks, they
discovered the heroin,'' Langley said.
   Langley said the smugglers had drilled out the rocks, stuffed
them with heroin, sealed the holes and then coated the rocks with a
green-tinged dirt and sand mixture to make them look like jade.
``It was a very good job,'' he said.
   Mounties removed most of the heroin and replaced it with a
lookalike powder. The Mounties followed the shipment to Montreal
and waited for someone to claim the rocks. The path eventually led
to the Windsor area.
   John Laudicina, 42, of Sandwich South Township near Windsor;
Joseph Guaragna, 23, and Antonio Zambito, 46, both of Montreal,
were arrested Monday in a raid on a home about 12 miles east of
Windsor, authorities said.
   They were charged with possession of narcotics and face a
maximum sentence of life in prison.
   ``We've never really come into contact with this type of
concealment before,'' Langley said. ``The majority of our
experience in the past has dealt with false-sided suitcases and
body packs for heroin.''
   The largest heroin haul in Canadian history was 60 kilos, or 132
pounds, in 1972, and 70 pounds were confiscated in 1986, both in
Montreal, officials said.
   A drug crackdown in the United States is diverting shipments to
Canada, and Vancouver is a prime port of entry because of its
proximity to Southeast Asia, the origin of much of the heroin and
other drugs, Langley said.
</TEXT>
