<2ND_LINE>PM-Canceled Graduation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suicide Fears Cancel Commencement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES dropped `on' in lead and `diplomas' in 2nd graf pvs.
PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The problem ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High school graduation ceremonies in an
affluent Erie suburb have been canceled over fears that some
students might try to commit suicide on stage, officials said.
   About 150 seniors were to have received their diplomas on Sunday
in the Fairview School District.
   ``The problem is if one person on this stage shoots himself or
someone else, the board is responsible'' and the board has
``evidence there is a possibility this could happen,'' district
Solicitor Frank Kroto said Tuesday at a meeting of board members
and parents.
   A senior at the school committed suicide over the Christmas
vacation in front of another student. In addition, several
administrators have received threats and are under police
protection, Kroto said.
   ``It's more than just pranks,'' Kroto said of the threats today.
   ``Certain students and certain groups of students continue to
make threats ... and there's enough substance to what they say and
what else is happening in the community to make the school board
aware of it.''
   Psychologists and psychiatrists were brought in to counsel
students and teachers after the suicide, said board President
Barbara Junker. Kroto said there were unofficial reports
circulating that more students had attempted suicide.
   ``Over the course of the past several months, we have been in
constant contact with various individuals and groups within the
student body who have threatened to cause serious disruption at
this year's graduation,'' Ms. Junker said.
   ``It is with great sorrow and regret that the board has
concluded they cannot insure you, your childrens' nor your guests'
safety at any commencement exercise,'' Ms. Junker told parents at
Tuesday's meeting.
</TEXT>
