<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ParentalLeave     06-08 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parental Leave,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watered-Down Version of Bill on Parental Leave Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of senators today announced
a watered-down version of a bill requiring private firms to offer
unpaid leave to new parents, but the bipartisan compromise failed
to draw business support.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chief sponsor of the new
measure, said he and his colleagues ``made some very tough
decisions and major changes designed to reduce the cost of the bill
and help employers plan for workers taking unpaid leave.''
   The bill introduced today by 16 Democrats and six Republicans
would require businesses with 20 or more workers to offer
job-protected parental and medical leave to employees who had been
with a firm at least a year. The original bill covered businesses
with 15 or more workers without regard for the length of service.
   Employees would be entitled to up to 10 weeks on the birth,
adoption or serious illness of a child, or 13 weeks of medical
leave for a personal illness. That compares to 18 weeks and 26
weeks, respectively, in the initial bill.
   The General Accounting Office said the new version of the plan
would cost employers less than $194 million, most of that in health
insurance premiums for employees on leave. The GAO estimated the
initial Dodd bill would have cost less than $500 million.
   The Concerned Alliance of Responsible Employers, a coalition of
corporations and business groups, said it remains opposed to ``this
well-intentioned but misguided legislation.''
   The alliance, one of many business groups fighting parental
leave bills in the House and Senate, said changes in the amount of
leave and the number of eligible workers haven't changed its
opposition to government-mandated employee benefits of any type.
   The House Education and Labor Committee last November passed a
family and medical leave act requiring firms of over 50 employees
to offer at least 10 weeks' unpaid leave to parents and up to 15
weeks for a personal illness. The bill, unlike its Senate
counterpart, also requires that leave be available to employees who
must care for a sick relative other than a child.
</TEXT>
