<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0674 06-08 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0674,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Children and Pregnant Woman Among Seven Dead in Apartment
Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with cause of fire; PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `Six of ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A faulty fan started an apartment house
blaze that killed five children, a man and a pregnant woman, the
fire chief said today.
   A woman and two other men were injured in the early-morning fire
Tuesday one floor above a used furniture store in a dilapidated
section of this southwestern Ohio city.
   The building's sole street-level access door was padlocked in
violation of the city fire code, said Fire Chief Don Lickert.
Residents apparently locked and unlocked the padlock by reaching
through a window in the door, he said.
   Lickert said a fan on the floor of the living room is believed
to have started the fire. Temperatures soared into the 90s the day
before the fire, and overnight lows fell to the 60s.
   ``We don't know if the motor froze or if the cord shorted out,''
he said. ``It will be checked by an electrical engineer.''
   Lickert said the the building's owners will receive a $100
citation for not having a working smoke detector in the apartment.
   Six of the seven victims were found beneath a boarded window
that also may have prevented their escape, the chief said. However,
there were at least two unblocked windows in the apartment, fire
officials said.
   The seventh victim, a 30-year-old man, was found in a
second-floor hallway.
   The victims died of smoke inhalation, according to Butler County
Coroner Dr. Richard Burkhardt.
   Elizabeth Blackburn, who owns the building with her husband,
Art, said she was unaware of the padlocked door on the three-story,
wooden-frame building.
   Under the city code, there should have been at least one smoke
detector for each of the three apartments on the second floor, and
another in the hallway, but Lickert said firefighters found only
one smoke detector, with no batteries.
   City inspectors had noted the lack of smoke detectors in a
previous inspection and Mrs. Blackburn had them installed,
officials said.
   Firefighters could not account for the missing detectors,
Lickert said.
   ``Routine inspections would have stopped the likelihood of
something like this happening,'' said Dr. William Karwische, city
health commissioner.
   Killed were Faye Dunham Reeseman, 18, and her 2-year-old son,
Christopher, who occupied one apartment; Mary Smith, 6; Jennifer
Miller, 4; and twins Wesley and James Miller, 2. Ms. Reeseman was
three months pregnant, the coroner said.
   Mrs. Blackburn said the Smith girl and the Millers were the
children of Karen Miller, 30, who was hospitalized in serious
condition. Ms. Miller and her children lived in a second apartment,
officials said.
   There was no indication whether Lee Cooper, whose body was found
in the hallway, was related to the other victims.
   A 24-year-old man and a 20-year-old man were hospitalized in
fair condition.
</TEXT>
