<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Drought 2ndLd-Writethru a0688 06-08 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0688,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eighty-Four of 92 Counties in Indiana Declared Disaster Areas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Indiana counties declared
disaster areas, water usage record set in Indianapolis. Picks up
2nd graf, `With pastures ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty of Indiana's 92 counties were declared federal disaster
areas today because of a drought threatening Midwest crops.
   Elsewhere, an Atlanta-area fire chief worried about hydrants
going dry, and the Art Institute of Chicago was warned to halt
daytime watering of lawns as officials in drought-gripped regions
imposed new restrictions on water use.
   Earlier this week, 24 other Indiana counties were declared
disaster areas by the federal government, thereby permitting
emergency grazing and haying on land set aside under government
programs.
   If it doesn't rain soon, farmers in southern Indiana may face
the worst spring drought in 25 years, said Jack Washburn, Harrison
County extension agent. The Midwest has had no significant rainfall
since the end of April.
   Water usage in Indianapolis on Tuesday was a record 182.15
million gallons, breaking the old mark of 175 million gallons set
the week before, water company officials said.
   With pastures deteriorating in Illinois, U.S. Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng agreed Tuesday to a request from state
congressional leaders for an emergency decree allowing farmers to
graze livestock and collect hay in 35 counties normally off-limits
under federal programs.
   Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich sent a letter Tuesday asking Lyng to
release for haying and grazing all or part of the nearly 2 million
acres the state's farmers have enrolled in a conservation program.
The action would help farmers avoid excessive feed costs caused by
drought, Perpich said.
   Crop yields are down substantially throughout Minnesota, farmers
said.
   ``Even if it does rain, it's not going to do much good unless
some lucky farmer gets a thundershower above his farm,'' said Art
Ramsdell of the National Weather Service in Paducah, Ky., just
across the Illinois line. ``We've got no relief in sight.''
   In Kentucky, state water officials said the drought is rated
severe in the horse-breeding country around Lexington, and moderate
or mild elsewhere.
   Berea, 30 miles south of Lexington, is the most parched area in
the state with rainfall 9.6 inches below normal, according to Pamla
A. Wood, supervisor of the water-quantity management section of the
state Division of Water.
   In northern Georgia, only a few showers and thundershowers were
expected today.
   In several subdivisions north of Atlanta, hydrants ran dry
Monday night. Fulton County Fire Chief James Gibson said Tuesday
there would have been serious problems had a major fire broken out.
   Restrictions on watering lawns were imposed in northern Fulton
County, Roswell north of Atlanta and Carrollton near the Alabama
border.
   In Illinois, restrictions went into effect in Chicago, suburbs
north and south of the city, Mahomet in the central section of the
state and Troy in the south.
   The Art Institute was warned it was violating restrictions by
watering lawns during the day, said Chicago Water Department
spokeswoman Cindy Gountanis. Watering is allowed only at night and
during a few hours after dawn.
   ``Our people also put about 1,000 locking caps on fire hydrants
in areas where people are prone to turning them on to get cool,''
Ms. Gountanis said. ``That can cause serious local pressure drops.''
   Chicago does not have a water shortage. However, communities
farther from Lake Michigan were reporting problems with water
pressure, she said.
   ``Normally, we have around 10 to 11 feet (of water) in our
reservoir, but we were down to 6 feet,'' said Tim Scheunke, manager
of suburban La Grange Park Village.
   Illinois corn and soybeans are beginning to show signs of stress
but ``look pretty decent'' considering what the area is going
through, said Tom Stoutenborogh, agricultural adviser in central
Illinois' Coles County.
   ``We've just got to have rain soon or we're going to go
downhill,'' Stoutenborogh added.
</TEXT>
