<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PartyLineDisconnected     06-08 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Party Line Disconnected,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bell Disconnects Its 900 Party Line Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The party's over for Connections, Illinois Bell's
party-line service.
   Bell disconnected the year-old service Tuesday, saying callers
repeatedly violated guidelines. The company filed a formal request
with the Commerce Commission to end Connections, which provided
conversation lines for groups of up to nine people, company
spokesman Tim Bannon said.
   ``However, it became clear that a small number of Connections
callers abused the service, ignored the guidelines and used the
service in ways we had not intended,'' said Robert Ligett, Bell
general manager for residence marketing.
   Bannon said that despite warnings from monitors of the service,
callers exchanged names and telephone numbers. Obscene
conversations also were reported to Bell.
   Connections was one of dozens of services offered on the 900
telephone network. Party-line services operated by independent
companies are not affected by Bell's action, the company said.
   After Connections began, with an initial charge to the customer
of 20 cents for the first minute and 8 cents for each succeeding
minute, the independent companies began offering their services at
higher rates.
   Party lines came under fire early this year when some parents
complained about huge telephone bills incurred by their teen-agers.
Under pressure, Bell began waiving those bills.
</TEXT>
