<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LostAshes     06-08 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lost Ashes,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow Wins Right To Sue TWA Over Cremated Husband's Lost Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline passenger who was forced to send
her husband's ashes through the baggage check-in rather than carry
them aboard won the right to sue Trans World Airlines for damages
after the luggage was lost.
   Dorothy T. Coughlin, 67, had sued TWA for $78,000 in 1985, but a
federal judge ruled the airline was liable for only $1,250 under a
tariff limitation.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned that decision
Tuesday and ruled that Coughlin's case should go to trial.
   The ashes were lost after a flight to Boston, where her husband
had wanted the remains buried in his family plot.
   ``He's still missing,'' said Coughlin's lawyer, Marc Levine.
``It was devastating to her. ... Can you imagine the embarrassment
and grief of literally losing your husband?''
   The appeals court ruled that a TWA ticket agent violated airline
policy by telling Coughlin she had to pack the cremated remains in
her suitcase. Airline policy says valuables should be carried
aboard.
   As a result, the airline can't expect to be protected by the
$1,250 liability limit, said the court.
   ``The cremated remains were unquestionably valuable, and there
is nothing in the record to suggest carriage of human ashes on
board was prohibited,'' they wrote.
   TWA's lawyer, James M. Derr, was out of town and could not be
reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
