<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   06-08 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0714</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   June 3
   The Columbian, Vancouver, Wash., on the Reagan-Gorbachev summit:
   Experts, observers, officials and others in the instant-wisdom
business are generally clustering under a consensus that the
recently concluded summit meetings in Moscow didn't produce much of
weight or import. ...
   Was the summit therefore not worth the considerable cost,
intense public attention and persistent anxiety that something
might go awry? ...
   Although the speeches (Reagan) had read earlier in Helsinki and
other stops on the trip toward the Kremlin were out of the old
mold, the president (saw) a new and different world in the faces of
actual Soviet citizens. ...
   Fortunately for the survival of humankind, the president got
nearer the truth when he predicted that the United States and the
Soviet Union would not go to war if the youth of both nations could
meet and mingle and get to know one another. ...
   The conversations between Reagan and Gorbachev upset the tough
guys in both camps, but the rest of us are justified in sleeping a
little easier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   Fergus Falls (Minn.) Daily Journal on the Reagan-Gorbachev
summit:
   It was something many Americans never expected to see: President
Reagan, standing in the Kremlin, saying he no longer considered the
Soviet Union to be the ``evil empire.''
   That description of the Soviet Union, made by Reagan five years
ago, has characterized U.S.-Soviet negotiations since that time.
   Reagan and Gorbachev did not emerge from their four days of
meetings with major breakthroughs on major issues, such as arms
control.
   But some events were impressive nonetheless, such as the
Soviets' willingness to consider discussion of human rights.
   Every summit need not conclude with grand results; in fact,
there is as much danger is being rushed into agreements on arms
control as there is in delaying them.
   It's not unreasonable for leaders to first talk, then reach
agreements later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   Dayton (Ohio) Daily News on Nancy Reagan-Raisa Gorbachev:
   Recent developments in Soviet-American relations have broken
down a lot of stereotypes. ...
   But the biggest change of all, no doubt, is the one brought
about through the combined efforts of Nancy Reagan and Raisa
Gorbachev.
   While their husbands have been hugging and signing and hugging
and signing and generally making nice, the first ladies have
sustained a pure, a pristine, a perfect, unhidden animosity for
each other that will not _ under any circumstances _ give way to
passing political tides.
   Once and for all Nancy and Raisa have put to rest the notion
that somehow the world would be a more peaceful place if only women
were running it.
   Way to go!
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 5
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on Reagan and Indians:
   President Reagan displayed both his ignorance about American
Indians and his ineptitude during a talk with students in the
Soviet Union.
   Sadly, he is not alone with those traits among his immigrant
compatriots in the United States. ...
   Reagan said that allowing Indians to maintain their culture on
reservations might have been a mistake.
   ``Maybe we should not have humored them in that, wanting to stay
in that kind of primitive lifestyle. Maybe we should have said:
`No, come join us. Be citizens along with the rest of us,''' the
president said.
   The remark understandably irritated Indian leaders. Indians, of
course, officially have been citizens since 1924 by an act of
Congress.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 6
   Houston Chronicle on asking H. Ross Perot to help the U.S.
Postal Service:
   Does the U.S. Postal Service realize what it has done?
   The post office has hired H. Ross Perot to review its
operations. The post office may never be the same again.
   Perot became interested in the Texas educational system and
drastic changes resulted.
   Perot attacks tasks like a buzzsaw. He cuts problems down to
size, changes their shape and trims them to fit. The federal
government isn't used to that sort of revolutionary thinking.
</TEXT>
