<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MaritalGag     06-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marital Gag,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court: In a Marriage, Private Talks Must Remain Private</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Husbands and wives may not testify in court about
their private conversations, even when both agree to do so and when
it would help their cause, Massachusetts' highest court ruled.
   In a unanimous ruling Tuesday that rejected a medical
malpractice claim, the Massachusetts Supreme Court also upheld the
common-law doctrine that prevents husbands and wives from repeating
in public what they said to each other in private.
   The justices called the rule outmoded and said they were
upholding it reluctantly, only because state law left them no
choice.
   The decision came in an appeal of a case in Middlesex Superior
Court in which a jury exonerated Dr. Garry A. Goldstein from
charges of medical malpractice brought by John Gallagher, a former
Natick resident, on behalf of his wife.
   Haline Gallagher suffered a cereberal hemorrhage in 1981 that
left her brain damaged and nearly quadriplegic. In his suit,
Gallagher charged that his wife's condition was the result of the
doctor's faulty diagnosis.
   At trial, the doctor testified that Mrs. Gallagher described her
headache as ``moderate.'' Her husband wished to testify that she
told him otherwise, but he was not allowed to take the stand.
   ``It's a tragedy,'' Gallagher's attorney, Jan Schlichtmann,
said. ``The court had the opportunity to correct a tragic
injustice.''
   Schlichtmann noted that if the Gallaghers had been living
together outside of marriage or if they had been divorced,
Gallagher could have testified.
   Under a state law enacted in 1851, any person ``of sufficient
understanding'' may testify, except for criminal defendants who
choose not to testify and a few other cases. Among them, the law
says, ``neither husband nor wife shall testify as to private
conversations with the other.''
   The court said the law means that contents of private
conversations are ``absolutely excluded.''
   Citing a scholarly law article, the court said there were five
reasons for the rule, including that a married couple has only one
interest, so no point would be served by having one spouse testify
for or against the other, and that a spouse has a ``bias of
affection'' and would not testify truthfully.
   According to Schlichtmann, Gallagher is a retired postal
inspector who has moved to Las Vegas, Nev., where he helps provide
the elaborate nursing care his wife requires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0132 </DOCNO>
