<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   06-08 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: revolutionary thinking.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   Westerly (R.I.) Sun drug seizures on the high seas:
   Along don't-they-have-anything-better-to-do lines was the Coast
Guard's reward when it seized the ... yacht Ark Royal after finding
traces of marijuana aboard.
   There was more grumping ... when the charter yacht Monkey
Business ... also was seized after the discovery of a single
marijuana cigarette.
   The Coast Guard was only the instrument of an (overzealous) new
drug law enforcement policy ... to confiscate upon finding even the
tiniest scraps of any illegal drug. ...
   In their eagerness, ... authorities overreacted (and) ignored
the cherished principle that punishment should fit the crime.
   Common sense has come to the rescue. Under new guidelines,
possession of small amounts of drugs will no longer result in
seizure. ...
   But if there is evidence that a vessel is being used for drug
trafficking, it will be seized. That is a fair and reasonable
policy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 6
   The Miami Herald on the drug war:
   The drug war has two main fronts, both extremely evil.
   At one end, drug consumption is corroding values of American
society. At the other end, drug trafficking is undermining
democratic institutions in supplier nations.
   Colombia is losing its war to a deadly combination of drug
trafficking and a violent leftist insurgency. Government officials,
judges, journalists and law enforcement officers often have had to
choose between death and surrender.
   In choosing surrender, they have increased traffickers' power
incalculably. ...
   The Reagan administration should call upon all nations of the
hemisphere to join the United States in a task force against drugs.
   This group should assess the mutual threat calmly, without
recriminations as to whether U.S. consumers or Latin American drug
suppliers are most to blame for the crisis.
   Then it should devise a common strategy _ diplomatic, military
and judicial _ for fighting the drug menace in unison.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   Morgantown (W.Va.) Dominion-Post on aid to Afghanistan:
   Soviet troops are finally on their way out of Afghanistan, and
if all of them leave _ a big if _ that tortured country will
eventually face the task of peaceful reconstruction.
   If today's anti-communist rebels become the core of a legitimate
Afghan government, the United States should play a major role in
helping that government rebuild.
   After their herioc sacrifices against Soviet imperialism, we owe
the Afghans the kind of aid that we gave our shattered allies after
World War II.
   In a trillion-dollar federal budget, surely Congress can find
the money somewhere.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 7
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on air travel safety:
   Air travel is remarkably safe in this country. That doesn't mean
it can't be improved.
   One reasonable way to do that is a proposed Federal Aviation
Agency rule which would mandate better seats on airliners.
   As you may have noticed, present accommodations are not exactly
top-notch. And in crash landings, seats often break loose, clogging
the aisles and resulting in increased deaths and injuries.
   The FAA's plan is to require replacement of all seats over the
next seven years, costing $33 million in all, or $7,200 per plane.
That's less than the price of a compact car _ and well worth it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 2
   The Jackson (Tenn.) Sun on teaching religion:
   Imagine teaching ``Paradise Lost'' without referring to its
Biblical allusions; imparting the genius of Michelangelo's Sistine
Chapel paintings without a Bible; teaching world history without
explaining the role religion has played. ...
   The organization which includes the National Education
Association and the National Council of Churches has provided
guidelines for schools to use in discussions about religion with
students.
   They don't want schools to preach, but teach _ an academic
approach to religion that's part of any healthy intellectual
endeavor. ...
   In restricting prayer in the classroom and turning down
creationism laws, the courts never meant to outlaw discussions
about religions. They meant to exclude only narrow definitions of
religion that give emphasis to one religion over another. ...
   These guidelines attempt to encourage the academic pursuit of
understanding religion that should always be welcome.
</TEXT>
