<HEAD>UNDATED: be welcome.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   The Philadelphia Inquirer on George Bush's budget plan:
   In his quest to be more than an echo of President Reagan, George
Bush has managed only a shade of difference on taxes and spending.
   In 1980, Reagan made such specific campaign promises, notably a
defense buildup and a huge tax cut, that everybody knew he couldn't
keep his promise to balance the budget in 1983.
   Bush, who is promising a balanced budget for 1993 while vowing
to cut taxes and increase some spending along the way, has stayed
vague enough to sound almost plausible.
   (But) in its theme of painless gain, Bush's semi-secret plan to
end the deficit suggests alchemy, the ancient hope of making gold
from cheap metals.
   That was a hard trick to pull off, and so is Bush's plan for
balancing the budget with tax cuts and higher spending.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 1
   North Jersey Advance, Flanders, N.J., on having banks cash
government checks:
   Proposed federal legislation that would require banks to cash
government-issued checks to the elderly and the poor should get a
quick endorsement from our representatives in the House and Senate.
   Peggy Miller, representing the Consumer Federation of America,
recently told a Senate subcommittee considering the legislation
that check cashing agencies and unlicensed community locations take
as much as 30 percent in ``fees'' to cash a personal check.
   Bankers representative August Zinsser III contended the proposal
``is premature, inappropriate and unfair to depository
institution.'' Zinsser also charged the concept would subject banks
to large fraud losses.
   Nonsense. ... The fraud rate is far below that of personal
drafts.
   Zinsser's comments suggest that banks don't want to get involved
simply because there is no financial gain for them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 4
   Stevens Point (Wis.) Journal on the Great Lakes water level:
   Not so long ago, people were worried ... about the rising levels
of the Great Lakes and the damage this was doing to buildings and
other things along the shores. ...
   All sorts of emergency measures were being proposed to lower the
levels before Chicago, Detroit and Cleveland disappeared beneath
the waves.
   After all, there was evidence that the lakes had been several
feet higher some centuries earlier, and there was speculation that
that might have been the ``normal'' level.
   Some skeptics suggested that steps to lower the lakes might be
risky and ineffective. ...
   In the meantime, the skeptics suggested, wet weather might taper
off and the problem could correct itself.
   In the paper recently there have been stories that said, in
effect, that the problem has corrected itself, at least as far as
Lakes Superior and Michigan are concerned, and the level has
dropped so far that navigation in channels and harbors is posing
some difficulties. ...
   But for the moment, we can be grateful that a couple of billion
dollars wasn't spent on crash programs to eliminate one of those
... non-problems.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 6
   The Baltimore Sun on Vietnam's withdrawal from Cambodia and Laos:
   Vietnam occupies Cambodia and Laos, threatens Thailand and
alarms China. Vietnam also costs the Soviet Union billions of
dollars in annual subsidies.
   Its economy is a shambles, its inflation legendary and its
political leadership in disarray. Agriculture is so dreadful in the
northern, more Communist, part of the country that Hanoi says three
million Vietnamese are near starvation.
   That is the context in which Hanoi announced that it would
withdraw 50,000 troops from occupied Cambodia this year, and the
remaining 50,000 to 75,000 by 1990. It also pledged to withdraw
troops from Laos. ...
   Whether the pullout is genuine remains to be seen. But Moscow
wants it. ...
   ``Cambodianization'' of Cambodia's security problem is probably
possible. The Vietnamese and government forces have succeeded
pretty well in driving Khmer Rouge and right-wing insurgents across
the Thai border. ...
   Vietnam should not only be compelled, but allowed, to keep its
word about troop withdrawal. Vietnamese, Cambodian and Laotian
people would all benefit.
</TEXT>
