<HEAD>Presbyterian Church In America Meets In Knoxville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida minister with a national
television program has been elected moderator of the General
Assembly of the Presbyterian Church in America.
   More than 700 church delegates, making up the delegaton's
governing body, convened in Knoxville on Tuesday to begin
discussing committee reports and conduct general sessions. The
convention ends Friday.
   D. James Kennedy, senior minister of Coral Ridge Presbyterian
Church in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., was elected moderator. Kennedy,
whose church has about 7,000 members, succeeds Gerald Sovereign of
Gulf Breeze, Fla., who is retiring.
   The denomination split from the Presbyterian Church in the
United States in the early 1970s. It has since grown from 240
churches to more than 1,000, officials said.
</TEXT>
