<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Harrods,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harrods Investigates Claim That Saleswomen Sold Sex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harrods department store said Wednesday it is
investigating a newspaper's allegations that some saleswomen were
selling sex to customers.
   In a front-page story, the tabloid Daily Mirror claimed that
women selling perfume at the fashionable Knightsbridge store were
earning up to $1,800 a night, mainly from wealthy customers who
slipped them their phone numbers.
   ``These are very serious allegations and we are now holding a
full investigation into the situation,'' said Harrods spokesman
Andrew Wiles.
   He said the saleswomen at the perfume counters were not directly
employed by Harrods, but worked for agencies and often moved
between top London department stores.
   Harrods, which boasts that it can provide everything from the
cradle to the grave, is a favorite shopping haunt of Princess Diana
and holds royal warrants from Queen Elizabeth II and most other
members of the royal family.
   Founded in 1849 by grocer Henry Harrod, the store has been owned
since 1985 by Egyptian entrepreneur Mohamed Fayed and his two
brothers.
</TEXT>
