<HEAD>Ariane Launch Scheduled For June 15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The demonstration launch of the Ariane-4 rocket
that was delayed by mechanical and computer problems has been
rescheduled for June 15, officials announced Wednesday.
   A statement released by Arianespace, the commercial arm of the
European Space Agency, said repairs on the rocket were completed at
the launch site in Kourou, French Guiana.
   The repair work between the payload and launcher sections of the
rocket involved rewiring an adapter. A new on-board computer was
fitted in the vehicle equipment bay and tested, the statement said.
   Ariane-4, designed to serve as the space agency's new workhorse,
will carry three satellites into orbit _ a European weather
satellite, and two telecommunications satellites, including one for
the American company Pan American Satellite.
   The launch also is designed as a demonstration for future
customers of the rocket's versatility and power.
