<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearBombs-Waste 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-08 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Bombs-Waste, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Claims Massive Radiation Contamination Around Nuclear
Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs penultimate graf to restore Resnikoff's first name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private study group says an independent
oversight agency for the nation's 16 major nuclear weapons plants
should be created because mismanagement has allowed radioactive
contamination of air, soil and water.
   The Radioactive Waste Campaign, a self-styled public interest
group based in New York City, made the recommendation in a letter
to members of Congress. The letter was released the same day the
group released a 170-page report which charged there are dangerous
levels of radioactive pollution at all 16 of the Energy
Department's main production facilities for nuclear weapons.
   The two-year study by nine researchers concluded there is ``a
pattern of gross mismanagement by the department, which is allowing
radioactivity to leak out of the sites through soil, water and air
_ in many cases intentionally.''
   Many of the problems cited by the report have long been
acknowledged by the Energy Department and have been the subjects of
several blistering reviews by the General Accounting Office. But
the independent study is the most wide-ranging report yet published
on the issue and suggests cleanup costs will exceed the Energy
Department's estimate of $100 billion.
   The Energy Department referred calls on the subject to the
office of an official who was not immediately available for comment
Tuesday.
   Among key examples of contamination cited by the report:
   _At the Hanford Reservation in southeastern Washington, billions
of gallons of radioactive water are routinely pumped into the
ground each year. An underground plume of radioactivity stretches
six miles to the Columbia River, one of the world's premier salmon
runs and an irrigation source for two states.
   _At the Savannah River Plant in South Carolina, millions of
gallons of radioactive fluids are poured into seepage basins
actually designed to leak at a steady rate. Strontium-90, which can
cause bone cancer and leukemia, is entering surface water at rates
43,000 times above the government's standard for drinking water.
The report charges further that Atlanta's water supply is
threatened by toxic chemicals from the site.
   _At the Feed Material Production Center in Fernald, Ohio,
uranium is contaminating suburban Cincinnati's water supply.
   _At the Nevada Test Site, underground nuclear explosions are
contaminating underground water supplies, and radioactive fallout
has drifted as far as Salt Lake City.
   _Plutonium, one of the most carcinogenic materials known, has
been dispersed into the air or water at weapons facilities near
Dayton, Ohio; Santa Fe, N.M.; and Denver.
   _At Oak Ridge, Tenn., where three plants are based, ``35 million
pounds of uranium are sitting in the ground, so there's uranium in
the runoff in streams and a large amount of uranium put into the
air,'' Resnikoff said. That's the largest store of uranium anywhere
in the country, he said.
   The group, in its letter to Congress, also called for an
immediate halt to dumping of radioactive wastes into the ground,
and urged the weapons sites be given top priority for clean-up. It
also called for creation of an independent oversight agency for the
weapons plants.
   The 16 sites covered by the study are:
   _Savannah River Plant, near Aiken, S.C.
   _Three facilities at Oak Ridge, Tenn.: The Y-12 plant, Oak Ridge
National Laboratory, Oak Ridge Gaseous Diffusion Plant.
   _Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant in Portsmouth, Ohio.
   _Feed Materials Production Center in Fernald, Ohio.
   _Mound Laboratories in Miamisburg, Ohio.
   _Paducah, Ky., Gaseous Diffusion Plant.
   _Pantex Plant, Amarillo, Texas.
   _Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, N.M.
   _Sandia National Laboratory, Albuquerque, N.M.
   _Rocky Flats Plant outside Denver.
   _Nevada Test Site about 100 miles from Las Vegas, Nev.
   _Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, Calif.
   _Idaho National Engineering Laboratory, Idaho Falls, Idaho.
   _Hanford Reservation in Hanford, Wash.
   Marvin Resnikoff, a nuclear physicist, said the nine who
performed the study reviewed several hundred Energy Department
documents and visited some of the sites.
   The Radioactive Waste Campaign issues a quarterly newspaper that
is sent to 13,000 members. It has five full-time staff members and
some part-time workers, Resnikoff said.
</TEXT>
