<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LawFellowship     06-08 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Law Fellowship,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Offers to Pay 125 for Pro Bono Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City's biggest law firm has announced a
$10 million program to place lawyers just out of law school in
public service organizations, where they will represent the poor in
civil cases.
   Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom said Tuesday that it will
pay the salaries of 125 young lawyers willing to spend their first
two years after law school working for the poor.
   ``This will tend to contradict the view that the established bar
has about large law firms, the view that we take from society and
do not give back,'' said an executive partner, Peter P. Mullen.
``We have been successful, and we have made money, and we have
decided to put some of it back.''
   The program also will instill in the lawyers a taste for pro
bono _ public benefit _ work, said Mullen.
   Last year Skadden, Arps was reported by The American Lawyer to
have had the highest earnings of the nation's law firms. Founded 40
years ago, it has 177 partners and 675 associates and offices in
seven U.S. cities, London and Tokyo.
   Unlike criminal defendants, poor people who are deprived of
civil or human rights are not guaranteed counsel by the
Constitution.
   The program will take the form of fellowships that pay about
$32,500 a year plus fringe benefits, comparable to second-year
salaries of federal judicial clerks, said Skadden, Arps. The firm
will also help repay student loans.
   Beginning associates at Skadden, Arps earn more than $70,000 a
year. Entering lawyers in legal-services offices earn an average of
slightly more than $25,000.
   Twenty-five lawyers, starting next June, will be named each year
for the next five years. The lawyers will be under no obligation to
return to the firm.
</TEXT>
