<HEAD>Environmentalists Clash With West Berlin Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters occupying a plot of land near the
Berlin Wall used slingshots to shoot stones and steel balls at West
Berlin police early Wednesday, injuring one of the officers,
authorities said.
   Since May 25 about 60 environmentalists have been occupying the
site, known as the Lenne Triangle, which is on the West Berlin side
of the wall but is owned by communist East Berlin.
   They are protesting plans to build a street through the area
once the site is handed over to West Berlin on July 1 under an
agreement to exchange small parcels of land near the wall.
   Some protesters stepped off the plot of land on Wednesday to
fire slingshots at officers, injuring one in the thigh, a police
spokesman said.
   Police responded with blasts from a water cannon and the
protesters retreated onto the triangle. West Berlin police cannot
legally step onto the property since it is still owned by East
Berlin.
