<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0734,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defiant Mother Seeks Sanctuary In Church Rather Than Testify</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify that she sought rather than received
sanctuary, since there is no legally recognized sanctuary. SUBS
grafs 17-19 bgng, `Sharpton this ...' with three grafs with comment
from Abrams' spokesman.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black woman who has refused to testify about
her daughter's alleged abduction and rape by six whites sought
sanctuary in a church this morning to avoid arrest for contempt of
court.
   Glenda Brawley, her two attorneys and two bodyguards entered the
Ebenezer Baptist Church in Queens about 6 a.m., according to the
Rev. Al Sharpton, who also was with Mrs. Brawley.
   ``The Rev. Timothy Mitchell invited us to be here to seek
religious asylum and sanctuary,'' said C. Vernon Mason, one of Mrs.
Brawley's attorneys. ``We're prepared to stay here as long as it
takes.''
   Police made no immediate attempt to arrest Mrs. Brawley and were
nowhere to be seen outside the modern church, which dominates the
industrial neighborhood with its orange stained-glass spire and
stainless steel cross.
   ``We don't know what we're going to do yet,'' said Sgt. Ed
Burns, a police spokesman.
   The 33-year-old Mrs. Brawley ``will not answer the judge's call
or the attorney general's call,'' Sharpton said, reading from a
statement outside the church. ``She will answer a higher call
today.''
   However, Mrs. Brawley's attorneys backed off from their earlier
contention that police could not legally arrest Mrs. Brawley inside
a church.
   Andrew Schnier of the New York State Bar Association's criminal
justice section said there was no state or common law that would
preclude authorities from executing an arrest warrant inside a
religious institution.
   The front door to the church was guarded by a well-dressed man
who screened parishioners showing up to participate in the church's
day care and senior citizen programs. Reporters were turned away.
   Mrs. Brawley's daughter, Tawana, was found Nov. 28, four days
after she had disappeared. The 16-year-old was lying dazed in a
plastic bag in Wappingers Falls, about 10 miles south of
Poughkeepsie. Her hair had been shorn, animal excrement had been
smeared on her body and racial epithets had been scrawled on her
torso.
   She said she had been attacked by six white men, one of whom
flashed a police-like badge.
   Neither Miss Brawley nor her family has cooperated with
investigators or made public more details, claiming that state
officials are involved in a racially motivated cover-up.
   On Monday, Judge Angelo Ingrassia of Dutchess County sentenced
Mrs. Brawley to 30 days in jail and fined her $250 for defying a
grand jury subpoena to testify in an investigation led by state
Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   Authorities on Tuesday issued a statewide warrant for Mrs.
Brawley, saying she was ``fair game'' for arrest.
   Mrs. Brawley took sanctuary in a black church rather than appear
before a grand jury in Poughkeepsie this morning. Her daughter was
not at the church this morning.
   ``You don't mess with black people in their churches,'' said
Mrs. Brawley's sister Juanita.
   Sharpton this morning issued a direct challenge to Abrams,
saying, ``There's nothing legally stopping you from coming in here.
So show the nation the moral beast you are and come through these
doors and arrest her.''
   Abrams spokesman Tim Gilles said: ``Whether she's arrested
today, tomorrow, Glenda Brawley is no particular threat to public
safety or public order. If they (they sheriff's office) were to
wait a few days, we have no objection to that.''
   Abrams and Gilles were in Poughkeepsie where the grand jury
probe continued.
   Sharpton reiterated claims of a cover-up this morning and called
again for Abrams to step aside and for Gov. Mario Cuomo to appoint
a special prosecutor. He also hinted that Miss Brawley would
cooperate with an ``impartial prosecutor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
