<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SoulPatrol     06-08 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Soul Patrol,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Founder Says `Soul Patrol' Makes School Grounds Safer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student ``Soul Patrol'' has succeeded in
stopping neighborhood bullies from victimizing students outside a
middle school.
   The 25-member Soul Patrol was formed at Joy Middle School, in an
inner-city east side neighborhood.
   ``There used to be a time when there would be about 10 or 12
guys outside the school building waiting on kids to come outside so
they could jump them,'' William Howard, a Detroit Urban League
worker who established the program in 1986 after seeing a student
robbed, said recently.
   Each day, patrol in yellow jackets and caps patrol the school
grounds, using walkie-talkies and whistles. The students get help
from parents, Urban League volunteers and police Officer Anthony
Thompson, who is assigned to the school.
   ``Before the program started, I used to have to take in at least
one or two kids a day for delinquent behavior, but in the past few
months, I haven't had to take anyone in,'' Thompson said.
</TEXT>
