<2ND_LINE>PM-Refinery Explosion,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant Explosion Forces Closure of Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at a Chevron
refinery today injured up to six employees and shot flames 150 to
200 feet in the air, witnesses and officials said.
   A pump station caught fire about 9:40 a.m. and spread to some
small storage tanks nearby, Chevron spokesman Art Spencer said. The
pump station moves unfinished gasoline from the manufacturing
section to storage area, he said.
   ``There is concern for the fire spreading, but we do not feel it
will spread to the manufacturing section because it is divided'' by
a bayou and a highway, Spencer said.
   The cause of the blast was not immediately known.
   He said four workers were taken to Park Place Hospital. The
injuries, he said, were not serious. However, a hospital
spokeswoman said six employees were being treated for undetermined
injuries.
   ``The fire is emitting an awful lot of black smoke into the air
but it does not have any environmental impact,'' Spencer said.
