<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TeenWorries     06-08 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen Worries,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Teens Worry About AIDS, Paying For College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three out of 10 teen-agers say they have
changed their sexual practices because of AIDS, and they are as
worried about the disease as they are about paying for college,
according to a study released Wednesday.
   The survey, which looked at the top concerns of junior and
senior high school students, revealed that money, AIDS and making
the wrong decisions about the future are their biggest worries.
   And while the teens were generally happy with their own lives,
they were ``fairly pessimistic about the world around them,''
especially about social problems and the country's future, said Jay
Friedland of Guideline Research, which conducted the study for the
American Home Economics Association.
   For example, 58 percent do not think there will be an end to
racial discrimination in the United States in their lifetimes; 42
percent think there will be nuclear war in their lifetimes; and 62
percent think their lives will be harder than those of their
parents.
   The study, funded by Chesebrough-Pond's Inc. and Lever Brothers
Co., surveyed 510 high school juniors and seniors nationwide
between March 25 and April 5. Quotas were established so that a
sample of 300 teens selected at random reflected Census Bureau
breakdowns of student population by sex, race and ethnicity. A
supplemental group of 210 included only blacks and Hispanics.
   The average age of the respondents was 17, and the survey had a
margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   The teen-agers were asked how concerned they were about 32
issues. Topics that drew responses of ``extremely'' or ``very''
were considered top concerns.
   Being able to pay for college was a top concern for 39 percent
of the teens surveyed, as was the fear of contracting AIDS.
Thirty-four percent listed making the wrong decisions about the
future and not being able to change them as a top concern.
   Fear that the United States ``is steadily going down hill''
greatly concerned 33 percent; and the prospects of a nationwide
depression worried 30 percent. Not earning enough money to enjoy
the better things in life was a top concern for 29 percent.
   Eleven percent said they know someone who has acquired immune
deficiency syndrome or who has died of it. Thirty percent said the
statement ``I have changed my sex life because of fear of getting
AIDS'' applied to them.
   The teens were not asked to elaborate, or whether in fact they
were sexually active. The survey thus did not reveal whether fear
of AIDS led them to elect abstinence or to take precautions when
having sex.
   The data showed that high school juniors and seniors are keenly
aware that drugs, alcohol and sexual abuse are issues that affect
their friends. But they are less likely to admit to having such
problems themselves.
   Fifty-eight percent of those surveyed have a friend who has
thought of or committed suicide, and 53 percent said some of their
friends were ruining their lives because of drugs. Forty-six
percent report alcohol abuse among their friends, and 32 percent
claim to have a friend who has been sexually abused.
   But only 8 percent or less admitted that they have drug or
alcohol problems or have thought about suicide.
   Despite their worries, 65 percent of those surveyed said they
believe that science will find cures for serious diseases such as
AIDS and cancer in their lifetimes.
   And they were optimistic about the future _ 78 percent expect to
attend college and 94 percent believe having a job they enjoy will
be an important part of their lives.
   Dr. Gail House, the association's executive director, said the
survey will be used to develop courses to help teens with economic,
health, emotional and other life problems. The American Home
Economics Association represents more than 27,000 home economists,
including educators, dieticians and others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CoyoteWarning     06-08 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coyote Warning,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventor's Gadget Uses Siresn, Strobe Lights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coyote may lose his appetite for mutton if
he attacks sheep protected by a new collar that wards off predators
with sirens, strobe lights and an ear-piercing,
ultra-high-frequency signal, the inventor says.
   A patent is pending for Kevin Parmely's Sonic Spook collar, a
2.5-pound device activated by sudden movement.
   Parmely, who raises sheep, said he initially began to develop a
stationary warning device but realized it would be difficult to
keep sheep near one.
   ``I decided I needed a device that goes on the sheep, and it
took three years to finally get it small enough,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``You can't have a sheep carrying around a big
battery.''
   ``When the coyotes come into sheep, the sheep jump up and it
activates the sirens and flashing lights,'' he said. The warnings
continue for 10 seconds, and the unit resets itself in 10 minutes,
he said.
   In addition to a strobe light, each collar emits either an
audible warning, such as a siren, or a high-frequency sound that is
said to be painful to coyotes, he said.
   The collar contains an electronic eye that shuts it off in the
daytime, since about 95 percent of coyote attacks occur at night,
Parmely said.
   The collars are sold in sets of five, which is adequate to
protect about 200 sheep, Parmely said. Each set costs $625, he
said. The first shipment has been sold to sheep producers in South
Dakota, Parmely said.
   The combination has been shown to keep a coyote away from sheep
for an average of 93 days, Parmely said.
   The state Agriculture Department helped Parmely get started by
purchasing 80 percent of his $29,000 bank loan.
   ``It was unique and innovative enough so we could get involved
in it,'' said Randy Englund, rural development officer in the
department. Englund said Parmely also has obtained backing from
private interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
