<DOCNO> AP880608-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece     06-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Denies Tensions with Greece Over Extradition Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department denied Wednesday that its
relations with Greece are tense over Greek reluctance to extradite
a Palestinian suspected of the terrorist bombings of two U.S.
airliners.
   U.S. officials have said privately that Greece is stalling on an
American request to extradite Mohammed Rashid, who is wanted in
connection with an explosion aboard a Pan American World Airways
plane in Hawaii in 1982 and a blast aboard a Trans World Airlines
jet over Greece in 1986.
   They said Rashid was arrested recently in Greece on the basis of
U.S. intelligence information.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said, ``In general
... our bilateral relations with Greece, including cooperation on
anti-terrorism policy, continue to be conducted normally.''
   She declined to comment on details of the Rashid case, saying
only that ``it's our practice to share information with our allies,
including Greece, on the issue of terrorism. We do not discuss the
specifics of such sharing of information.''
   U.S. officials said privately that Greece has told the United
States it does not have sufficient evidence against Rashid to
warrant extraditing him, and asked for additional information.
   U.S. Ambassador Robert Keeley met with Greek Prime Minister
Andreas Papandreou in Athens last Thursday to discuss the case.
Greek officials have refused to comment publicly on the case or to
say whether they are holding Rashid.
   Mrs. Oakley said the State Department's senior counter-terrorism
official, L. Paul Bremer, went to Athens recently and had
``fruitful discussions on anti-terrorism issues.''
   Privately, U.S. officials say Bremer took the opportunity of his
visit to press the U.S. demand for Rashid's extradition.
   The flap over Rashid comes at a delicate juncture in U.S.-Greek
relations. The two countries are negotiating the renewal of leases
for four American military bases in Greece that expire Dec. 31.
   Papandreou threatened last year to call off the negotiations
when the United States accused his government of being lax toward
terrorism.
   The United States backed off its accusations in a formal letter
to Papandreou, and the talks resumed.
   ``There are no new tensions in our relationship,'' Mrs. Oakley
said Wednesday.
   Rashid is reportedly a member of the Abu Nidal group, which is a
Palestinian splinter group based in Libya.
   Bremer said in recent interviews that Abu Nidal has stepped up
his group's terrorism activities recently, sometimes as a surrogate
for Libya.
</TEXT>
