<DOCNO> AP880608-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChinaProtest Bjt   06-08 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China Protest, Bjt,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Thwart Student Rally In Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police thwarted a student march and pro-democracy
rally planned for Beijing's huge main square Wednesday and
dispersed a dozen students who gathered nearby to complain. Armed
officers ringed the square until 11 p.m.
   Nearly 1,000 students rallied late into the night on the Beijing
University campus 10 miles away, but speakers urged them to press
their demands through ``proper channels.'' No plans were made to
try the march another day.
   ``I wouldn't join a demonstration. Now isn't the time,'' said
one student. Another declared: ``Quite frankly, we are afraid.''
   Students began arriving at Tiananmen Square in midafternoon,
apparently traveling singly from Beijing University and other
schools, but found the police were there in force.
   At the National Museum of Chinese Revolution, on one side of the
square, about a dozen students from Beijing University complained
in late afternoon that their right of expression had been violated.
Police quickly intervened.
   Officers were seen taking one person away, but the students said
he was not from their group.
   City authorities had told students the 10-mile march they
planned for Wednesday afternoon from Beijing University to
Tiananmen, the symbolic political center of China, was illegal and
would endanger the stability necessary for economic and political
reforms.
   Hundreds of students at China's most prominent university milled
around posters calling for democracy, human rights and better
conditions for underpaid intellectuals, but seemed undecided about
what to do.
   Students at both the campus and Tienanmen said school
authorities had called meetings to warn students of consequences,
including arrest, if they went ahead with the march.
   At the 100-acre square, police stood at attention about 50 feet
apart around the perimeter. Several dozen students in small groups
waited nearby until early evening.
   One student said: ``I came to watch, but I won't join in because
students have no power. What good is it?''
   Police reinforcements and vehicles were posted in side streets
around the square, which is framed by the Great Hall of the People,
Mao Tse-tung's mausoleum, the Museum of Revolution and the old
Imperial Palace.
   Tourists usually stroll through the square, but were ordered out
at 1 p.m. and milled around the edges, waiting for something to
happen.
   Posters promoting the rally had been displayed on the Beijing
University campus for several days, but those put up Wednesday had
a more sober tone.
   ``People of Beijing University, think three times,'' one
advised. ``If Beijing University moves one step, all of China will
shake.''
   Several others also echoed official statements published by the
government press Wednesday urging students to maintain the nation's
stability and unity so China can continue the reforms of the past
decade.
   One poster said bluntly: ``We should march, but we should also
obey the law.''
   A mass march would have been the first major political protest
by students since pro-democracy demonstrations in the winter of
1986-87 that led to a crackdown on Western liberal ideas. Hu
Yaobang, a noted liberal, was ousted as Communist Party chief for
failing to quell the disturbances quickly.
   The latest unrest stems from the death June 2 of a Beijing
University student who was beaten by a gang off-campus.
   About 1,000 students joined an all-night march from the campus
to Tiananmen Square after the death of Chai Qingfeng, 22. Police
did not interfere with that protest, which focused on demands for a
quick resolution to the murder case and did not address sensitive
political issues.
   Six non-students were arrested, satisfying student demands for
quick justice, but the protest expanded to such complaints as poor
living conditions on campus and bleak economic prospects for
intellectuals after graduation.
   Since the killing, hundreds have gathered on the campus in the
evenings for impromptu debates. Posters appeared on bulletin boards
demanding democracy, a free press, an end to government corruption
and greater respect and higher salaries for intellectuals.
   Beijing University students marched to Tiananmen Square in 1919
to protest Japan's occupation of part of China. The result was a
nationalist fervor from which the Communist Party emerged in the
1920s.
   Since then, Beijing students often have flocked to Tiananmen to
celebrate important events or voice political concerns.
</TEXT>
