<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrasslandsFire     06-08 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grasslands Fire,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Battle Wildfire In Montana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAME DEER, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of firefighters today battled a
wind-driven blaze on the Northern Cheyenne Indian reservation that
has blackened nearly 18,000 acres of drought-stricken prairie,
authorities said.
   About 750 people from Montana, Wyoming, Idaho and the Dakotas
used picks, shovels and small napalm-like bombs for triggering
backfires to control the three-day-old blaze east of the Custer
Battlefield National Monument.
   Michelle Ravnikar, a fire information officer, said that the
situation was ``looking pretty good'' because of progress made in
laying down fire lines. She said that officials expect to contain
the fire by Thursday night.
   Firefighters had completed 22 of the 28 miles of fire lines
needed to encircle the blaze, she said.
   No homes or businesses were threatened by the fire, but
officials were urged caution by motorists on smoke-covered roads.
   Airspace above the fire was closed to aircraft because of poor
visibility and to make room for helicopters helping firefighters.
Smoke could be seen 60 miles away in Hardin.
   The fire started near the Crazy Head Campgrounds about 14 miles
east of Lame Deer. Investigators believed that the fire was
man-caused.
   Helicopters dropped ping-pong balls loaded with flammable liquid
to start backfires on the edges of the blaze. Backfires char the
area in front of the fire and deprive it of fuel.
</TEXT>
