<HEAD>Consumer Federation Honors Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest consumer group has
selected four people for distinguished service awards in consumer
protection.
   The awards will be presented Thursday by the Consumer Federation
of America, a coalition of more than 200 national, state and local
consumer groups.
   Being honored are:
   _Sen. Robert T. Stafford, R-Vt., who helped lead the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee to achievements in
environmental improvement, including battling toxic waste and
asbestos in schools and improving the safety of drinking water.
   _Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., for his work to ensure enforcement of
food and drug safety laws.
   _Dr. Stewart M. Lee of Geneva College in Pennsylvania, who has
served the consumer movement at the local, state and national level
for three decades. He has been active in the American Council on
Consumer Interests, Consumer's Union, the President's Consumer
Advisory Council and the U.S. delegation to the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development.
   _Erin Moriarty of CBS News, who has reported on consumer affairs
since 1980, including work in Cleveland, Baltimore and Chicago.
