<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Disarmament 2ndLd-Writethru   06-08 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Disarmament, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0805,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Proposes Permanent Nuclear Test Moratorium If US
Agrees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. ambassador's comments.
Pick up 3rd graf pvs: ``Shevardnadze also...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
announced today that the Soviet Union would observe a permament
moratorium on nuclear testing if the United States also agrees.
   In a speech to a special General Assembly session on
disarmament, Shevardnadze also declared that the Soviet Union would
announce the presence or absence of nuclear weapons on naval ships
calling on foreign ports, if the United States and Western allies
do the same.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters later praised the speech as
``hopeful, useful and good.''
   ``It was an extremely interesting new speech, it broke a lot of
new ground and it is deserving of study,'' the permanent U.S.
representative said.
   Shevardnadze also said the Geneva accords for the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan are being violated, undermining
confidence in other peace talks.
   The Soviet official did not identify the United States or
Pakistan as the offending parties, but his implication was clear.
   ``When one party observes its obligations under the Geneva
agreements while the other party is violating them, this naturally
causes us to have doubts about our partner and to refuse to trust
him,'' he said.
   The United Nations helped negotiate a pact, signed in Geneva,
which calls for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Red Army troops
from Afghanistan within a year, and the repatriation of millions of
Afghan refugees who fled to Pakistan and Iran.
   In his 45-minute address, Shevardnadze called for reductions in
conventional arms in Europe, including cutbacks by both sides of
about 500,000 soldiers each.
   His speech included a call for a ban on space weapons, a
chemical weapons ban, a U.N. naval force and a central role for the
United Nations in verifying disarmament.
   The Soviet Union announced a unilateral testing moratorium in
August 1985, the United States refused to go along and the
moratorium ended 1{ years later.
   The highlight of the speech appeared to be a renewal of the
Soviet offer.
   ``Our invariable position on a nuclear testing moratorium is
still valid,'' Shevardnadze said. ``On the basis of reciprocity
with the United States, we are ready to reintroduce and to observe
it, this time not for a year and a half, but for all times.''
   Without limiting and banning nuclear tests, he said, it is
difficult or impossible to prevent the global spread of nuclear
weapons.
   The Soviet Foreign Minister repeated his call for creation of
U.N. naval forces comprised of forces of the permanent members of
the Security Council: the Soviet Union, the United States, Britain,
China and France.
   On port calls, Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union was ``ready to
announce the presence or absence of nuclear weapons aboard its
naval ships calling at foreign ports.''
   The United States consistently has refused to make disclosures
about port calls by nuclear-armed ships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TBOutbreak     06-08 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TB Outbreak,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outbreak of TB Revealed in Nevada Rest Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tuberculosis outbreak at a rest home
has infected 23 employees, 19 patients and four people working at a
nearby hospital, prompting the state to consider rules to prevent a
recurrence.
   The outbreak at Ruby Mountains Manor in Elko, which has been
known to health authorities since January, resulted in its
temporary decertification although Health Division Administrator
Larry Matheis said Tuesday all people involved have been treated
and ``the situation now is completely under control.''
   Matheis said the outbreak is the first serious problem involving
TB in Nevada in 25 years, the first of its sort in a nursing home
anywhere in the nation in recent years, and follows a national
resurgence of the disease.
   Ruby Mountains, headed by John Watson of Sparks, is operating
under a provisional license, has passed one inspection, and is due
for a follow-up in about two weeks, Matheis added.
   Matheis said federal Medicare and Medicaid funds have been cut
off although state Medicaid payments are still being made to the
facility. He also said no new admissions are being allowed at this
time. There are about 70 patients at the home.
   Four of the cases are being treated as confirmed TB while the
others are viewed as infections. All those involved have undergone
treatment, Matheis said.
   A Board of Health hearing July 20 will deal with a proposed
regulation requiring all nursing homes admissions to be tested for
TB as a result of the outbreak at Ruby Mountains Manor.
   Gov. Richard Bryan had been asked to sign emergency rules but
instead suggested Matheis send a letter, being mailed this week, to
all nursing homes requesting the tests and a records review to
ensure all employees have had annual TB tests.
   Dr. Debra Brus, who headed a Health Division inspection team
sent to Ruby Mountains Manor, said one woman still working at the
facility is a confirmed TB sufferer and may have been the source of
the infections _ but hadn't had a TB test since 1986.
   ``Probably, had that test been performed, this might not have
happened,'' said Brus. But she added it's ``pure, unadulterated
baloney'' to suggest the state didn't react quickly enough to the
problem.
   One elderly patient at the home is infected and near death, but
Brus said she was advised by the nursing home's medical director
that old age, heart trouble and other ailments rather than the TB
infection are the main causes for the patient's condition.
</TEXT>
