<DOCNO> AP880608-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Export-ImportBank     06-08 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Export-Import Bank,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba, Ethiopia Loan Repayments Doubted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects of loan repayments by the
governments of Cuba and Ethiopia are doubtful but prospects of
repayment from the Soviet Union are excellent, President John A.
Bohn Jr. of the government's Export-Import Bank told senators
Wednesday.
   Bohn said he expects repayment only if there is a change in the
Cuban government.
   Ann Frey, a press officer at the bank, said Cuba owes it more
than $92 million in principal and interest. The debt is from loans
made before President Fidel Castro came to power.
   Ms. Frey said Ethiopia owes more than $17 million in loans and
guarantees and has not received any additional loans since 1984.
Bohn said he sees no chance of repayment under the present system
there.
   The Soviet Union owes more than $142 million, having already
paid most of the money the bank lent it in 1973 and 1974, and is
continuing repayments on schedule, according to the bank's figures.
   These loans are carried on the bank's books as assets. So are
loans made to the Nationalist government on mainland China before
the communist government drove it to Taiwan in 1949.
   Bohn told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on foreign
operations that the bank lost $461 million in the year that ended
last Sept. 30 and expects to lose $350 million in the current year.
He explained the losses as due largely to loans made at low
interest rates in the early 1980s while the bank itself had to
borrow at higher rates.
   The bank sees its job as lending money, at subsidized interest
rates when necessary, to promote sales of U.S. industry _ largely
to Third World purchasers. It competes with similar lenders in
other exporting countries, especially France, Japan, Britain and
Canada.
   It is asking Congress for authority to lend another $705 million
in the year beginning Oct. 1 and to guarantee $10.2 billion in
loans by commercial banks. Bohn submitted a table showing the bank
expects to make money again in the year 2008, as it did until 1982.
   The General Accounting Office, which watches over spending for
Congress, wants the bank to set up a reserve to cover losses, as
commercial banks do. Bohn declined that proposal again Wednesday.
   ``We would have to make determinations that certain countries
are not likely to repay,'' he said.
   ``Although we would attempt, of course, tokeep such information
secret... (it) would almost certainly become public knowledge. This
could not only impair U.S. bilateral relations but could also send
the wrong signal to debtor countries and in fact may encourage them
not to repay their debts.''
   Another witness, Nancy D. Frame, is acting director of another,
smaller U.S. government effort which promotes both trade and aid
objectives: the trade and development program of the International
Development Cooperation Agency.
   She testified that since 1980 it has promoted more than $1.2
billion worth of U.S. exports and expects to generate another $7
billion worth. The program has had $128 million in appropriations
over that period and is seeking another $20.4 million for fiscal
1989.
   By far the agency's biggest activity has been in China, where it
spent $15.7 million between 1981 and 1987. It spent $7.6 million in
Thailand, $4.6 million in the Philippines and $4.3 million in
Indonesia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JapaneseRedArmy     06-08 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japanese Red Army,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Question Alleged Japanese Red Army Member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines deported an alleged terrorist to
Japan on Wednesday and police questioned him about whether the
Japanese Red Army plans attacks at the Olympic Games in South
Korea, a police official said.
   Hiroshi Sensui, 51, was arrested Tuesday at a Manila hospital,
where he was said to have undergone plastic surgery to conceal his
identity. He was deported Wednesday afternoon and about 100 police
stood guard when he arrived at Tokyo's Narita airport.
   ``He kept silent throughout the brief interrogation upon his
arrival,'' said the police official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Mirian Defensor-Santiago, the Philippine immigration
commissioner said in Manila that preliminary reports from security
officials in the region indicated ``the terrorists have initiated
activity expected to culminate in the Olympic Games.''
   She said evidence indicated the Japanese Red Army, formed in
1968, had planned to use Manila as a base for operations during the
Olympics, scheduled for Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in Seoul, South Korea.
   Authorities in Japan and Manila have said Sensui was the Red
Army's chief representative in the Philippines. The Japanese police
official said Sensui needs some rest and sleep,'' and interrogation
would resume Thursday.
   He would not say what charges the man would face beyond that of
using a false passport in Manila. The official said when and how
Sensui went to the Philippines was not clear.
   Mrs. Defensor-Santiago said the suspect had lived there for
several years under the assumed name Hiroshi Yamaguchi and
initially denied being Sensui. Officials said fingerprints
confirmed his identity.
   Police say Sensui was released from prison in 1977 in exchange
for hostages aboard a Japan Air Lines plane the Japanese Red Army
hijacked in Dacca, Bangladesh.
   Recent arrests of several alleged members of the terrorist group
have caused speculation that it had resumed operations after being
dormant for several years, and might be planning attacks at the
Olympics.
   Authorities learned that Sensui was in the Philippines after
Osamu Maruoka, alleged to be No. 2 in the Japanese Red Army, was
arrested in Japan in November, police said.
   After Maruoka's arrest, investigators found he had contacts in
Manila with Sensui and Sasaki Norio, an explosives expert alleged
to be a member of the group, officials said.
   Police said they also found Maruoka had a one-way airplane
ticket to Seoul the following month.
   On May 6, Yasuhiro Shibata, an alleged Red Army member linked to
the hijacking of a Japan Air Lines plane to North Korea in 1970,
was arrested in Tokyo. Yu Kikumura, another suspected Red Army
member, was arrested in the United States in April on charges of
possessing explosives.
   Italian police are seeking two more alleged Red Army members _
Junzo Okudaira and Fusako Shigenobu, said to be the terrorist
group's leader _ for suspected involvement in a car bomb attack in
Naples in April.
   At its peak, the Japanese Red Army had only about 300 members,
police say, and crackdowns in Japan forced it to move to the Middle
East. It gained notoriety with an attack at Tel Aviv's Lod Airport
in 1972 in which 28 people were killed, including two of the three
terrorists involved.
</TEXT>
