<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-08 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welcome to Kidsville USA, where
youngsters are mayor, bankers, even inmates.
   Karen Harris devised the community within her classroom at
Brentwood Elementary School to teach her kindergarteners cash flow,
debts and the law of supply and demand.
   ``We have a mayor and city council members, others own stores
and sell merchandise,'' said Ms. Harris, who won first place
Tuesday in Fayetteville's Economic Education Award program.
   The program is sponsored by the Fayetteville Area Chamber of
Commerce and the Fayetteville State University Center for Economic
Education. It recognizes teachers who use innovative methods for
economics education.
   Kidsville USA operates on construction paper currency. Pupils
are paid $5 each week for ``work'' in a store or bank or office.
   ``They can borrow money from the bank to buy a car, or write
checks. It's actually a community at work,'' Ms. Harris said.
``They realize that if they don't make sound decisions it will cost
them money. And it could also cost them a visit to the jail.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALPARAISO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Porter-Starke Services Inc. and the
Valparaiso YMCA wanted to put 160 acres of farmland to good use, so
they came up with the idea of a turkey farm, an idea that appears
to be, well, a turkey.
   Only two families have signed up for the program, and at least
20 were needed by Wednesday's deadline.
   For $18, a family gets a 1-day-old turkey chick. For the next
five months, each family takes turns feeding all the chicks.
   After five months, the 16- to 35-pound turkeys are sent to a
commercial processor, where they are dressed and returned to each
family in time for Thanksgiving dinner.
   ``I talked to some people who said, well, I'm not going to eat
something I raised,'' said Dick Carlson, executive director of the
YMCA. ``It's a shame. I think it's kind of a neat project myself.''
   Carlson said he may extend the deadline.
</TEXT>
