<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     06-08 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel ,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Reportedly Beaten To Death By Israeli Troops, Four Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab died after being beaten by Israeli
troops, a hospital official said Wednesday, and the army reportedly
stepped up protection for Israeli-appointed Arab officials after
the stabbing of a West Bank mayor.
   Soldiers, meanwhile, shot and wounded four Palestinians on
Wednesday during clashes in a West Bank refugee camp and village,
hospital officials said. The army confirmed three of the shootings.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin toured the Gaza Strip on
Wednesday and told residents who complained about the presence of
soldiers that troops would leave if Arab protests calmed down.
   ``We don't want to keep the army here any more than we have
to,'' Rabin said on Israel radio. ``If there is quiet, there will
be fewer problems, fewer beatings.''
   Doctors at Shifa hospital in Gaza City said Hussein Jama Abu
Jallalah, 19, died late Tuesday after being beaten in the head a
day earlier in the Jabaliya refugee camp, a frequent site of
violence. The army confirmed the death but said it was
investigating the circumstances.
   Dr. Ahmed Yassih said Abu-Jallalah was admitted to the hospital
with a ``very bad head injury. He had contusions and lacerations
all over the body, and fractures on the left leg and right hand.''
He said the young man died at Tel Aviv's Tel Hashomer Hospital,
where he was transferred after suffering a brain hemorrhage.
   The death raised to 202 the number of Palestinians killed during
the six-month Arab uprising. Two Israelis have also died.
   In scattered violence Wednesday, troops shot and wounded a
stone-throwing Arab protester in the Balata refugee camp near
Nablus and two others in the nearby village of Beit Farouk, the
army said. Officials at the Al Ittihad hospital said three were
wounded in Beit Farouk.
   The army imposed a curfew on the West Bank village of Bet Ur et
Tahta after an Israeli motorist was injured there in a firebomb
attack, the military command said.
   The Hebrew daily Maariv said the West Bank military government
was stepping up protection for Israeli-appointed Arab officials
after a stabbing attack Tuesday on Hassan Tawil, the 74-year-old
mayor of El Bireh north of Jerusalem. Tawil was reported in stable
condition Wednesday after suffering a stab wound to the heart.
   Underground leaders of the Arab uprising have repeatedly
demanded that Israeli-appointed mayors and other appointed
officials quit their posts, threatening retaliation if they don't.
   An army spokesman would not comment on reports of stepped up
protection for Arab officials, but Hanna Atrash, the elected Arab
mayor of the West Bank town of Beit Sahour, said eight soldiers in
two jeeps offered to protect him Wednesday morning.
   He said he refused help from the soldiers and added: ``I also
told them they are hurting me more than they are helping me.''
   In Tel Aviv, a group of Israelis and Palestinians on Wednesday
announced plans to repair houses in the West Bank village of Beita,
where the Israeli army destroyed homes after a teen-aged Jewish
girl was killed in a confrontation with Arab residents April 6.
   Jewish settlers initially claimed the girl was shot by an Arab.
But an army report later showed Tirza Porat was accidentally shot
by an Israeli guard who accompanied Jewish teen-agers on a hike in
the area.
   ``We felt it was one of the most outrageous incidents in the
whole uprising in which the army retaliated unnecessarily,''
Professor Yosef Grajinsky, a member of the new Committee for Beita,
said of the house demolitions.
   The committee said it sent nine architects to assess damage in
the village and also hired lawyers to represent residents jailed
after the incident.
   Azmet Bishara, a Palestinian member of the group, said the
architects found $160,000 in damage done to 20 houses in the course
of the destruction of 14 other homes. Israel has frequently
demolished homes in retaliation for attacks on its soldiers or
Israeli civilians.
</TEXT>
