<HEAD>Presbyterians To Consider Paper On Pornography</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with election of moderator,
edits to conform. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The pornography...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. C. Kenneth Hall was elected today to
lead the nation's largest Presbyterian denomination through its
bicentennial year.
   Hall, a 63-year-old minister from Butler, Pa., was selected over
four other candidates on the first ballot by the 630 commissioners,
or delegates, to the 200th General Assembly of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A.).
   Hall will be chief spokesman for the 3 million-member
denomination for the following year.
   Hall received 319 votes. Other candidates were the Revs.
Juventino R. Ballesteros, 54, of Savannah, Ga., 133 votes; James R.
Struthers, 66, of Stillwater, Okla., 30; Roy H. Zuefeldt, 63, of
Abilene, Texas, 79; and James Spalding, 66, professor of religion
at the University of Iowa, 64.
   After today's election, the commissioners moved into committee
meetings to discuss various issues, incluing a report saying
pornography debases God's gifts and is ``far from the mutual sexual
delight depicted biblically.''
   ``Pornography: Far From the Song of Songs'' recommends, among
other things, that members of the church boycott materials and
companies that market or produce pornographic materials.
   The pornography report's title refers to ``The Song of
Solomon,'' an Old Testament book that contains some of the most
sexually explict language in the Bible.
   Some critics, however, say the paper does not go far enough in
condemning pornography.
   Sharlyn Stare, who heads a special Presbyterian committee on
pornography in Cincinnati, said the ``recommendations need to be
more aggressive to moving people to support prosecution of illegal
obscenity and child pornography.''
   Other reports include a paper entitled ``Christian Obedience in
a Nuclear Age,'' which declares that nuclear war and the theory of
nuclear deterrence are immoral and calls on Presbyterians to be
more active in the fight for peace.
   While the paper stops short of calling for a denominational
position of civil disobedience, it calls for the support of those
who feel compelled to engage in resistance and recommends
establishing a fund to support resisters.
   Anti-abortion groups within the church are also hoping to
persuade the commissioners to toughen the church's stance against
abortion.
   The reports will be considered by the commissioners at committee
meetings on Thursday and Friday. The commissions reassemble
Saturday to deal with the reports.
   The meeting runs through next Wednesday.
   As part of the anti-abortion effort, Presbyterians Pro-Life
sponsored a visit here Tuesday by Mother Teresa of Calcutta, who
called abortion the ``greatest destroyer of love and peace.''
   ``If I had power, I would open a jail and put every single
doctor in jail for killing life, killing a child, a gift of God,''
said the Nobel Peace Prize winner who is noted for her work with
the poor.
   ``Every single child, every unborn child in the womb, is
precious to Him, is created for greater things, to love and be
loved,'' she said in a speech to about 600 people, including
commissioners and St. Louis Roman Catholic Archbishop John L. May.
   The Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) has condemned abortion as a
method of birth control, but said the decision rests with the
woman, her physician and God.
   Presbyterians Pro-Life wants the church to condemn abortion in
all instances except where the mother's life is in danger.
   The denomination was formed by the 1983 merger of the United
Presbyterian Church in the United States of America, which was the
principal denomination in the North, and the Presbyterian Church in
the United States, which was the principal southern body. The
merger healed a split over slavery stemming from the Civil War.
   There are seven smaller Presbyterian groups in the United States.
</TEXT>
