<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CalProps     06-08 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cal Props,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orange County's Growth Control Measure Fails</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Undated AM-State Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM SCHIFFMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California voters said no to quarantining
AIDS sufferers, kept the Rancho Seco nuclear plant alive and
refused to form their first new county in 80 years, while sending
mixed signals on taxes and growth in the most populous state.
   With all but a handful of Tuesday's votes counted, voters
rejected Propositions 71 and 72, both aimed at relaxing state
spending limits.
   Proposition 71, which would have allowed government to spend
more money, was defeated 49 percent to 51 percent. Proposition 72,
designed to modify the limit to allow the gasoline sales tax to be
spent on highway construction, was turned down 38 percent to 68
percent.
   The ceiling, approved in 1979 after voters slashed taxes with
Proposition 13, ties annual expenditures to population growth and
the cost of living.
   Proposition 69, the AIDS measure backed by extremist Lyndon
LaRouche, was defeated by a 68 percent to 32 percent margin. It
called for adding AIDS to the state list of communicable diseases,
giving officials the right to quarantine patients and those testing
positive for the virus. A similar proposal was rejected at the
polls 18 months ago.
   San Bernardino County voters opposed by a two-thirds majority
the creation of an 18,160-square-mile Mojave County. The county
would have been the state's largest, claiming 90 percent of the
land in San Bernardino County but just 20 percent of its residents.
   The Rancho Seco plant won a reprieve from the wrecking ball.
Voters in Sacramento County and part of Placer County narrowly
approved a measure, backed by a $1.4 million campaign by the
nuclear energy industry, to give plant managers 18 months to iron
out problems that have caused more than 100 outages since it opened
in 1974. The vote was 51.6 percent in favor and 48.4 percent
opposed.
   An opposing measure, which would have turned off the reactor for
good, lost by an even narrower margin _ 49.6 percent in favor to
50.4 percent opposed.
   Voters also approved two measures to control on campaign
spending.
   Proposition 68, aimed at limiting contributions to legislative
candidates, was approved 53 percent to 47 percent. Proposition 73,
which limits contributions in all state and local races and
prohibits public campaign financing, won the support of 58 percent
of the voters.
   Under state law, since Proposition 73 won by a greater margin
than 68, its provisions will supersede Proposition 68 in areas
where the two conflict.
   Voters statewide showed they were ready to spend money for some
projects. They said yes to an $800 million school bond issue, 65
percent to 35 percent; approved a bond issue to fund housing loans
for veterans, 68 percent to 32 percent; OK'd a $150 million bond
issue to fund reinforcement of masonry apartment buildings which
could tumble in an earthquake; and also backed a $776 million bond
issue for purchase and development of parks and land supporting
endangered species, 65 percent to 35 percent.
   Proposition 74, a $1 billion bond issue to build and improve
state highways, was too close to call, with ``yes'' and ``no''
votes separated by about 10,000 out of more than 5 million cast.
The outcome might not be known until July 5, when the official vote
count is released.
   Measures aimed at slowing growth met mixed receptions. Orange
County's Measure A, the most sweeping, was opposed by 55.7 percent
of voters and favored by 44.3 percent. The initiative aimed to
limit growth depending on the impact it would have on roads,
emergency services, flood control and parks.
   Growth-related measures passed in the Southern California
communities of Irvine, Hemet, San Clemente and San Marcos. But
measures in the Los Angeles suburbs of Manhattan Beach and Pasadena
were defeated easily.
   Voters in San Francisco split on two measures aimed at reducing
the city's expected $179 million deficit. They passed Proposition
B, calling for a one-year freeze on wage hikes for city employees,
with 78 percent in favor and just 22 percent opposed. But they
turned down Proposition K, which would have lifted the
state-imposed limit on spending, defeating it by 56 percent to 44
percent.
   Mayor Art Agnos said Wednesday that he would have to lay off 356
employees, close three fire stations and cut health srvices.
   Taking advantage of a state law passed last year allowing all
counties to raise the sales tax for transportation and permitting
the 46 smallest counties to use the money for general needs, four
counties approved half-cent increases. But six said no to a sales
tax hike.
</TEXT>
