<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HurricaneData     06-08 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Data,510</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Computers To Improve Hurricane Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airborne computers will send more easily
understood data back from inside hurricanes this year, helping
ground-based meteorologists better track and predict the giant
storms.
   In the past, the weather information radioed back from research
aircraft has had to undergo analysis on the ground before it could
be used in storm reports and studies. Now, some of that work will
be done aboard the airplane itself.
   ``The real benefit involved in doing this is that the forecaster
on the ground will be seeing things in the data almost as quickly
as the observer on the airplane,'' explained Dr. Stanley Rosenthal,
director of the Hurricane Research Division of the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration in Key Biscayne, Fla.
   ``Over the years it's become apparent that people on the
(research) plane are able see things, important things, that
forecasters on the ground ought to be able to see,'' he said in a
telephone interview Wednesday.
   ``This has not been possible before, but now we are able to
provide the man on the ground with information almost as quickly as
on those on the aircraft,'' he said.
   While information such as the wind speed and direction,
temperature and rainfall may seem simple, instruments collecting
this data don't necessarily provide it in simple numerical form,
Rosenthal said.
   Past practice has been for the various electronic readings to be
radioed back to the ground, where they were converted to numerical
readings and then combined for use in research and forecasting.
   The new system _ tried experimentally last year _ uses a new
computer on the NOAA P-3 Orion aircraft to quickly convert the
instrument readings to usable data and combine the numbers in
various ways to make them mose useful to forecasters on the ground.
   That means that as the plane flies through the storm its will be
sending back a steady stream of data on the state of the hurricane
itself, its direction of movement and any changes, according to Dr.
Hugh Willoughby, also of the Hurricane Research Division.
   The information is sent from the aircraft to satellites and then
returns to the ground at the NOAA satellite station at Wallops
Island, Va. From there is is transmitted both to the researchers in
Key Biscayne and to forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in
nearby Coral Gables.
   Much of the information will continue to be sent in the
traditional manner, Rosenthal said.
   But the new system will be used, in addition, for factors which
tend to influence the development and movement of the storms.
   Among the most important of these is the exact location of the
hurricane'e eye, which it is vital to know in order to predict the
movement of the storm. Willoughby said an error of as little as 30
miles in locating the eye _ the relatively calm center of the storm
_ can make a vast difference in determining what coastal under is
under threat and how soon landfall is likely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
