<DOCNO> AP880608-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoorFrisco     06-08 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poor Frisco,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SF Voters Reject New Tax Plan, Approve Wage Freeze</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Los Angeles-dated AM-Cal Props</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Agnos said Wednesday that voters'
refusal to help fend off a projected $180 million budget deficit by
raising the spending limit will force him to lay off 356 employees,
close three fire stations and cut health services.
   ``I am concerned about it, I'm not frightened by it,'' he said
of the prospective cuts in public safety and health. ``What people
are saying is `We will accept that risk because we don't want to
pay for it.'''
   Proposition K, an override of the state-imposed spending limit
that would have allowed the city to raise and spend $30 million in
additional business, hotel and parking taxes, went down to defeat
in Tuesday's election by a 56 percent to 44 percent margin.
   It would have allowed Agnos to raise the hotel tax from 11
percent to 12 percent, increase the business payroll tax from 1.5
percent to 1.6 percent and levy an annual $200 business
registration fee for small businesses.
   Agnos, who took office early this year, had warned that without
the taxes, which were fiercely opposed by the business community,
he would be forced to lay off police officers and firefighters,
shut down fire stations and reduce health services.
   A special task force of business, labor and union leaders will
meet within the next week to review his recommendations, which will
be discussed in budget hearings by the Board of Supervisors.
   Layoff notices, meanwhile, are scheduled to be mailed out this
week and union officials have threatened lawsuits or ballot
initiatives seeking minimum staffing levels that would prevent some
dismissals.
   Voters apparently bought the anti-Proposition K campaign pitch
that raising the spending limit to an unspecified level would
amount to giving the Board of Supervisors a ``blank check,'' Agnos
said.
   San Franciscans did approve another ballot measure calling for a
wage freeze for police and firefighters to save $10 million, and a
voluntary early retirement plan. They also passed a bond measure to
spend $90 million to improve school facilities.
   Supervisor Bill Maher, a leading opponent of Proposition K,
predicted that Agnos' forecast of cutbacks won't materialize.
Instead, he said, overtime expenses can be reduced and other
portions of the budget that don't affect human services can be
further tightened.
   ``The message is real clear: cut the spending and cut the
government payroll,'' he said.
   San Francisco has more police officers than any county in
California, with 26.7 per 10,000 population.
</TEXT>
