<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Cuomo-Dukakis     06-08 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Dukakis,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Endorses Dukakis _ Three Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo finally endorsed
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for the Democratic presidential
nomination on Wednesday but continued to insist his support was
``never relevant.''
   A day earlier, by winning the lion's share of delegates in the
final four primaries, Dukakis wrapped up the nomination.
   Cuomo also said he felt Jesse Jackson could be a plus for the
Democratic ticket as the vice presidential candidate, but said he
hadn't discussed that with Dukakis.
   Cuomo's public endorsement of Dukakis came only after some
semantic tooth-pulling by reporters at a news conference.
   When Cuomo revealed that he had talked to Dukakis on Wednesday
morning, reporters asked the New York governor if they had talked
about an endorsement. Cuomo brushed the question aside.
   ``For months, I said I was for whoever comes out of the primary
process first ... so that was a fait accompli as soon as the
primaries were over,'' said Cuomo.
   Pressed on the point, Cuomo said, ``It's an empty question. I
gave the endorsement months ago to whoever came out first. My
endorsement was never relevant.''
   ``Why can't you bring yourself to say that you endorse him?''
one exasperated reporter finally asked.
   ``I endorse him! I endorse him! I endorse him,'' shot back Cuomo
as laughter swept through the news conference. ``There, three times
I endorsed him.''
   In the days leading up to New York's crucial April 19
presidential primary, Cuomo announced that he would not endorse any
of the candidates until after the primary season ended. After that,
Cuomo said he would get behind the front-runner help him secure the
nomination.
   At the time, some speculated that Cuomo might be hoping for a
deadlocked convention that might then turn to him with the
nomination. Cuomo denied that and insisted he had ruled out any
convention draft.
   The New York governor repeated his assertion that Jackson could
be good for the Democratic ticket.
   ``Certainly, he could be good for the ticket,'' said Cuomo.
``How could you say no? All those millions of people who voted for
him thought he was better than Gore, better than (former Arizona
Gov. Bruce) Babbitt, better than (Delaware Sen. Joseph) Biden,
better than (Illinois Sen. Paul) Simon. How could you say he
wouldn't be good for the ticket?''
</TEXT>
