<DOCNO> AP880608-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Religion     06-08 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Religion,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graham, Catholic Churchmen Arrive In Soviet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Billy Graham, who arrived in Moscow on
Wednesday along with a high-ranking Vatican delegation, said he was
hopeful of new religious freedom in the Soviet Union.
   The religious leaders are here for celebrations marking the
1,000th anniversary of Christianity in what is now the Soviet Union.
   Graham, 69, caused controversy when he suggested during a 1982
visit that there was more religious liberty in this officially
atheist nation than Americans had been led to believe. The Baptist
minister said Wednesday he saw hopeful signs under Mikhail
Gorbachev, who became Soviet leader in March 1985.
   ``We have heard with great interest that there is an official
commitment by General Secretary Gorbachev and other leaders of your
government to expand the religious rights and opportunities of
believers and churches,'' Graham said upon arrival at Moscow's
Sheremetyevo Airport.
   Graham said he wanted to learn how ``glasnost,'' Gorbachev's
policy of openness on selected issues, and ``perestroika,'' his
program for restructuring the economy, had affected religious
believers.
   He and 10 Roman Catholic cardinals, part of the largest Vatican
delegation ever in the Soviet Union, were greeted by Metropolitan
Filaret, a senior official of the Russian church.
   The leader of the Vatican delegation, Cardinal Agostino
Casaroli, was carrying the first letter from Pope John Paul II to
Gorbachev.
   Casaroli told reporters he does not know whether he will meet
with Gorbachev, but Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro said such a
session might occur Monday during a Kremlin ceremony marking the
anniversary.
   Casaroli, the Vatican's secretary of state, declined to disclose
the contents of the papal letter.
   He called perestroika ``a good idea.''
   ``Everything which assures a greater participation of the people
and greater participation of the church in the society is
positive,'' Casaroli told reporters.
   Before leaving Rome, Casaroli expressed ``great satisfaction''
in the progress made so far in Vatican-Soviet relations, but said
they had not yet reached the stage where a papal visit would be
possible.
   The Polish-born pope has frequently expressed his desire to
visit his flock in the Soviet Union, but only if he would be free
to travel to visit Catholics throughout the country, including the
Ukraine and Lithuania.
   Among the other Catholic dignitaries traveling with Casaroli are
Cardinal John O'Connor of New York, and Cardinal Roger Etchegaray,
president of the Vatican's Justice and Peace Commission.
   The festivities begun this week come at a time when Communist
authorities are rewriting laws regulating religion to allow
believers more latitude in expressing their faith.
   O'Connor, on his first visit to the Soviet Union, said the
Vatican delegation hopes its visit ``will help advance the cause of
spiritual union between East and West, between Orthodoxy and the
Roman Catholic Church.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopExecution     06-08 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Execution,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Meeting With Parents, Mormon Clergy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted child killer Arthur Gary Bishop
has met with his parents and a Mormon chaplain as he prepared for
his execution early Friday, a corrections official said.
   Barring unexpected legal intervention, Bishop will die by lethal
injection shortly after 12:01 a.m. Friday to become the 99th inmate
executed in the United States since a 1976 U.S. Supreme Court
ruling ended a nationwide moratorium on capital punishment.
   Bishop, 36, has said he hopes his death will bring peace to the
parents of the five boys, ages 4 to 13, he sexually molested and
killed during the late 1970s and early 1980s.
   ``He seems to be preparing himself for what will take place, as
well as anyone can,'' Corrections Department spokesman Juan
Benavidez said Wednesday.
   Benavidez said Bishop had indicated he will fast during the
hours prior to the execution.
   Bishop will be strapped to the gurney and a solution of sodium
penathol, Pavulon and potassium chloride will be injected into his
veins. The drugs first will put Bishop to sleep, then paralyze his
lungs and stop his heart.
   Utah law allows the condemned to choose between lethal injection
or firing squad.
   Bishop, an Eagle Scout and former Mormon missionary who was
excommunicated prior to his arrest, initially appealed his death
sentence. But after the Utah Supreme Court rejected his appeal Feb.
3, Bishop filed a motion to fire his attorneys and replace them
with counsel willing to abandon further appeals.
   Following a 3rd District Court competency hearing, the high
court on May 2 ruled in Bishop's favor.
   The last execution in Utah was that of Pierre Dale Selby in
August 1987. Selby was executed after 13 years of appeal for the
torture-murders of three people during a 1974 robbery. Selby's
execution was the first in Utah since that of Gary Gilmore in 1977.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrawleyCase Bjt   06-08 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Case, Bjt,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawley Mom Holed Up in Church and Prepared to Wait</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY41</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to a black teen-ager who claims she
was abducted and raped by six white men dared the state attorney
general to ``show the nation the moral beast you are'' and arrest
the girl's mother, who sought sanctuary in a church after refusing
to testify about the case.
   Glenda Brawley spent Wednesday morning ``resting and praying''
in Ebenezer Baptist Church in the New York City borough of Queens,
said the Rev. Al Sharpton, an adviser to the family.
   Mrs. Brawley, 33, was sentenced Monday to 30 days in jail for
defying a grand jury subpoena to testify about the alleged attack
on her daughter, 16-year-old Tawana.
   Her advisers have accused local and state authorities of a
racially motivated cover-up and claimed the Brawleys cannot get
justice from the courts.
   Sharpton appeared outside the church and challenged Attorney
General Robert Abrams, who had given Mrs. Brawley until Wednesday
to appear before the grand jury.
   ``There's nothing legally stopping you from coming in here. So
show the nation the moral beast you are and come through these
doors and arrest her,'' Sharpton said.
   ``She'd rather be arrested in the house of God than to be
sitting in front of a stacked grand jury to participate in the
hanging of her daughter,'' he said, adding, ```But even you, Mr.
Abrams, your arms are too short to box with God.''
   However, Mrs. Brawley's attorneys backed off from earlier claims
that police could not legally arrest Mrs. Brawley in the church,
which dominates an industrial neighborhood.
   Andrew Schnier of the New York State Bar Association's criminal
justice section said there was no state or common law that would
preclude authorities from executing an arrest warrant in a
religious institution.
   A spokesman for Abrams, who was appointed by Gov. Mario Cuomo to
handle the case, said he was prepared to wait before arresting Mrs.
Brawley.
   ``Whether it's today, tomorrow _ Glenda Brawley is no particular
threat to the public safety or public order,'' said spokesman Tim
Gilles, who was with Abrams in Poughkeepsie, 85 miles north of New
York, where the grand jury was continuing its investigation.
   Miss Brawley was found lying dazed in a road about 10 miles from
her Poughkeepsie home after having been missing for four days last
November. She was wrapped in a plastic bag, her hair shorn, with
animal excrement smeared on her and racial epithets scrawled on her
body.
   Miss Brawley initially told authorities she was abducted and
raped by six white men, but she and her family have refused to
cooperate with the grand jury.
   Sharpton and the family's lawyers _ C. Vernon Mason and Alton
Maddox Jr. _ once again called for Abrams to step aside and for the
governor to appoint a special prosecutor. Sharpton also hinted that
Miss Brawley may cooperate with a new ``impartial prosecutor.''
   Speaking through the media to Abrams, Sharpton said:
   ``If you do not step aside, the minute you close your grand jury
we will only go to the governor and say, `Governor, give us a
prosecutor because we have a new witness and new evidence _ her
name is Tawana Brawley.'''
   The grand jury would likely wind up its probe in ``a month or
so'' if the Brawleys do not cooperate, Gilles said.
   ``We're prepared to stay here as long as it takes,'' Mason said
outside the church. Mrs. Brawley was invited to seek ``religious
asylum and sanctuary'' at the church by its pastor, Rev. Timothy
Mitchell, he added.
   Mrs. Brawley did not appear outside. Black reporters from a
radio station were allowed inside but said they did not see Mrs.
Brawley. All other reporters were barred by a well-dressed man
guarding the front door. No city police were at the church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PentagonAudits     06-08 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon Audits,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Number of Defense Contractors Denied Right To Bid in Early
1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department stripped a record 284
contractors of their right to bid for military work because of
wrongdoing during the first half of fiscal 1988, according to a
Pentagon report released Wednesday.
   In addition, the bidding rights of another 173 contractors were
suspended temporarily, and 2,373 civilian and military indictments
were obtained alleging contracting improprieties.
   The new figures are contained in a semi-annual report to
Congress by the Pentagon's inspector general. Previously, the
record for debarring defense contractors of bidding rights during a
six-month period was the 275 reported for the last half of fiscal
1987.
   During all of fiscal 1987, the Defense Department debarred 505
individuals and companies of their right to bid on contracts _ an
annual record.
   The latest report, which covers the period from Oct. 1, 1987, to
March 31, also found that Pentagon and U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
auditors saved the government an estimated $3.1 billion during the
six-month period by challenging questionable awards or future
contracting plans.
   To produce those savings, the auditors issued more than 26,000
reports and questioned more than $57.6 billion in contract costs,
the report said.
   Another $2.7 billion was reported saved during the period
through follow-up audits aimed at completing cases that originally
led to management disputes over the auditor's recommendations.
   Among some of the more significant investigative actions cited
during the period were the racketeering and bribery convictions of
defense employees at the clothing directorate of a Philadelphia
procurement center; a cost-mischarging case settled by Motorola
Inc. for $9.9 million; a defective pricing and illegal gratuities
case against the Eaton Corp. that produced $9.5 million in
restitution; and a huge defective pricing case settled with Bell
Helicopter Textron Inc. for more than $85 million.
   The inspector general by law maintains a staff of auditors and
investigators who operate independently, outside the control of top
Pentagon executives. The latest report is dated May 30 but was not
released until Wednesday.
   In a foreword to the report, Inspector General June Gibbs Brown
wrote the figures demonstrated ``our commitment to vigorous,
innovative efforts to achieve the widest possible cooperation in
fighting the misuse of dollars appropriated for the defense of our
country.''
   On the investigative side, the inspector general said there were
294 indictments during the period obtained by the Justice
Department on the Pentagon's behalf, plus another 143 indictments
at the local, state or foreign level and 1,936 recommendations for
courts-martial.
   During the six months, the Justice Department obtained 244
convictions; local, state and foreign authorities 188 convictions
and the military commands another 2,448 through courts-martial.
   The inspector general said the federal government managed to
recover $245.3 million during the first half of the year thanks to
completed investigations _ another record _ plus another $35.9
million in fines, penalties and restitutions and $23.7 million in
civil settlements and judgments.
   The Pentagon's Fraud Hotline, meantime, fielded 5,449 reports
during the period, up slightly compared with the previous six-month
period. Of the total received, 1,865 were judged to be
``substantive complaints'' and were referred for investigation or
other action, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
