<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-ContraHearing     06-08 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra Hearing,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Organizations Seeking Access To Pre-Trial Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six major news organizations on Wednesday
asked the judge in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case to allow
reporters to attend a closed pre-trial hearing scheduled to be held
on Monday in U.S. District Court here.
   The news organizations, which include the ABC and CBS television
networks and The New York Times, asked U.S. District Judge Gerhard
A. Gesell to open the hearing where government officials are
scheduled to testify about how witnesses were briefed before they
were questioned by the Iran-Contra grand jury.
   Gesell ordered the hearing to determine whether or not
government officials who appeared before the grand jury had been
exposed to the immunized congressional testimony of Oliver North
and two co-defendants when they were prepared by government lawyers
for the grand jury sessions.
   North, former national security adviser John M. Poindexter and
arms dealer Albert Hakim have moved to dismiss the 23-count
indictment on the ground that the prosecution and the grand jury
made impermissible use of the congressional testimony the
defendants gave last year under limited grants of immunity from
prosecution.
   In explaining why he scheduled the closed hearing, Gesell said
in a brief June 2 order that ``it is expected the testimony may to
some extent involve classified materials and to some degree relate
to matters of attorney-client privilege.''
   Gesell also said that he would promptly release a transcript of
the hearing after deleting any classified or privileged material.
   In seeking to open the hearing, the news organizations argued
that Gesell had not met Supreme Court requirements for closing the
hearing. ``The closure of a portion of a criminal trial must always
be done with the utmost caution and deliberation,'' said a joint
brief filed by six news organizations, which also included The Wall
Street Journal, The Washington Post and the Los Angeles Times.
   ``The need for such caution is especially evident in this case
since it involves issues of such national interest and
importance,'' the brief said.
   The news organizations contended that ``the mere fact that
certain material may be classified is not in itself sufficient to
warrant automatic closure of an entire hearing.''
   ``At most, it would justify exclusion of the press and the
public from that portion of the hearing at which classified
information was discussed,'' the brief said. It said that Gesell's
order ``does not explain why partial closure is not sufficient'' to
protect secret information.
</TEXT>
