<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Autograph,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Autographed Magazine Cover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An incident in Moscow that led to a full-page
newspaper advertisement for Time magazine resulted from an aide's
request that President Reagan get Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's autograph for a friend, the White House disclosed
Wednesday.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Kenneth M.
Duberstein, deputy White House chief of staff, asked Reagan to get
Gorbachev to sign the Jan. 4, 1988 issue of the magazine that had
the Soviet leader's picture on the cover as ``Man of the Year.''
   He said Reagan made the request just after the formal farewell
ceremony at the conclusion of the U.S.-Soviet summit last week, and
Gorbachev complied.
   Duberstein, asked about the incident as he left a White House
luncheon Wednesday, said he made the request on behalf of ``an old
friend in New York.'' The deputy chief of staff did not return a
reporter's telephone call seeking more details.
   The autograph incident was first reported by Tass, the Soviet
news agency, which did not mention that Reagan asked for the
autograph at anybody's request. Time reproduced a New York Times
account of the Tass version in a full-page ad in Wednesday's
editions of the Times, under the headline, ``What WAS signed in
Moscow last week.''
