<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YouthTraining     06-08 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Youth Training,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Proposes Changes in Job Training for Disadvantaged
Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Wednesday
proposed changing the way the government spends some $750 million a
year on training hard-core disadvantaged youths for jobs.
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said the administration plans to
send a bill to Congress in the next two weeks that would allow
local communities to expand the current summer-only program to a
year-round effort.
   It also would change the formula used for allocating the funds
in order to shift more of them to inner cities where youth
unemployment is highest, particularly among black teen-agers.
   The current formula established by Congress is based on local
unemployment rates generally. The new formula would be based on
Census Bureau data on the percentage of disadvantaged youths in a
community's population.
   ``We have been concerned for some time on how to reach the most
disadvantaged youths,'' Mrs. McLaughlin told the employment
subcommittee of the Senate Labor Committee. ``Cyclical changes in
unemployment rates may cause large funding swings under the current
formula that are unrelated to the youth poverty situation in a
local area.''
   The program under Title II-B of the Job Training Partnership Act
now provides about $900 each for six-week job-training programs in
the summer for about 800,000 youths ages 14 to 21 each year.
   Robert Jones, assistant labor secretary for job training, said
the changes would allow communities to spend up to $2,000 or $3,000
on each youth in the program.
   ``Technically, we would serve a few less,'' he said, ``but we
would serve them much more effectively. You can't address the youth
unemployment issue just in terms of numbers; you have to do it
qualitatively.''
   Unemployment among teen-agers is about three times the overall
civilian jobless rate of 5.6 percent. Although joblessness among
black teen-agers has declined more than 15 percentage points since
the early 1980s, it is still more than six times the overall rate.
</TEXT>
