<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsBonds     06-08 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Bonds,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Drop For Second Consecutive Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. savings bonds dropped for the
second consecutive month in May, falling 0.9 percent to $655
million, the government said Wednesday.
   The Treasury Department said April sales were $6 million lower
than in April and $51 million lower than in March. However, prior
to the two drops, sales had increased eight months in a row. Also,
May sales were 8.8 percent higher than sales a year ago.
   With the inclusion of interest earnings, the value of
outstanding bonds rose $540 million to $105.65 billion in May, 9.9
percent higher than a year ago.
   Since November 1982, savings bonds held five years or longer
earn market-based interest rates. The current rate, in effect until
Nov. 1, is 6.90 percent, down from 7.17 percent in the six months
that ended May 1.
   The Treasury Department began a new program a month ago to sell
bonds by telephone. Investors can use a credit card to purchase
bonds 24 hours a day by calling 1-800-US-BONDS.
</TEXT>
