<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HolocaustSurvivors     06-08 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust Survivors,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Germany Offers `Humanitarian Aid' to Holocaust Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany expressed readiness Wednesday to aid
Jews who survived the Nazi Holocaust.
   The official news agency ADN quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman
Wolfgang Meyer as saying the Communist government ``is now prepared
to give humanitarian aid and assistance to Jewish victims in other
countries.''
   That appears to reverse previous policy. East Germany, formed in
1949, has said it bore no legal or moral responsibility for the
actions of Adolf Hitler's Third Reich.
   ADN said the decision came after contacts with Jewish leaders in
and outside the country, and ``the kind and amount of help are
still under discussion.''
   Heinz Galinski, chairman of the German Jewish Council, said
Monday the East German government was prepared to pay up to $100
million to Jewish victims.
   Galinski, who lives in West Berlin, said the money would be
offered as ``aid for Holocaust survivors who are in need of
material assistance,'' not as repayment to German Jews for their
losses under Nazi rule.
   He said the agreement was reached after a meeting with Erich
Hoenecker, the East Germany leader.
   The news agency report did not mention a money figure, but said
the agreement to assist survivors was concluded in meetings with
Jewish leaders, including Galinski.
   More than 6 million Jews were killed in the Holocaust.
   In 1952, the Luxembourg Agreement covering reparations was
signed by the World Jewish Congress and West Germany but not by
East Germany.
   West Germany has paid more than 80 billion marks _ $48 billion
at the current exchange rate _ to Holocaust survivors around the
world.
</TEXT>
