<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Abortion     06-08 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Abortion,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Introduces Bill To Permanently Ban Federal Funds for
Abortions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan sent Congress legislation on
Wednesday to make permanent the ban on use of federal funds for
abortions unless the life of the mother is endangered, the White
House said.
   Currently, the anti-abortion provision is included annually in
the appropriation act for the Department of Health and Human
Services.
   In his letter to Congress, Reagan said, ``This important
legislation carries out my commitment to protect the rights of
unborn children by prohibiting federal dollars from being used to
fund abortion unless a mother's life would be physically endangered
by carrying the fetus to term.''
   Reagan said the bill would enact the so-called Hyde Amendment,
named for Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., on a permanent basis.
   ``Enacting this prohibition on the funding of abortion in
general legislation will exend its application to all agencies and
to all federal funds,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan's domestic policy adviser, Gary Bauer, said the bill was
to fulfill a pledge Reagan made in his last State of the Union
address to try to make the amendment permanent.
   But Kate Michelman, the executive director of the National
Abortion Rights Action League, called it a ``a last ditch effort''
on the part of the administration.
   ``I don't believe Congress is prepared to go that far to
institutionalize this forever,'' she said.
</TEXT>
