<DOCNO> AP880608-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0768 06-08 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0768,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Tries To Clear Obstacles In Bases Negotiations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 7 grafs after 6th graf pvs, After their ... UPDATING
with U.S. briefing on talks, replies to Mideast reports. Picks up
7th graf pvs, Spain has ... with minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz tried
to clear some obstacles Wednesday to a new agreement on U.S. bases
in Spain, which is the newest NATO member and is evicting 72 U.S.
jet fighters.
   Shultz sought to speed negotiations on American use of the naval
base at Rota, in southwestern Spain, and two joint air facilities
in time for signing before the summer holiday of Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez and his government.
   Rota is an important support post for the U.S. 6th Fleet, which
patrols the Mediterranean.
   Before Shultz met with Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez
Ordonez, however, the Spanish official was quoted as saying the
secretary's 72-hour visit would not accelerate the accord.
   ``During the meeting we will clarify certain points, but nothing
else,'' he said state-run television.
   After their talk, Shultz said: ``These discussions are good, and
it was a worthwhile investment of an hour.'' Fernandez said the
meeting was ``very positive and constuctive (but) there's still
work to be done.''
   Shultz also briefed Prime Minister Gonzalez on Wednesday about
the U.S.-Soviet summit meeting in Moscow and his unsuccessful
effort for Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   ``The bulk of the discussion was devoted to the bases agreement,
(with) the secretary expressing our thought (that) this ought to be
moved to completion,'' a senior U.S. official said.
   The official, who spoke with journalists on condition his name
not be used, would not predict when the new defense agreement would
be finished. ``Any time you are in one of these negotiations you
don't have an agreement until you have an agreement,'' he said.
   Shultz also paid a courtesy call on King Juan Carlos.
   The senior U.S. official was asked about a report that Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said in New York he had not
discussed the specifics of the U.S. peace plan with Shultz in the
Middle East.
   ``I really don't know what he's talking about. They talked about
the Middle East at length,'' the official said.
   When questioned about a report that President Hafez Assad of
Syria asked Shultz to open contacts with Iran, the official said it
never happened.
   Spain has ordered F-16 fighter jets of the 401st Tactical
Fighter Wing to leave Torrejon Air Base outside Madrid, forcing the
unit's relocation at a projected cost of $500 million.
   On June 4, the Italian government agreed to accept the 72 jets
subject to parliamentary approval. They are to leave Spain within
three years after the new bases agreement is signed.
   Moving the fighter wing will cost Washington an estimated $150
million, the U.S. share of contributions to the infrastructure fund
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. The fund will finance
the move unless NATO defense ministers decide on an another
approach.
   The United States also has agreed to pay an estimated $12
million of the total cost of recreational facilities at the new
F-16 base in Italy.
   Lord Carrington of Britain, the NATO secretary-general, said:
``I think the outcome is very satisfactory. If the alliance as a
whole had not decided to ask Italy and decided to pay for the
transfer, this would have sent a wholly wrong signal to the United
States ... in connection with European interest in the defense of
the southern flank.''
   Carrington addressed a news conference the day before the spring
meeting of the North Atlantic Council, the first to be held in
Spain since it became the 16th member of NATO in May 1982.
   Several administrative and other obstacles hold up completion of
a new eight-year defense accord between the United States and Spain
announced Jan. 15, when the United States agreed to move the F-16s.
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower and Gen. Francisco Franco, the
Spanish dictator, signed the first agreement in 1953. Franco died
in 1975.
   The Reagan administration is encouraged by the fact that the
next extension will be for eight years, rather than the usual five,
and that no U.S. aid to Spain will be tied to it.
   Gonzalez saw his Socialist Party's second electoral victory two
years ago as a mandate to evict the U.S. planes from Torrejon, a
joint-use base just outside Madrid.
   In a referendum Gonzalez called in March 1986, Spaniards
approved retaining NATO membership but on condition the U.S.
military presence be reduced, Spain be free of nuclear weapons and
its armed forces stay outside the integrated NATO command.
   Spaniards tend to view U.S. military bases as a symbol of
American support for Franco.
   Negotiations began two years ago when Spain indicated it would
seek a reduction in U.S. military forces in keeping with the
referendum results.
</TEXT>
