<DOCNO> AP880608-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-KittyDukakis     06-08 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kitty Dukakis,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Dukakis Ready To Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis said Wednesday she was thrilled that
her husband Michael had clinched the Democratic presidential
nomination and said she was looking forward to leaving the Boston
hospital where she had spinal surgery last week.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 51, was scheduled to leave Massachusetts General
Hospital on Thursday, six days after undergoing delicate surgery to
replace two herniated cervical discs that were placing pressure on
her spine.
   She said that while she no longer felt the numbness and pain
that nagged her before the operation, her hip was quite painful.
Doctors removed bone slivers from her left hip to replace the discs.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, was returning from
California to Boston Wednesday night after gaining a mathematical
lock on the nomination Tuesday with wins in the final four
primaries. He was to visit his wife Wednesday night.
   ``He better,'' she said with a laugh.
</TEXT>
