<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Three Guerrillas In Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops on Wednesday shot and killed
three guerrillas north of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone in
southern Lebanon, the army said.
   The troops were searching for rocket launching sites and
guerrilla strongholds when they spotted a guerrilla ring and opened
fire, an army spokesman said. He said there were no army casualties.
   Israel radio said the guerrillas were apparently on their way to
carry out an attack in the security zone, a six-to-10 mile wide
strip of land north of the Israeli border.
   Troops discovered three bodies while searching the area of the
clash, the radio said.
   Neither the army spokesman nor the radio identified the group to
which the guerrillas belonged. The location of the clash also was
not disclosed.
   The incursion north of the security zone was the first reported
by the army since a two-day operation early last month in which
three Israeli soldiers were killed and 17 wounded. Forty guerrillas
of the Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem Hezbollah (Party of God)
movement were killed.
   On May 25, about 600 Israeli-backed Lebanese militiamen assisted
by Israeli artillery and helicopters again attacked Hezbollah
strongholds. Forty Hezbollah guerrillas were killed and about 30
wounded in clashes. Five militiamen were also wounded.
   Israel radio quoted a senior officer in the army's northern
command as calling Wednesday's search operation a ``routine mission
on the security zone's border'' carried out by a small infantry
force.
   Israel established its security zone in June 1985 when it
withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon following a three-year
occupation. The zone is patrolled by Israeli troops and
Israeli-backed Lebanese militiamen.
