<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Withdraw Authorization For Red Cross Activities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing rebels said Wednesday they
will no longer authorize Red Cross activities throughout most of
Mozambique, claiming troops launched devastating attacks on
designated Red Cross aid drop sites.
   The Mozambican National Resistance said airborne forces attacked
such sites June 3-6, killing 217 civilians and wounding 391.
   It said in a note released in Lisbon that during those three
days, air force planes dropped napalm bombs on civilians who were
supposed to receive Red Cross food and medical attention at Mulumbo
and Derre in Zambezia province and Tambara in Manica province.
   The note, signed by the rebel group's spokesman in Lisbon,
Manuel Frank, said Mozambican, Zimbabwean and Tanzanian paratroops
took part in the attacks.
   The rebel note said those gathered at the cities included no
rebel guerrillas and that no rebel bases exist in the towns that
were bombed.
   However, the note contradicted itself by saying the towns were
under the rebel's control at the time of the attacks.
   Afonso Dhlakama, leader of the Mozambican National Resistance,
``has decided to withdraw authorization for free movement ... by
the Red Cross in the provinces of Nampula, Zambezia and Manica
until the situation is clarified,'' according to the note.
   It said the rebels will allow the Red Cross to keep operating
its humanitarian programs in neighboring Sofala province.
   The rebel group has fought to topple the Marxist government
since 1977, two years after the southern African nation achieved
independence from Portugal.
   The rebels and and South Africa have denied repeated Mozambican
charges that South Africa has kept supplying the rebels despite a
1984 Mozambican-South African non-aggression pact.
