<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-NYPhilharmonic     06-08 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-NY Philharmonic,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Philharmonic and Soviet Orchestra Perform Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of music-loving Muscovites huddled under
umbrellas in summer showers as the New York Philharmonic and a
Soviet orchestra joined in a Wednesday evening concert capped by a
fireworks display.
   Zubin Mehta, music director for the Philharmonic, and Soviet
conductor Gennady Rozhdestvensky drew shouts of ``Bravo, bravo!''
after each led the 200-member orchestra.
   The covered stage in Moscow's Gorky Park resembled a
checkerboard of musicians with the Soviets from the State Symphony
Orchestra of the Ministry of Culture dressed in black and the
Americans in white. In each row, an American and Soviet sat next to
one another, accentuating the pattern.
   The concert was the seventh and final engagement in the
Philharmonic's 10-day tour of the Soviet Union, which ends
Thursday. The orchestra gave previous performances in Leningrad's
Bolshoi Hall and three at Moscow's Tchaikovsky Hall.
   ``May we thank you on the last day of our tour for your
incredible hospitality and the warmth of your public that we will
not forget for a long time,'' Mehta told the audience in Gorky Park
prior to the concert.
   Rozhdestvensky was first on the program with Dmitri
Shostakovich's ``Symphony No. 5,'' followed by Mehta conducting
Hector Berlioz's ``Symphonie Fantastique.''
   The concert began under threatening skies and gusts of wind, but
when the rain began about 20 minutes into the program, only a few
people left.
   Musicians left their seats during the fireworks display and
moved to the front of the stage to watch the multicolored bursts
above the roof of the theater. Rozhdestvensky, his arm draped
around Mehta's shoulders, watched from the front edge of the stage.
   Although they listen intently at concerts, Soviets generally are
restrained in their applause. But the Philharmonic drew sustained
and loud applause at each of its concerts.
   ``I enjoyed it so much,'' said 53-year-old Tanya Lesina. ``It's
the first time for me, hearing someone coming from New York. ... I
hope this can continue.''
</TEXT>
