<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Election     06-08 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Breaks Silence, Appeals For Legislative Majority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand appealed Wednesday to
French voters to elect a National Assembly majority that will help
his Socialist government carry out its programs.
   Mitterrand's Socialists and a center-right coalition ran almost
even in the popular vote after the first round of voting Sunday.
But computer projections gave the Socialists an edge in next
Sunday's runoff elections.
   ``I need, to carry out my mission, a stable majority ready to
vote without delay for laws on social justice, equality of
opportunity, national solidarity and economic modernization,''
Mitterrand said at a weekly cabinet meeting led by Premier Michel
Rocard.
   The statement was released by Mitterrand's spokesman, Hubert
Vedrine.
   Mitterrand called early legislative elections less than a week
after his May 8 re-election to a second seven-year term.
   On Wednesday, Mitterrand spoke out for the first time in the
legislative campaign _ he had said previously that he would get
involved only ``if necessary.''
   In his statement, the Socialist president said he hoped for the
largest possible majority behind ``the values of liberty, equality
and respect for others'' and said it was his duty to warn French
voters ``against any coalition of electoral interests that might be
lacking in these principles.''
   Rocard said later the president intended to criticize the
relations between the center-right alliance and ``the racist and
xenophobic extreme right.''
   The extreme-right National Front of Jean-Marie Le Pen and the
conservative coalition agreed Tuesday not to run against each other
in key districts in and around the southern port of Marseilles,
where the runoff would otherwise have split the vote three ways and
made a Socialist victory more likely.
   Socialist leaders denounced the deal, while conservatives
defended it as a purely local accord, similar to those made by the
Socialists and Communists.
   But former Socialist Premier Laurent Fabius said the accord with
the National Front was a ``dishonor for those who signed it.''
   In Sunday's election, candidates who won more than 50 percent of
the vote in the first round automatically won seats in the assembly.
   In 455 of the 577 districts, candidates who drew less than 50
percent but at least 12.5 percent of the vote in the first round
are to participate in Sunday's runoff.
</TEXT>
