<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PTL-Bakkers     06-08 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Bakkers,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jim Bakker: A Man With A Plan _ From God</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker said Wednesday that God has
given him a plan to save PTL as a Christian retreat, and if the
ministry is sold for non-religious purposes, it will be cursed.
   Bakker said he has started raising money to buy back the $160
million televangelical empire he built over 14 years and lost 15
months ago after a sex and money scandal. He refused to say how
much money has been raised.
   Asked if he had the resources to buy PTL, he said, ``God does.''
   ``God has given us a plan how to pay for it and how to restore
it,'' he told The Associated Press after a brief news conference.
``The same God that has given me the vision to build it has given
me a vision to maintain it.''
   Bakker did not reveal details of his vision.
   Bakker said he would try to buy PTL's 2,300-acre Heritage USA
complex in Fort Mill piece by piece as it is liquidated in
bankruptcy court.
   The ministry is as much as $130 million in debt. A
reorganization plan calling for the sale of much of PTL's assets is
up for final approval by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds on
June 16 in Columbia.
   Under the plan, a separate, non-profit corporation called
Heritage Ministries would be formed to run the cable television
show and church at Heritage USA. However, even those operations
were threatened as PTL officials said they haven't raised enough
money to pay TV affiliates.
   George Shinn, owner of the Charlotte, N.C., Knights minor-league
baseball team and the new Charlotte Hornets of the National
Basketball Association, is among those who have expressed interest
in buying Heritage USA. Shinn would like to build a baseball
stadium there.
   Bakker and his wife, Tammy Faye, returned to Fort Mill on
Tuesday from Gatlinburg, Tenn., and set up in an office about a
mile from Heritage USA.
   ``We are prepared to do whatever it takes to restore PTL,''
Bakker said Wednesday. ``We are also prepared to wait. If anyone
takes Heritage USA and turns it into anything other than what it
was dedicated, I'm convinced it will be cursed.''
   Bakker met Wednesday with supporters in the office, which had
been headquarters of the Bring Bakkers Back Club. The meeting ended
with a prayer session in which he read from the Bible.
   Then, everyone stood up, reached their arms toward Bakker and
began talking and chanting. Some appeared to speak in tongues.
   Bakker resigned his ministry March 19, 1987, as a story about
his tryst with former church secretary Jessica Hahn was about to
break. His successor, the Rev. Jerry Falwell, banished Bakker after
the Internal Revenue Service said Bakker and his aides diverted
millions of dollars from the ministry.
   ``God forgives anyone of sin. We must live in love,'' Bakker
said.
</TEXT>
