<2ND_LINE>AM-Alioto Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0850,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former SF Mayor Joe Alioto Cleared In State Bar Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout with background of case, noting in lead
that clearing is provisional.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former San Francisco Mayor Joseph L. Alioto
was cleared provisionally Wednesday of all charges by the referee
of a State Bar Court trial over a $5.2 million legal fee in a 1975
antitrust case.
   Alioto's son, Joseph M. Alioto, faces charges from the case, in
which the plaintiffs, beef ranchers, won a $9 million settlement in
their case against three supermarket chains. The son's hearing
continues.
   The 73-year-old former mayor could have faced disbarment,
suspension or probation had he been found guilty. The referee's
decision is subject to approval of the bar's Review Department, bar
spokeswoman Anne Charles said.
   Earlier Wednesday, before the elder Alioto testified, he had an
indication of the outcome. Referee C. Thorne Corse was reported to
have told associates he was inclined to dismiss the charges against
the senior Alioto.
   Alioto issued a statement thanking the bar court ``for a just
and fair trial which has resulted inevitably in complete
vindication. ... I was confident I could prove the charges were
nothing more than vicious and baseless attacks on my reputation and
my practice.''
   Alioto was charged with collecting an `unconscionable fee'' and
acts of unethical conduct in the case, brought by plaintiffs
including Wyoming beef rancher Courtney Davis.
   The Aliotos said the fee was not unconscionable because their
clients, cattle ranchers, were receiving more than the $9 million
settlement because they also would receive 20 cents a pound more
for their beef.
   The former mayor also repeatedly maintained he had nothing to do
with the negotiation of the settlement.
   Alioto and his son were accused of acts ``moral turpitude,
dishonesty and corruption'' in taking a $5.2 million fee for
handling the case.
   Alioto told Corse, testifying only for himself, that he had been
told over the telephone by his son, a member of his firm, that the
plaintiffs had been offered $9 million.
   He said he advised his son to ``take the money and run.'' The
former mayor repeated to State Bar prosecutor Jerome Fishkin that
although he owned the firm he had not been involved in reaching the
settlement or the fee.
   He said responsibility for matters in the business had been
delegated while Alioto ran for mayor. He said he played only a
minor role in the settlement later on because he was busy being
mayor, an office he held in the late 1960s and early '70s.
</TEXT>
