<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IllegalFireworks     06-08 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illegal Fireworks,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illegal Fireworks Seized At East Coast Ports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents searching for illegal fireworks
in East Coast ports have seized 7 million spinners, cherry balls,
Roman candles and other dangerous pyrotechnics imported from China,
officials said Wednesday.
   The goods, valued at almost $1 million, were seized over the
past two months during ``Operation Eastern Thunder'' at ports in
Baltimore, Philadelphia, Charleston, S.C., and Miami, said Terrence
Scanlon, chairman of the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission.
   Searches earlier this year at West Coast and Great Lakes ports
resulted in the seizure of 54 million units of fireworks valued at
$4 million, Scanlon said.
   The seized fireworks represent about 6 percent of the nation's
total retail market for fireworks, he said.
   Scanlon said the joint effort by his office, U.S. Customs
Service and the Coast Guard extends the search for illegal
fireworks from roadside stands to shipping docks for the first time.
   Inspectors seized fireworks with improper warning labels,
unstable bases, defective fuses and excessive powder, officials
said.
   In 1987, more than 9,000 people were treated in U.S. hospital
emergency rooms after suffering injuries in fireworks accidents. An
estimated 12,600 injuries linked with fireworks in 1986, according
to federal statistics.
</TEXT>
