<2ND_LINE>AM-Uruguay,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Set Afire As Strike Hits Uruguay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist union members staged a
nationwide 24-hour strike Wednesday to demand higher wages, with
six scattered incidents reported but no casualties, police said.
   Most factories, banks, schools and public offices closed for the
day. The buses that did run carried few passengers and most were
driven by their owners.
   Police said a parked, empty transit bus was burned in Montevideo.
   The strike by members of the PIT-CNT, Uruguay's largest union,
was the sixth since 1985, when civilian President Julio Sanguinetti
was elected and restored democracy after 12 years of harsh military
rule.
   Labor Minister Hugo Fernandez Faingold called the strike
counterproductive, saying ``much more is lost than won'' by a
national walkout.
   Inflation averaged 58 percent over the last 12 months in this
nation of 3 million people, half of whom live in the capital. The
government says real wages fell 50 percent from 1968 to 1985,
prompting worker unrest and demands for wages to match the rising
cost of living.
</TEXT>
