<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Brings June Chill To The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front was working its way slowly southward through the
mid-Atlantic coastal states and the Midwest on Wednesday, to bring
significantly cooler weather to the eastern half of the nation by
Friday.
   Temperatures behind the cold front were about 20 to 30 degrees
cooler than the readings to the south.
   Thunderstorms developed along the front in Virginia and parts of
the upper and middle Mississippi Valley. Green Bay, Wis., got its
first measureable rainfall since May 9. Thunderstorms also
developed in Montana.
   Showers and thunderstorms were widespread in Florida, Georgia
and South Carolina. Scattered thunderstorms ranged from eastern
Wyoming to western Kansas, with showers lingering over coastal
Oregon and northern California.
   Temperatures were in the 90s over most of the Great Plains, in
the lower Mississippi, Tennessee and lower Ohio valleys and across
the Carolinas, with a few 100-degree readings from western Kansas
across western Oklahoma to western Texas.
   Behind the cold front, readings were only the 60s with some
upper 40s and 50s over northern Michigan, northern Wisconsin and
northern Minnesota.
   In the far west, temperatures ranged from the 50s and 60s over
the Pacific Northwest, to the 80s and lower 90s in the desert
southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Houghton Lake, Mich., to 110 degrees at Altus AFB in
Oklahoma. The nation's low was 22 degrees at Truckee and South Lake
Tahoe, Calif.
   The national weather forecast for Thursday called for scattered
showers will extend from New England across New york and eastern
Pennsylvania to the mid-Atlantic states. Showers and thunderstorms
will reach from Oklahoma across eastern Texas, the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to the south Atlantic coastal
areas. Scattered thunderstorms will develop from western South
Dakota across eastern Wyoming to eastern Colorado. Showers and a
few thunderstorms will occur over the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures will be in the 50s over New England and New
York; in the 60s or 70s from the mid-Atlantic states acrooss the
Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes and the upper half of the Mississippi
Valley to eastern portions of the northern and central Plains; in
the 60s or 70s from the Pacific Northwest to northern and coastal
sections of California; over 100 degrees in portions of southwest
Texas and the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs will be in the 80s
or 90s.
</TEXT>
