<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF-SpaceStation     06-08 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Space Station,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Finalizes Accord on International Effort for Manned Space
Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration announced Wednesday it has completed negotiations
with Canada, Europe and Japan for cooperation on the space station,
which it called ``the largest international scientific and
technological venture ever undertaken.''
   The United States will provide the overall space station
framework and operating subsystems, committing $16 billion, NASA
said.
   Canada will spend $1 billion for a mobile servicing system;
Japan, $2 billion for an experiment module; and the European Space
Agency, $4.2 billion for a laboratory and an unmanned free-flying
platform.
   The partners will cover more than 25 percent of the station's
expected annual operating costs.
   The current timetable calls for the station to be in orbit and
manned by late 1996.
</TEXT>
