<DOCNO> AP880608-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BenefitsTax 1stLd-Writethru a0936 06-08 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Benefits Tax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0936,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS: Deferred Compensation Not Taxable Under Proposed Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: To UPDATE with AFSCME comment, INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf
pvs bgng, `McGrath estimated'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has backed away
from its interpretation of a part of tax law that could have made
deferred benefits such as the vacation pay and sick time of public
and nonprofit employees' taxable, according to a Treasury
Department letter released Wednesday.
   O. Donaldson Chapoton, assistant secretary for tax policy, said
in the letter that ``bona fide'' vacation leave, sick leave,
compensatory time, severance pay, disability pay and death benefits
will not be taxable under Section 457 of the tax code.
   ``I am very happy that the IRS has decided to drop its unfair
interpretation of Section 457 of the tax code,'' said Rep. Raymond
McGrath, R-N.Y., at a news conference.
   ``This is certainly good news for the public employees of the
states,'' McGrath said. ``It is certainly good news for the
tax-exempt employees. ... It signifies that the IRS will not be
picking the pockets of these employees.''
   McGrath estimated that the some 14 million state and local
employees nationwide would have been affected, as well as untold
numbers of workers in nonprofit organizations.
   The president of the 1.1 million member American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees _ the nation's largest public
employee union _ applauded the decision.
   Gerald W. McEntee said in a statement that he was ``happy and
relieved that the Internal Revenue Service has backed away from its
plan to start taxing hard-won fringe benefits.''
   In January 1987, the IRS issued a public notice that Section 457
_ which provides rules for certain types of deferred compensation
for employees of state and local governments and tax-exempt
organizations _ would be interpreted to apply to ``nonelective''
deferred compensation.
   Nonprofit employee organizations and public employee unions,
fearing the rule would have applied to benefits that were never
taken, deluged legislators with petitions asking for help in
changing the rule.
   The IRS change came one day after Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan,
D-N.Y., introduced legislation to rescind the measure.
   Moynihan had measured praise for the IRS' decision, but said
some problems remain, such as what constitutes bona fide
compensation and how deferred cash compensation will be handled.
   ``I will discuss the matter with Treasury and with public
employee and tax-exempt employee groups, and pursue legislative
relief to the extent problems remain,'' he said in a statement.
   McGrath, who is a co-sponsor of a similar bill in the House,
credited Vice President George Bush for assisting in the debate
between Congress and the IRS on the issue.
   ``I called the vice president to explain the concerns of
millions of union members and elected officials from New York and
other states,'' McGrath said. ``He contacted Treasury Secretary
James Baker, who had the IRS reconsider its position.''
   But both Moynihan and McGrath admitted neither bill has a great
chance of passing this year because there will be no appropriate
legislative vehicle, such as a tax bill, to which their bill could
be attached.
   The IRS will formally announce its decision in the next week,
according to Chapoton's letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-O'HareInvestigation     06-08 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Investigation,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Inspectors Launch Probe of O'Hare Controller Errors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities are investigating air traffic
controllers at O'Hare International Airport after they made three
mistakes in two days this week, including one that led to a
near-miss, officials said Wednesday.
   ``The significant increase in operational errors, from 12 in all
of last year to 20 already this year, set off concern for us,''
said Mike Benson, a spokesman for the National Transportation
Safety Board in Washington.
   O'Hare is the world's busiest airport in terms of takeoffs and
landings.
   Benson said four investigators would arrive in Chicago, possibly
by Thursday, and focus on O'Hare's radar room, where most of the
mistakes have been made.
   The radar room routes air traffic in a 30-mile radius of O'Hare
while controllers in the tower primarily direct takeoffs and
landings, he said.
   Radar controllers have been responsible for 15 of the 20
mistakes, including the three earlier this week, Benson said. Last
year, they made nine of the airport's 12 errors.
   On Monday, a United Airlines Boeing 727 carrying 128 passengers
to Ontario, Calif., came within 1,200 feet of a Lear jet after
takeoff, said Dan Sheehy, a United spokesman.
   The pilot of the Lear jet filed a near-midair collision report,
said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   United did not file a report because it and the FAA consider a
near-collision to be when two aircraft come within 500 feet of each
other, Sheehy said. The United pilot did not need to take any
evasive action but the company is investigating the incident, he
said.
   Later Monday, a United 727 bound for Washington flew near a
Cessna 172 shortly after takeoff, Sheehy and Benson said.
   ``The captain did take evasive action, but the separation was
3,000 feet,'' Sheehy said.
   The third error involved an American Airlines DC-10 and a Midway
Airlines Boeing 737 on Tuesday, Benson said, but he could provide
no other details.
   The investigators will interview a cross-section of controllers,
including those involved in the errors, and examine things such as
training, quality assurance and amount of overtime worked.
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association, based in
Washington, said controllers at O'Hare and other airports
nationwide are overworked.
   ``We would welcome any type of outside oversight right now,''
said John Thornton, the group's national coordinator. ``Our concern
right now is not only for air traffic control problems at O'Hare.
Around the country we're seeing short staffs, equipment problems
and sometimes an insensitivity on the part of the FAA to resolve
these problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
