<DOCNO> AP880608-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Hollywood     06-08 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Hollywood,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. and Soviet Filmmakers Form Venture for Napoleon Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West Coast teamed up with the East bloc on
Wednesday when the Soviet Union's largest film studio and a small
Hollywood company formed the first U.S.-Soviet joint movie venture.
   Mosfilm, the Soviet Union's largest filmworks, signed a
long-term contract with FresFilm to produce several movies,
beginning with a portrayal of Napoleon's invasion of Russia in 1812.
   Soviet director Sergei Solovyev described the agreement as ``a
realistic first step toward cultural cooperation'' following the
summit in Moscow last week between President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The first film, ``Rendezvous With Bonaparte,'' will be ``a
Russian romance'' with political overtones, said Solovyev.
   Tom Meehan, president of FresFilm, described the agreement as a
foot in the Soviet door for his small studio.
   Although U.S. and Soviet studios have cooperated in previous
films, such as ``Bluebird'' with Elizabeth Taylor in the 1970s,
this deal is the first signed under a joint venture law.
   The law, which took effect last year, allows foreign firms to
own a stake of up to 49 percent in a company.
   ``Everyone in Hollywood wanted to be the first to be to sign a
contract in the Soviet Union,'' said Meehan, a cigar-chomping
resident of Fresno, Calif.
   ``Rendezvous with Bonaparte'' will be filmed in the Soviet
Union, Poland and France and distributed in the English-speaking
world by FresFilm. Mosfilm will have distribution rights in the
East bloc, and rights to distribute elsewhere will be negotiated
later.
   Under the agreement signed Wednesday, FresFilm will supply film
and rent cameras, lights and other advanced cinematographic
equipment to Mosfilm for scenes filmed in the Soviet Union and
Poland, said Meehan.
   MosFilm has agreed to provide 2 million rubles, or $3.4 million,
making ``Rendezvous with Napoleon'' the most expensive movie in its
budget this year, Solovyev said.
   ``We'll get everything we need to make the film,'' he said.
   The film will be based on a novel by Bulat Okuzhava, a beloved
Soviet lyric poet and bard.
   ``One of the aims of Napoleon invading Russia was to bring
freedom to the Russian people,'' to introduce the ideas of the 1789
French Revolution and topple the czar, said Solovyev.
   ``But when he tried to do so by force, the Russian people rose
up and defeated him. However, his ideas remained,'' said Solovyev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SeabrookSuit     06-08 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook Suit,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Sues to Overturn NRC Licensing Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general asked a federal appeals
court Wednesday to overturn a rule that could ease the licensing of
the controversial Seabrook nuclear power plant over the objections
of Massachusetts officials.
   Attorney General James Shannon argued that the rule, which lets
utilities draw up their own emergency evacuation plans when states
refuse to cooperate, poses ``a great risk to the safety of the
citizens of Massachusetts.''
   Shannon contended that the Nuclear Regulatory Commission adopted
the rule precisely to bypass state officials' opposition to opening
of the plant in Seabrook, N.H.
   William Briggs, attorney for the NRC, said the regulation
balances the interests of utility companies and public safety.
   Last year, the NRC adopted the rule allowing the commission to
consider evacuation plans drafted by nuclear plant owners if state
and local authorities refuse to offer their own proposals.
   The rule presumes that state and local officials will follow the
utility's plan in case of an actual emergency.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis so far has thwarted the
licensing of Seabrook, a completed but still idle reactor two miles
north of the Massachusetts border.
   Dukakis maintains that no emergency evacuation plan can
safeguard residents of six coastal Massachusetts towns within 10
miles of Seabrook.
   The three judges on the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
questioned attorneys on both sides but gave no indication of how
and when they might rule.
   During arguments, Appellate Judge Raymond Acosta questioned
Briggs about the wisdom of yielding emergency planning duties to
utilities. ``It seems to me it's a little like the fox guarding the
henhouse,'' Acosta said.
   ``But who's the fox?'' Briggs countered.
   ``Let's face it. These are money-making operations,'' the judge
said, referring to the utilities.
   Shannon argued that the NRC's own regulations require
``reasonable assurance'' of ``adequate protective measures'' for
the public in case of a nuclear accident.
   That standard requires the cooperation of state and local
authorities in handling traffic, fire and rescue operations, he
said.
   The NRC unreasonably presumes that states will cooperate in an
actual disaster, Shannon said, but he insisted that Massachusetts
could not and would not cooperate.
   The attorney general also argued that the new regulation entails
``an impermissible delegation'' of the governor's public safety
duties.
   Briggs said the NRC acted within its powers in approving the
regulation. He contended that Shannon's position would give states
a veto power over nuclear licensing decisions, usurping a
responsibility Congress has given to the NRC.
   He also said the NRC has never lessened the public safety
standard that evacuation plans must meet.
   Shannon was supported by attorney Karla Letsche, representing
the state of New York, Gov. Mario Cuomo and New York's Suffolk
County, as well as Ellen Weiss, representing the Union of Concerned
Scientists.
   Cuomo prevented New York officials from participating in
emergency planning for the Shoreham plant on Long Island and
steered an agreement between the state and Long Island Lighting Co.
two weeks ago that will prevent the $5.3 billion plant from ever
generating salable power.
   Meanwhile, selectmen in Groton, Mass., voted Monday to stop
paying their share of the Seabrook plant, saying it looks unlikely
they will ever see power from it.
   Gary L. Hunt, general manager of Massachusetts Municipal
Wholesale Electric Co., which made the investment for the town,
called the vote ``horribly irresponsible.''
   MMWEC last week decided to stop paying its share of the
maintenance of Seabrook but to continue to pay interest on its
share of the plant's debt. The Groton selectman voted to stop all
payments, including debt interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
