<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pakistan     06-08 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zia Trip Reported Canceled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq of Pakistan has
canceled a visit to the United States scheduled for next week,
informed sources said Wednesday.
   The trip was to include talks with President Reagan and a speech
to the U.N. disarmament conference in New York.
   Questions were raised last month about whether Zia would make
the visit after he dismissed the Pakistan government headed by
Prime Minister Mohammed Khan Junejo.
   Zia on May 30 accused the Junejo Cabinet of incompetence and
corruption and of failing to maintain law and order. He then called
for new elections for the National Assembly within 90 days, acting
under a provision of the Pakistani constitution.
   The Pakistan Embassy said it would have no information until
Ambassador Jamsheed Marker returned from Islamabad, where he had
gone to make preparations for t he visit.
   Plans for the Washington leg of Zia's visit had remained
tentative and had not been confirmed, according to a U.S. source
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier Zia actions had been praised by U.S. officials for
progress toward restoring democracy in the South Asian Moslem
country. The 64-year-old army general had seized power in a 1977
bloodless coup, and appointed Junejo prime minister in March 1985,
after national elections. He later ended martial law.
   But dismissal of the Junejo government prompted the State
Department on May 31 to say it hoped that the required elections
would be held promptly and that they would be free and fair. Later
reports from Islamabad told of growing doubt in the Pakistan
capital about prospects for prompt elections.
</TEXT>
