<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola     06-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Angola,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africans Skirmish With Cubans, Mobilize Reserves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces commander
announced a call-up of reserves and said Wednesday that South
African soldiers had skirmished with Cuban troops in Angola.
   Gen. Jannie Geldenhuys said the mobilization responded to a
buildup of Cuban troops in southern Angola. He said Cuban units
were within 12 miles of the border with South-West Africa.
   South Africa governs the territory, also known as Namibia, in
defiance of the United Nations.
   Geldenhuys spoke to reporters at an air base after returning
from the war zone. He said no casualties resulted from a skirmish
last week between South African soldiers and a Cuban reconnaissance
unit near the frontier.
   South African troops in Angola aid rebels of the Union for the
Total Independence of Angola, known as UNITA. About 45,000 Cuban
soldiers support the Marxist government.
   South African officials have said the southward Cuban advance,
which President Fidel Castro has confirmed, could jeopardize
negotiations aimed at resolving Angola's 13-year-old civil war and
bringing independence to Namibia.
   Peace talks involving South Africa, Cuba, Angola and the United
States were held May 3-4 in London. South African and Angolan
delgations met May 13 in Brazzaville, Congo. A possible third round
of talks is in limbo because of a dispute over the meeting site.
   The South African call-up involves units of the Citizen Force, a
branch of the army made up of white men who have completed thir
obligatory two years in the military and take part in annual
training camps, subject to mobilization.
   Geldenhuys gave no details of the mobilization.
   He said a press report that 11,000 Cubans were in southern
Angola might be a useful ``rough calculation.''
   ``We have the forces to handle the situation, although the
situation is serious,'' he said. ``The point is, how does it affect
the negotiations?``
</TEXT>
