<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-SouthAfrica     06-08 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-South Africa,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Defends Mandela Birthday Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The BBC on Wednesday rejected criticism of its
plans to broadcast a birthday concert honoring Nelson Mandela, but
the government dodged a demand to send the jailed black South
African leader birthday greetings.
   A South African Foreign Ministry statement charged that by
broadcasting the 10-hour concert Saturday, the publicly funded
British Broadcasting Corp. will be providing platform for the
African National Congress, a black guerrilla movement.
   Musicians participating include Whitney Houston, Dire Straits,
Simple Minds, George Michael, the Bee Gees, Joan Armatrading and
Joe Cocker.
   In an apparent resurgence of anti-apartheid campaigning in
Britain after months of relative inactivity, a strategy was
unveiled in London to boycott South African gold, and the BBC
screened a documentary Wednesday night alleging that black youths
have been tortured in South Africa.
   In Parliament, Gerald Kaufman of the opposition Labor Party
urged Foreign Office Minister Lynda Chalker to send a message of
``congratulations and good will'' to Mandela on his 70th birthday
July 18.
   Mrs. Chalker replied that the government supported freeing
Mandela, but said it was up to the Speaker to decide if the House
of Commons should send greetings. Speaker Bernard Weatherill,
seated in the chamber, made no response.
   Mandela, titular leader of the African National Conference, is
serving a life sentence for plotting the violent overthrow of white
rule in South Africa. The organizers say the guest of honor will be
ANC President Oliver Tambo.
   ``It is ironic that, while increased efforts are being made in
the U.K. to curtail funding for organizations using violent
methods, the ANC is offered this financial windfall,'' the South
African statement said.
   Nearly 60 other countries will broadcast the concert, including
the United States and the Soviet Union, the BBC said in a
statement, adding it is paying no fee to the promoters.
   The BBC broadcast a documentary Wednesday night which has also
drawn South African protest. ``Suffer the Children'' interviews
parents, lawyers, priests and children as young as 11 years old who
say they have been tortured and held for months without being
charged.
   The South Africans say the program is biased and did not give
their government the right of reply.
   Meanwhile, a new anti-apartheid group calling itself the World
Gold Commission announced plans to try to block the sale of gold
mined in South Africa, the world's largest producer.
   South Africa produces 52 percent of the gold mined in the West,
receives half its foreign income from gold sales and raises a
quarter of its taxes from the gold industry, the group said.
   By South African law and custom, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The country's 5 million whites control
the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health
services.
</TEXT>
