<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     06-08 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers And Producers Meet For Sixth Straight Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators met Wednesday for a sixth
straight day in the 14-week-long strike by movie and TV
scriptwriters.
   Both sides have declined to comment on the progress or substance
of the talks at the headquarters of the Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers.
   Negotiators for the Writers Guild of America and for movie and
TV producers went back into session with federal mediators
Wednesday afternoon, said union spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden.
   They had met for nearly 12 hours the night before, adjourning
early Wednesday morning.
   The writers struck the film industry March 7 in a dispute over
residuals for reruns of one-hour television shows. Demand for such
programs as reruns is declining, and the producers want to tie
payments to a show's success in the rerun market.
   The writers are also seeking more creative control over changes
made in scripts during filming, and more on- and off-screen credit.
   The guild has signed full-term contracts with about 80
independent producers, but the alliance says those producers employ
only a fraction of the 3,000 active writers.
