<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WillProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0968 06-08 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Will Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0968,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel To Investigate Dropping of Indictment Against George
Will's Wife</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with diGenova's statements that report is
inaccurate; diGenova is cq; NO pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee is investigating
allegations that Justice Department officials improperly quashed a
criminal indictment of the wife of syndicated columnist George
Will, a source said Wednesday.
   WUSA-TV, which reported on the congressional investigation, said
former U.S. Attorney Joseph diGenova intervened to stop the
indictment, overruling the strong recommendation of his assistant
prosecutors.
   The case involved Madeline Will, an assistant secretary of
education and wife of the conservative columnist who is a close
friend of Nancy Reagan and was a campaign debate coach for
President Reagan.
   The case concerned the submission of false travel vouchers,
wrongful use of a government limousine and driver and keeping an
employee on the government payroll for months after the employee
stopped working.
   DiGenova, reached at home Wednesday by The Associated Press,
said the report that he stopped an indictment of Mrs. Will was
``totally inaccurate'' and that he acted only after receiving the
consensus of career, non-politically appointed prosecutors in the
department.
   ``There was disagreement as to how the case should be handled,''
said diGenova, who left the U.S. attorney's job March 1 to join a
private law firm. ``Rather than make the decision personally, I
referred back to them for a group decision. That group recommended
to me that it not be handled criminally but that it be referred to
the civil division for civil action,'' he said. The reason for that
decision was insufficient evidence against Mrs. Will, he said.
   Neither Mrs. Will nor her husband could be reached for comment
Wednesday evening.
   The House Subcommittee on Human Resources and Intergovernmental
Relations ``is looking into several investigative cases at the
Department of Education that also involve the Justice Department,''
a spokesman for the panel told The Associated Press, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   A source said the hearing June 23 would include the Madeline
Will case.
   In 1986, the Education Department's inspector general's office
found that Mrs. Will submitted false travel vouchers for
reimbursement. She said it was her secretary's fault, WUSA reported.
   Investigators also found that she used a government limousine
and driver to take her to a local beauty salon and repeated lunches
at a Capitol Hill restaurant, the TV station reported.
   Mrs. Will denied the allegations, but admitted keeping an
employee on the federal payroll for nearly four months even though
the employee did not come to work, WUSA said.
   Investigators referred the case to the U.S. attorney's office
for criminal prosecution. On June 10, 1986, chief prosecutor
William Block recommended that Mrs. Will be prosecuted, the station
reported.
   But diGenova said Wednesday that Block was part of the group of
prosecutors that recommended to him that the case be turned over to
the civil division. ``Mr. Block came back with the group ... and
they recommended to me that it not be handled criminally, but that
it be handled civilly.''
   Mrs. Will was never indicted and remains an assistant secretary
of education. She did repay the Treasury Department the $12,022
paid to her missing employee from the settlement resulting from the
civil proceedings, according to department records.
   An attorney who worked on the case but who spoke only on
condition of anonymity said, ``The thought that this was a cover up
or that (diGenova) overruled a decision to prosecute is absolutely
absurd.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
