<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Soviet     06-08 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Premier Wants Greater Soviet Role In Vietnam-Cambodia
Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng urged the Soviet Union on
Wednesday to play a greater role in ending Vietnam's occupation of
Cambodia.
   The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Li as telling Soviet Vice
Premier Yuri Maslyukov at a meeting Wednesday that ``We believe the
Soviet Union can do a lot'' to end the conflict in Cambodia.
   The agency also said Li praised the Soviet troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan.
   China says the three obstacles to normalizing political ties
between Beijing and Moscow are the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan;
Soviet support for Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia; and the
concentration of Soviet troops along the Chinese-Soviet border.
Relations have been strained since 1960.
   Chinese senior leader Deng Xiaoping has said there can be no
summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev until the
obstacles, particularly the conflict in Cambodia, are removed.
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev denied at a Tuesday
news conference in Beijing that his government is pressuring
Vietnam to pull its troops out of Cambodia. However, he expressed
support for recent proposals for Cambodian peace talks.
   Li also was quoted as saying that China thinks highly of the
recent U.S.-Soviet summit and hopes the superpowers will continue
serious talks over reducing strategic nuclear weapons.
   The repot said Li and Maslyukov also discussed economic reforms
in their countries.
   He said the situation varies in different socialist countries,
but many are carrying out reforms to bring into full play the
superiority of socialism.
   Maslyukov was in Beijing to attend a meeting of the
Chinese-Soviet Commission to Expand Trade, Scientific and
Technological Exchanges.
   The two sides on Wednesday also signed three documents on
economic cooperation.
   Although political relations remain cool, two-way trade has
climbed steadily. It reached $2.5 billion in 1986, up from $1.9
billion the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
