<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Phillips,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Actress' Acquittal On Drug Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress-singer Michelle Phillips'
acquittal on a possession of marijuana charge has been upheld by an
appeals court, and a prosecutor said he probably won't pursue the
case.
   Ms. Phillips, a member of the Mamas and Papas singing group in
the late 1960s, was found innocent of the drug charge by Potter
County Court-at-Law Judge Morris Overstreet, who ruled in February
that the search of Ms. Phillips' purse that yielded the majijuana
was conducted without probabe cause.
   The 7th state Court of Appeals upheld his decision on Tuesday.
   The appeal was one of the first in Texas under a constitutional
amendment in November and legislation that gives the prosecution a
limited right of appeal. Assistant Potter County Attorney Dave Kemp
said he was unlikely to continue the appeal.
   Ms. Phillips' purse was searched by two Texas Department of
Public Safety troopers. She was a passenger in an auto driven by
her boyfriend, Geoffrey L. Tozer, that the troopers stopped for
speeding on Interstate 40 near this Texas Panhandle city.
   Tozer, who consented to a car search after a single marijuana
seed was found on the car floor, was arrested but not charged.
   Ms. Phillips was charged with the misdemeanor offense of
possessing two ounces or less of marijuana, which carries a maximum
penalty of 180 days in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</TEXT>
