<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NavyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0904 06-08 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0904,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Ends in Navy Recruit Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Evidence in ..., with 2 grafs to CORRECT that
Morris, sted D'Alesio, makes recommendation on case; picks up 7th
graf: `Charged with ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy recruit described as being
literally scared to death when allegedly forced back into a rescue
training pool died by accident because ``the system broke down,''
defense lawyers argued Wednesday.
   A prosecutor, however, contended that forcing Airman Recruit Lee
Mirecki into the pool when he tried to quit the rescue course at
Pensacola Naval Air Station couldn't be blamed on the system, but
was a crime committed by people.
   ``The use of force to make people do things is not allowed by
the Uniform Code'' of Military Justice, said Lt. Cmdr. Larry D.
Wynne.
   The arguments closed a hearing into the March 2 death of the
19-year-old recruit from Appleton, Wis., at the Pensacola Naval Air
Station.
   Evidence in four days of testimony will be used by Cmdr. Daniel
J. D'Alesio Jr., the investigating officer, to make a
recommendation to Rear Adm. David Morris, chief of naval air
training, in Corpus Christi, Texas.
   Morris has 120 days from the May 10 filing of the formal
complaint to decide whether any punishment is warranted.
Recommendations can include court-martial proceedings, non-judicial
punishment or dismissal of the charges.
   Charged with involuntary manslaughter are Petty Officers 1st
Class Richard E. Blevins and David J. Smith and Petty Officers 2nd
Class Frankie D. Deaton, John W. Zelenock and Michael W. Combe, all
instructors at the Rescue Swimmer School.
   Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, the officer in charge of the school, is
accused of dereliction of duty.
   Witnesses testified Mirecki tried to quit training a month
before he died and was subsequently classified by a flight suregon
as unfit to continue training because he had a phobia about being
dragged under water.
   A clinical psychologist disagreed with the finding, and Mirecki
was returned to training through a series of errors without
obtaining a required physical examination and approval by a flight
surgeon, witnesses said.
   ``There was clearly a breakdown in the system,'' argued Lt.
Steven H. Cohen, lawyer for Blevins. ``The system broke down. It
failed Airman Recruit Mirecki.''
   ``It was a tragic accident,'' said retired Navy Capt. Ferdinand
Salomon, who represented Torchia.
   Mirecki's sister, Lynn Johansen, also of Appleton, and his
mother, Elaine Kitowski of Manitowish, Wis., attended the hearing.
They declined comment but issued a statement.
   ``We hope the information brought forth in this hearing will
bring about changes in the naval system to prevent this from ever
happening again,'' it said, in part.
   Testimony indicated Mirecki became frightened during a drill,
left the pool and held on to an equipment rack before a group of
instructors pried him loose and forced him back into the water.
   He then was taken back to the deep end in a head-hold by Combe,
according to testimony. There was conflicting evidence whether
Mirecki collapsed while in Combe's hold or broke free and put Combe
in a rescue hold, successfully completing the drill, before he
collapsed.
   Prosecutor Wynne derided the latter version as a ``B-movie
scenario'' concocted by the defense.
   ``It is unlikely anybody being frightened to death would have
the calm sense of the moment to perform a maneuver he had been
unable to do since the beginning of the drill,'' Wynne argued.
   The defense contended that physical contact was part of the
rigorous course and that it was not unusual for frightened, scared
or malingering students to be physically forced back into the pool
or pulled off its walls to resume drills.
   ``The Navy trained them in that fashion,'' said Lt. David S.
Yandle, the defense lawyer for Zelenock. ``The Navy trained them to
train in that fashion and the Navy told them their instruction
techniques were good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0248 </DOCNO>
