<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     06-08 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Violence Protesters Take Over Offices of Bishops Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of men, women and children raced
into the headquarters of the Latin American Bishops Conference in
Bogota on Wednesday and occupied the building, saying they were
protesting violence in Colombia.
   A communique issued by the protesters said they called
themselves Christians for Peace.
   An anonymous caller, claiming to be one of the protesters, told
The Associated Press a priest and a nun were being held hostage
until the demonstrators got to talk with a government
representative.
   He said there were 100 protesters, including 10 children, in the
three-story building in northern Bogota.
   Police surrounded the structure minutes after the protesters,
some with scarves wrapped around their faces, stormed inside.
   The caller said the protest was against right-wing death squads,
blamed for killing more than 800 persons in Colombia in the last
three years.
   The communique said ``we want to call attention ... to the
situation of violence that exists in Colombia.'' It asked ``the
church to intervene effectively in the mediation of the conflict,''
without specifying which conflict.
   The Roman Catholic church in Colombia has repeatedly offered to
mediate between the government and leftist guerrillas, but no rebel
group has agreed.
   The protesters demanded that Attorney General Horacio Serpa
Uribe, Cardinal Mario Revollo Bravo and others come to the occupied
building.
   The attorney general, who was in Medellin, said in a broadcast
interview with the Bogota radio station RCN that he would not talk
with them.
   University students have led the takeover of a dozen embassies
and other buildings in Bogota, the capital, in the last five years
to draw attention to protests.
</TEXT>
