longest general strike Wednesday and organizers declared it a
victory over government suppression of anti-apartheid groups.
   More than two million workers and students participated in the
three-day protest, which employers said cost the economy $250
million. At least 10 people were killed, 38 wounded or injured and
36 arrested, and many commuter buses and trains were attacked.
   Black labor federations, supported by prominent clergymen,
organized the protest to express opposition to restrictions put on
anti-apartheid groups Feb. 24 and proposed legislation that would
limit the rights of unions to strike.
