<1ST_LINE>a i PM-AfghanRefugees-Camp APPhotoPkg Adv13 06-08 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Refugees-Camp, AP Photo Pkg, Adv 13,0269</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 13, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Life in Afghan Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY600,602,603,604 of June 8. Fifth photo moving June
9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the maze-like refugee camps of
Pakistan's northwestern frontier, turbaned Afghans clad in the
pajama-like ``salwar kameez'' congregate everywhere. Women are
noticeably absent.
   The frontier province, which now is home for most of the 3.5
million refugees of the Afghan war, is a mirror image of more than
half of Afghanistan's population.
   Ethnically, the people of the frontier are of the Pashtoon
tribes. More than 60 percent of Afghans also are Pashtoons, but the
tribes are split by the Afghan-Pakistan border. The Pashtoon code
of honor that demands family, honor and religion be defended to the
death has played a major role in the Afghans' tenacity in their
10-year war.
   The ethnic minorities are many.
   The largest of these are the Hazaras, who live in Hazarajat in
north- central Afghanistan, and the Tajiks, Uzbeks and Turkomans,
who live toward the north along Afghanistan's border with the
Soviet Union. Along the northeastern border with Pakistan live the
fair-haired, light-skinned Nuristanis, who claim to be descendents
of deserters of Alexander the Great's army.
   For the most part, Afghans are farmers tilling small holdings
near their villages. The grueling heat of Pakistan contrasts
sharply to the fertile valleys and enticingly cool mountains of
Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Photos by AP Staff Photographer Jeff Widener
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 13</NOTE>
