<DOCNO> AP880608-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-AfghanRefugees-Work APPhotoPkg Adv14 06-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Refugees-Work, AP Photo Pkg, Adv 14,0317</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 14, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Eking Out Livelihood as Afghan Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY605,606,607,608,609 of June 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their hoveled shops, Afghan war
refugees who have sought asylum in Pakistan eke out a meager
existence. Anyone with something to sell slaps up a lean-to that
passes as a shop or simply squats on the side of a dusty road.
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and the World
Food Program supply food to the displaced Afghans, but the monthly
quota has never been reached.
   To supplement monthly allotments from those two relief groups
and Pakistan, the refugees open makeshift shops or take jobs in the
local community. Some Afghans prosper in exile, but they are not
the ones living in camps.
   The displacement caused by the Soviet Union's systematic
depopulation strategy in the Afghan war can be repaired, but the
human loss and injury will leave an indelible mark on Afghan
society. Widows and orphans have proliferated in the 10 years of
war.
   Attempts are made at education, but resources can't meet demand.
Improvised schools have been established. Afghan political parties
based in Peshawar have joined in the effort to educate the young. A
new generation of Afghans has been born in the camps. They know
only what they have been told.
   Hospitals, run by international aid organizations or Afghan
political parties, are overflowing with wounded and maimed. Bombs
shattered the legs of Zafar Khan, a refugee from Afghanistan's
northeastern province of Kapisa.
   He says without emotion, ``I was crippled in a bombardment.''
   Abdul Waheed lost his hand in a rocket attack.
   Their stories are not unusual.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Photos by AP Staff Photographer Jeff Widener
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 14</NOTE>
