<1ST_LINE>a i PM-AfghanRefugees-Pain APPhotoPkg Adv15 06-08 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Refugees-Pain, AP Photo Pkg, Adv 15,0279</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, June 15, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Psychological Scars Mar Refugee Children, Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos to move June 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan war refugees, haunted by
loneliness and memories of their bombed villages, their spouses or
children killed, sit for hours in the sun-baked mud homes of their
camps in Pakistan.
   The majority of the 3.5 million Afghan refugees are children,
with women making up the next largest group.
   Shrouded behind a veil or hidden behind high mud walls, women
are a society unto themselves. Transplanted from their villages,
where they openly tended their fields, to crowded camps surrounded
by strangers, Afghan women have been forced into seclusion.
   Dr. Mohammad Azam Dadfar, who runs a psychiatric center for
Afghans in Peshawar, said the exile forced on the refugees has left
millions with psychological wounds.
   If the refugees returned tomorrow to Afghanistan, the effect
would continue for years. There is a generation of psychologically
mutilated Afghans, said Dadfar. They are the children.
   Maryam was 9 years old when jets screamed over her village in
Baghland province and dumped their payload. For three days, she was
buried in the rubble of her home. Her family was dead. Afghan
guerrillas found her and brought her to Pakistan.
   In the summer, the refugee camps are treeless, parched
dustbowls; in the winter, cold damp prisons. The mortality rate
among children is high.
   ``Everyday they see their playmates die,'' Dadfar said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Photos by AP Staff Photographer Jeff Widener
</TEXT>
