<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 10,0557</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs June 10, or thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shipment of 10,000 Jewish high holy day prayer
books in Hebrew and Russian was flown to Moscow this week as a gift
to Soviet Jews by the Appeal of Conscience Foundation.
   Rabbi Arthur Schneier, foundation president, said approval for
the prayerbooks to enter the Soviet Union conformed with recent
statements of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev calling for more
tolerant attitudes toward religion.
   The interfaith foundation of Roman Catholic, Protestant, Jewish
and Eastern Orthodox leaders seeks to advance religious freedom
around the world.
   Schneier was in Moscow this week as the only American Jewish
leader invited to address ceremonies marking the 1,000th
anniversary of Christianity in what is now the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church historian Bill J. Leonard says
Southern Baptist churches increasingly are assigning more power to
the clergy, leading to a ``clergification'' of the denomination.
   Leonard, of Southern Baptist Theological Seminary, said the
trend toward autocratic leadership by pastors often threatens to
degrade the status of lay people. ``It makes the laity second-class
citizens. It undermines the most basic biblical understanding of
the church as the whole people of God.''
   He said the clergy leadership style is becoming similar to a
``chief executive officer of a corporation'' and is ``more publicly
visible in so-called superchurches, but is also quite prevalent in
smaller churches.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church Women United holds a conference here
June 16-17 on health needs of poor women and children to develop
strategies to combat the ``intolerable and scandalous''
feminization of poverty.
   Sylvia Ross Talbot, CWU president, says ``problems of health
disportionately affect women and children in poverty'' and the
extent of their plight demands a ``concerted assault'' by concerned
groups.
   The CWU is a national ecumenical organization of Protestant,
Eastern Orthodox and Roman Catholic women.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 260-member governing board of the
National Council of Churches has urged member denominations to
boycott Royal Dutch@Shell oil company until it ends operation in
South Africa or that country eliminates its apartheid racial system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Assemblies of God reports that its
number of ordained or licensed women ministers rose by 52 to 3,770
in 1987. They are among the church's 30,538 ministers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unlike some Roman Catholic dioceses that have
closed down services sponsored by the homosexual group, Dignity,
the Chicago Archdiocese simply has taken over the sponsorship.
   In doing so, Cardinal Joseph L. Bernardin said he was
``concerned that gay and lesbian Catholics receive the pastoral
care of their church'' and ``to make sure the church's teaching on
human sexuality is presented clearly.''
   Officers of Dignity, which opposes the church's condemnation of
homosexual activity, welcomed the move as providing an official
church ministry to homosexuals.
   Bernardin said the group's questioning of church teachings made
it inappropriate for the group to continue sponsoring a Mass at St.
Sebastian parish, so sponsorship was being assumed by the
archdiocese.
   A l986 Vatican document prohibited use of church facilities to
groups opposed to church teachings, and several dioceses had simply
shut down Dignity-sponsored services.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs June 10</NOTE>
