<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs June 17 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Parents Send Children on Dangerous Sea Voyages</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHANAT NIKHOM, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In March 1986, Nguyen Thi
Xuan-Sac sent her 15-year-old daughter on a boat to Thailand. Four
months later, she sent another daughter, then 11 years old, on the
same journey.
   Mrs. Xuan-Sac knew it was risky. Thousands of other Vietnamese
boat people, including her own sister in 1981, have been lost at
sea or attacked by pirates.
   But she sent the girls off anyway in the hope they would
eventually find new homes in the United States.
   The girls reached Thailand safely and now live outside
Washington, D.C., in Lanham, Md.
   ``I felt that if I died, there would be no one to take care of
my daughters,'' said Mrs. Xuan-Sac, whose husband fled Vietnam in
1976. ``And Vietnam is very poor and my daughters could not study.
... I want them to be happy.''
   Mrs. Xuan-Sac now is a refugee herself in Thailand and wants to
join her daughters in Maryland.
   Her situation is similar to that of many other Vietnamese and
Indochinese parents who have sent their children on the risky
voyages across the Gulf of Thailand in hopes they will find new
lives in the West.
   Except for the United States, however, Western nations are
reluctant to take the children.
   International aid officials are at odds among themselves over
the practice of parents sending their children away.
   Some see it as cruel, but others say what must be taken into
account is the Vietnamese value system that the future of offspring
is extremely important.
   Since the 1975 communist victories in their homelands, more than
10,000 Vietnamese, Laotian and Cambodian children under 18 years
old have made their way to United Nations-aided camps in Thailand
without parents or adult guardians. More than 1,000 of these
``unaccompanied minors'' remain in this camp near Bangkok,
Thailand's capital. An unknown number are among about 400,000
Indochinese in other Thai camps.
   Resettlement nations that refuse to accept the unaccompanied
children do so partly in the belief the parents send them off as a
precursor to their own expatriation and resettlement.
   International refugee officials call the practice an abuse of
international humanitarianism.
   Australia, for example, maintains that resettling minors only
encourages separation of families and countries should try to end
the exodus.
   Mrs. Xuan-Sac said in an interview life had been difficult since
the communists in 1975 closed the company where she worked and
ordered her family to toil on the land. She said she lost contact
with her husband after he fled in 1976 and knows only that he is
living somewhere in the United States.
   She said she never intended to follow her daughters, but then
couldn't bear the separation and made her way to Phanat Nikhom and
now wants to join them in Maryland.
   The United States, which has taken two-thirds of minors
resettled from Thailand, said in a recent policy statement it
considers the children of ``profound humanitarian concern'' because
of their vulnerability during flight and in refugee camps.
   It said the practice of purposely sending children off with the
intent of following them is ``abhorrent'' but that if families are
persecuted, the U.S. government is not concerned with whether
parents used children in this way.
   The United States attempts to resettle all minors with U.S. ties
and whose families were persecuted. It also will take half of all
other minors who demonstrate persecution in their homelands but
have no U.S. links. It also will consider ``paroling'' into the
country those with U.S. links who don't qualify as refugees.
   Some minors at a special center in Phanat Nikhom give accounts
of enduring harsh ordeals after being sent off by their parents.
   Danh Van Ha, about 7 years old, said he was on a 13-day,
storm-tossed boat journey during which pirates robbed and raped
passengers, including a woman who was taking care of him.
   Another Vietnamese boy suffered severe asthma on his journey and
was hospitalized for a long time at the camp.
   Yet the children interviewed didn't question that their parents
loved them, but instead worried about not being able to fulfill
what they see as their filial duty of getting resettled abroad.
   Bridget Messana, an American who runs the center for Thailand's
Catholic Office of Emergency Relief and Refugees, said some
children receive letters from arents angrily scolding them for
``misbehaving and taking so long'' to get resettled,
   The children here play happily, nevertheless, but Ms. Messana
said some possibly won't be able to get along with foster parents
in the United States or deal with problems likely to arise when
they're no longer in the protected environment of Phanat Nikhom.
   ``When they get to the U.S. and see the difficulty of the life
their parents sent them to, then the scars surface,'' she said.
``They've been separated. They're not in their own community. And
all of this none of their own choice.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs June 17</NOTE>
