<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv10   06-08 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 10 ,0878</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, June 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Greek Archbishop Condemns Attack on Dukakis' Religion</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The primate of the Greek Orthodox Church in the
Americas says attacks on Michael Dukakis' religious situation are
``extremely unjustified'' and that he is a steadfast son of the
church.
   ``He is a member of the church, was baptized in it and he has
never left it,'' Archbishop Iakovos says of the front-running
Democratic presidential contender, who has been assailed as ``an
apostate.''
   ``The attack is wrong in itself,'' Iakovos added in an
interview. His eyes flashed. ``It came from small people.''
   In widely distributed letters, James G. Jatras, a staff member
of the Senate Republican Policy Committee and a church layman,
called Dukakis a ``renegade, an outcast'' for his positions and his
marriage to a Jew.
   Jatras, writing under his Greek name, Dimitrios Iatreidis, said
Dukakis' church membership was ``severed by your marriage outside
the church.'' Iakovos termed that untrue.
   The white-haired archbishop, 76, who has maintained
relationships with Dukakis and his parents since his boyhood, noted
that Dukakis considers him ``his spiritual father,'' and added:
   ``We are proud that one of our young men has had the courage and
determination to run for the highest office in the nation.''
   While making no formal endorsement, avoided under church policy,
he said, ``I would put it that 99 percent of us are very proud
Dukakis is a front runner and almost certain nominee.''
   Iakovos, recalling the years 1942 to l954 when he was dean of
Boston's Annunciation Cathedral to which the Dukakis family
belonged and where he still is a regularly contributing member,
said:
   ``I remember him in his Sunday school pupil days. He was a
frequent participant as a teenager. The Dukakis family was one of
the best families in the church, his father a physician, his mother
a teacher of English.''
   Iakaovos, who has talked with Dukakis frequently over the years,
encouraging his political efforts, sometimes praying with him, said:
   ``Michael is a man who does much thinking, who doesn't react
emotionally. He has a very good head on his shoulders. He's very
learned. He is moderate, not a man of extremes. He's very prudent,
very careful, very studious.''
   Of Dukakis' marriage to a non-Christian, which under church
rules technically bars him from receiving communion (as are
divorced, remarried Roman Catholics) but does not excommunicate or
remove him from membership, Iakovos said:
   ``He did not leave the church. He is not excluded. He's not the
only one who has married outside the church.''
   The archbishop said about 70 percent of Greek Orthodox marriages
are with those of other denominations, an increasing number with
Jews.
   ``Its happening more and more now,'' he said. ``I have a
pastoral obligation to all our people, to strengthen and encourage
them.''
   He noted that Dukakis visited archdiocesan headquarters on
Manhattan's East 79th St. on April 14, took part in vespers
services and afterward met with Iakovos in his chandeliered,
second-floor offices.
   ``We had a brief service in the chapel,'' he said. ``Then we
discussed freely some of the issues.''
   Jatras made his charges in an open letter to Dukakis sent to all
Orthodox bishops and many others, as well as in letters to the
weekly Greek American which termed the attack a ``cheap political
ploy.''
   Jatras claimed Dukakis ``excommunicated himself'' by marriage to
a Jew and is ``a traitor'' who ``defames our church'' by upholding
legal abortion and opposing aid to Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   The archbishop said it ``was fanatic'' to attack a candidate's
church relationship. ``I find it extremely unjustified to make such
statements, to attack anyone running for any office on the basis of
his beliefs.
   ``In this multi-cultural, multi-national society, religion is
not one of the criteria for being elected president of the United
States.''
   While Greek Orthodoxy opposes abortion, he said Dukakis'
position resembled that of New York Governor Cuomo, a Roman
Catholic, in contending political leaders must uphold the law and
not try to impose their views about it.
   ``The president is president of all citizens, believers and
non-believers as well,'' Iakovos said. ``Any transgressions across
the border between state and church is at the expense of the unity
of the nation.''
   He said he had encouraged Dukakis' decision to seek the
presidency.
   Asked about Dukakis' religious commitment, Iakovos said ``this
is a very subjective matter,'' but Dukakis has been a steady church
member. ``He has embraced it all these years. This is not something
new. Many times, he would say I was his spiritual father.
   ``Through the campaign, I think he is feeling much closer to the
community than before.''
   He said that it seemed strange the attack about Dukakis'
religion didn't come until ``he was running for the presidency, but
then they start scrutinizing his conformity to church rules.
   ``If the man is qualified, and God wants him to be president, he
will be. Michael has some of the qualities we seek in that
position.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
