<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-FeeHunting Adv14   06-08 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fee Hunting, Adv 14,0802</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, June 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Land Access, Hunting Fees Divide Montana Sportsmen and Ranchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorents Grosfield's 15,000-acre ranch north
of Yellowstone National Park is home to deer, antelope, bear and
game birds. It's a paradise for hunters.
   Grosfield welcomes them _ if they're among the select 100
``season permit'' holders who've paid $160 apiece for the
privilege. Guests are charged $50 more each day.
   In the East, where most land ownership shifted to private hands
generations ago, such entrepreneurship might go unquestioned. But
in the vastness of Montana, which only a century ago was mostly
wild land open to all and where most land is still publicly owned,
fee-hunting and closed lands are divisive issues.
   The dispute is also being watched by sportsmen elsewhere because
of the growing pressure on available land.
   ``It's an upwelling rather than an overwhelming wave as we see
it, but it's clearly there and it's going to become more and more
important in the future,'' said Lynn Greenwalt, vice president for
resources conservation of the National Wildlife Federation in
Washington, D.C.
   The trend toward fee hunting has sparked debate between Montana
landowners protective of their property rights and sportsmen long
accustomed to easy access to land for hunting and fishing.
   Some sportsmen accuse landowners like Grosfield of trying to
usurp a natural resource for themselves.
   ``Wildlife, we feel, belongs to the whole public, not just to
the particular individual,'' said Tony Schoonen, president of the
Montana Wildlife Federation. ``If anybody takes and uses that
resource as a personal gain, it's privatization.''
   Landowners say it's a way for farmers and ranchers to make some
extra money and ease hunting pressure by controlling the number of
hunters. Grosfield said it takes time to deal with each hunter who
calls or knocks at the door.
   ``A rancher ... is essentially subsidizing the recreating public
to the extent of the time, effort and expense it takes to
accommodate that public. There's something not equitable about
that,'' he said.
   But it's more than that.
   It's also ``kind of in response to what is seen as an overly
aggressive attitude among some recreational groups to force issues
like access _ especially with the stream access thing,'' Grosfield
acknowledged.
   The ``stream access thing'' is a raw issue in Montana. In 1985,
the Legislature codified a Supreme Court decision giving sportsmen
the right to cross property lines at will if they followed streams
and stayed between the high-water marks.
   Jerome Jack, executive vice president of the Montana
Stockgrowers Association in Helena, described the decision as a
``bitter pill'' for ranchers and farmers. Many, he suggested, are
posting their lands to hunters in frustration over losing control
of their property.
   ``You have seen a lot more orange paint on gateposts and a lot
more limiting of access during the hunting season,'' Jack said. The
orange paint designates posted land.
   But most landowners who charge hunting fees are more interested
in the money than in defending the principle of private ownership,
said Bob Carlson of the Skyline Sportsmen's Club in Butte.
   ``The trend was already started'' before stream access became an
issue, said Carlson. ``I'm sure there's a lot of people who are
using that as an excuse.''
   Fee hunting also has increased the burden on property owners who
still allow free access, Schoonen said.
   ``As more and more private property owners close their land, it
throws more and more pressure on adjacent landowners who do allow
hunting, until they throw up their hands'' and decide to close
their lands as well, he said. ``It's like a domino effect. You see
it happening all over.''
   And some landowners, while not charging a fee, have restricted
the numbers of hunters they'll allow on their land.
   Grosfield began charging fees four years ago. Before that, he
said, it got to the point where he was simply overwhelmed by
hunters.
   ``We had a terrific amount of pressure _ between 800 and 1,000
hunter days per year. Now, in looking back on it, I just shake my
head when I think about accommodating that many.''
   Many private landowners, of course, continue to welcome hunters
as long as they ask permission and conduct themselves properly.
   ``We have full, open access and it's unusual to have problems,''
said rancher Joe Etchart of Glasgow. ``We have some irritants _ cut
fences and things like that _ but it's a relatively small amount
compared to the traffic.''
   But Carlson fears fee-hunting ``is going to do away with hunting
as we have known it in the past.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, June 14</NOTE>
