<HEAD>Adv12</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 11-12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Conference on Reservation Brings Indian, Non-Indian Youths</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Together
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty teen-agers from 22 states join 40
South Dakota Indian youths Saturday to live together for a week on
the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation.
   The plan is to have them share heritages of religion, legend and
song. The hope is that the friendships formed will give them fresh
appreciation of their nation's diversity, and each individual's
worth.
   ``The whole idea is to address prejudice and discrimination in a
very subtle way,'' said Rose Marie Ohm of the National Conference
of Christians and Jews, which is sponsoring the event.
   ``It's like a big rainbow. By interacting through direct
contact, they learn to appreciate each other, how to work
together.''
   The National Conference of Christians and Jews, a non-profit
organization that works to improve communication and understanding
among conflicting groups in American society, has chosen 40
students from different backgrounds and regions of the country to
attend the youth conference.
   The United Sioux Tribes helped select Indian students from 12
tribes who live on reservations and in urban areas around South
Dakota to attend the conference, being held at the high school in
Pine Ridge.
   The Pine Ridge reservation is a region of rolling, grassy hills
topped with pine trees in southwestern South Dakota. Its territory
includes Shannon County, one of the poorest in the nation.
   Pine Ridge School Principal Imogene Horse said the meeting
should help Indian teen-agers better understand young people from
other parts of the country. Some of the students cannot afford to
travel, she said, so they haven't had much contact with people from
outside western South Dakota.
   ``I think it will be good for the Indian students beause of the
isolation factor out here,'' the principal said. ``I believe the
students and adults who attend this will learn much about each
other's cultures.''
   Ohm said the National Conference of Christians and Jews sponsors
other conferences aimed at helping young people develop leadership
skills. Participants have included Indian youths in the past, but
the Pine Ridge event is ``the first time on Indian turf,'' said
Harry Robinson, NCCJ vice president for communications.
   The conference has a theme of ``Educating for the 21st Century:
Rights, Risks and Responsibilities,'' and is designed to help the
students sharpen the skills to become leaders in a diverse socity,
Ohm said. They will work to find their own ideas for addressing the
problems of the future, she said.
   Daily workshops will deal with cultural awareness, racial
understanding, friendships, dating, family relationships and other
issues faced by all young people. By living together, the high
school juniors and seniors will also learn to get along with people
from other backgrounds, Ohm said.
   On Sunday evening, the students will fill a poster spanning two
walls at the school with their names, races, ethnic identities and
a dozen other categories, giving ``a visual representation of their
diversity,'' Ohm said.
   On the final full day of the Pine Ridge conference, June 16,
students from various ethnic groups will give presentations on
their cultures. The Indians of Pine Ridge will present a special
program.
   Arthur Zimiga, who works with a United Methodist Church program
in Rapid City to help Indian youth learn job and social skills they
need in today's world, helped recruit the Indian participants.
   The meeting should help the South Dakota students realize the
state and its Indian reservations are not isolated islands, but
instead a part of the rest of the nation, Zimiga said.
   ``These young people should have an opportunity to be a part of
the decision-making process and also to have an opportunity to
lead,'' Zimiga said.
   One of the students who will attend the conference, Mark Pakula,
a 17-year-old from Leawood, Kan., said he hoped to get a better
undertanding of people from different races and backgrounds.
   ``Everyone is a person, and they really shouldn't be treated any
differently,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend editions, June 11-12</NOTE>
</DOC>
