<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-08 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0513</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans increased their installment
borrowing at an annual rate of 7 percent in April as growth in
consumer credit slowed from the first three months of the year, the
government said.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday that consumers took out
$3.65 billion more in credit than they paid off in April, compared
with net growth of $5.2 billion in March, $5.0 billion in February
and $6.2 billion in January.
   The annual rate of growth in April was below the 7.2 percent
rate for all of 1987 and the approximately 10.7 percent pace for
the first quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers' confidence has climbed to its highest
point since 1969 as low inflation and a strong job market have left
people ``somewhat euphoric,'' an economic research group said.
   The Conference Board said Tuesday that its Consumer Confidence
Index jumped 3.5 points to 119.2 in the May survey. That was up
16.2 points over its level of a year earlier and the highest since
December 1969, when it stood at 126.0.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 30-year, fixed-rate home
mortgages climbed in May for the second consecutive month,
encouraging Americans to turn to adjustable-rate mortgages, the
government says.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board on Tuesday reported the
national average for conventional, single-family loans jumped to
10.63 percent in early May, up from 10.48 percent in early April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earnings at the nation's commercial banks are
rebounding from the worst year since the Depression in every region
of the country except the Southwest, the government said.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said Tuesday the 13,541
banks it insures collectively earned $5 billion in the first three
months of this year, down somewhat from $5.3 billion in the same
period in 1987.
   However, earnings would have hit a record high if not for the
$1.49 billion loss at one Dallas banking company, said FDIC
Chairman L. William Seidman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is chipping away at its mammoth trade surplus
by expanding imports and overseas investment but the United States
has yet to adequately address its own foreign trade imbalance, the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry said.
   In a report released Tuesday on Japan's foreign trade in 1987,
MITI said structural changes in the country's economy, combined
with the yen's appreciation against the U.S. dollar, have led to
increased imports and slower growth in exports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional efforts to enact the omnibus
trade bill over President Reagan's veto are doomed unless sponsors
can switch a handful of votes before Wednesday's showdown on the
Senate floor, leaders said.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., told reporters
Tuesday he could not change the votes and could only hope that
last-minute home-state pressure would cause three senators to
relent and provide the two-thirds margin needed to override
Reagan's veto of the trade bill.
</TEXT>
