<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. has promised to give its
stockholders a third of the $5 billion it expects to raise from
asset sales as part of its bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   The White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant said Tuesday the
distribution would come in the form of a share buyback or some
other ``direct shareholder participation or distribution,'' and
would be made by the end of this year.
   Texaco said the distribution ``may involve cash or the use of
securities.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have proposed reducing
workplace exposure limits for 234 toxic chemicals and bringing 168
others under government regulation in what it called the largest
action of its type.
   In making the announcement Tuesday, the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration estimated the proposed regulations would
reduce job-related fatalities among some 17 million workers now
exposed to the chemicals by 500 a year and illnesses by another
55,000 annually from cancer, respiratory, cardiovascular and liver
and kidney diseases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appellate court has lifted an
injunction barring Eastern Airlines from selling its Northeast
shuttle operation to another subsidiary of its parent company,
Texas Air Corp.
   On Tuesday, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here lifted a
contempt citation issued against Eastern but gave a union
challenging the shuttle sale 10 days to seek a temporary
restraining order to stop it.
   The Machinists union contend Texas Air is trying to spin off
various components of the financially troubled carrier to undermine
the power of unions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners, a New York investment firm,
says it has accumulated a 4.9 percent stake in takeover target
Macmillan Inc. and wants to see the publishing giant sold to the
highest bidder.
   The partnership filed an affidavit Tuesday in Delaware Chancery
Court supporting Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass's effort to block
Macmillan's planned restructuring.
   Bass was rebuffed in his latest effort to acquire the publishing
and information systems company for $1.9 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International bankers and businessmen say the
stage is being set for the eventual creation of a universal banking
system, which would offer a variety of financial services to
customers around the globe.
   Rainer E. Gut, chairman of Credit Suisse in Zurich, said Tuesday
that the bank of the future will have to change its business
strategy by becoming more competitive and aggressive.
   His remarks were directed to the International Monetary
Conference, whose three-day meeting began Monday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground Tuesday as the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials fell 20.62 to 2,054.59.
   Bond prices turned broadly lower, and the dollar finished
slightly lower.
   Corn futures advanced strongly and soybeans finished slightly
higher on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</TEXT>
