<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     06-08 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumers' Confidence Reported High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The confidence of American consumers jumped in May to its
highest level since the end of the 1960s, according to a Conference
Board report that could bode well for future economic growth.
   The Conference Board, a business-supported research group, says
its monthly Consumer Confidence Index does a better job of
predicting growth than the government's Index of Leading Economic
Indicators.
   In other economic news Tuesday, the government said Americans
increased their installment borrowing at a moderate annual rate of
7 percent in April as growth in consumer credit slowed from the
first three months of the year.
   And in another report, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said
interest rates on 30-year, fixed-rate home mortgages climbed in May
for the second consecutive month. The national average for
conventional, single-family loans jumped to 10.63 percent in early
May, up from 10.48 percent in early April, it said.
   Stock prices fell as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up
118.77 points over the past five sessions, dropped 20.62 to
2,054.59. Bond prices also sank in reaction to renewed fears of
inflation.
   Consumers' confidence seems to be the result of low unemployment
and low inflation, said Fabian Linden, executive director of the
Conference Board's Consumer Research Center.
   Nevertheless, the optimism was somewhat surprising in light of a
report Monday by the Bureau of Labor Statistics that said
Americans' pay in the first three months of 1988 failed to keep
them ahead of inflation for the fifth consecutive quarter.
   Not since the spiraling inflation of 1979-81 have workers gone
so long without an improvement in their standard of living through
wage gains, the bureau said.
   The board's Consumer Confidence Index jumped 3.5 points to 119.2
in the May survey. That was up 16.2 points over its level of a year
earlier and the highest since December 1969, when it stood at 126.0.
   The Conference Board commissions a monthly survey of 5,000
households throughout the United States.
   ``All of the ingredients that give the consumer a sense of
well-being are working together at this moment,'' Linden said.
   The index has been kept since January 1969 and was recently
recalibrated against a base of 100 points in 1985.
   In its report on installment borrowing, the Federal Reserve
Board said consumers took out $3.65 billion more in credit than
they paid off in April, compared with net growth of $5.2 billion in
March, $5.0 billion in February and $6.2 billion in January.
   The annual rate of growth in April was slightly slower than the
7.2 percent rate for all of 1987 and considerably slower than the
approximately 10.7 percent pace for the first quarter of 1988.
   However, economists saw the slowing as a healthy trend at a time
when U.S. manufacturers are trying to boost their production for
export.
   ``What's happened is what should be happening. Consumer spending
is cooling off and freeing up resources to produce for export,''
said Sandra Shaber, an economist with the Futures Group, a
Washington consulting firm.
   ``The whole transition from a consumer-led economy to an
export-led economy assumes we can cool off consumer demand in order
to avoid heated up inflation,'' she said.
</TEXT>
