<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexacoSales Bjt   06-08 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco Sales, Bjt,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Promises Part of $5 Billion Asset-Sales Proceeds To
Shareholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. says it plans to give its
shareholders a third of the proceeds from the $5 billion it plans
to raise by the end of the year in sales of assets as part of its
restructuring plan.
   But the White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant said Tuesday that it
had not decided how the distribution would be made, promising
either a stock buyback program or some other method.
   ``The distribution may involve cash or the use of securities, in
anticipation of the proceeds to be realized from the sales
program,'' Texaco said in a statement.
   The rest of the proceeds will be used to repay debt, strengthen
the balance sheet and fund increased capital investment programs
for selected retained operations, it added.
   The move, which came in the midst of a proxy fight between
Texaco and takeover specialist Carl C. Icahn, stirred little
enthusiasm on Wall Street. In consolidated nationwide trading of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, Texaco closed at $51 per
share, up 12{ cents.
   Richard S. Pzena, who studies oil companies for the Sanford C.
Bernstein & Co. securites firm, said traders took a dim view of the
move because ``it's not like they're giving the shareholders
something they don't already own.''
   Icahn is running a five-man slate for the board of directors,
hoping to a victory will help him get the board to let shareholders
vote on his $60-per-share cash offer for the company. The votes are
to be cast at Texaco's annual meeting on June 17.
   By adding some value to shares already hovering in the $50
range, Texaco in effect was diluting the impact of Icahn's $60 cash
offer, Pzena said, thereby strengthening its chances of beating
Icahn in the proxy fight.
   Texaco's latest announcement came just 24 hours after it said it
had agreed to sell its 99.12 percent interest in Deutsche Texaco AG
of West Germany to a major utility in that country.
   Rheinish-Westfaelisches Elektrizitaetswerk AG, also known as
RWE, agreed to pay over $1.2 billion for the subsidiary. Both sides
expect no problems with a requirement that West Germany's Federal
Cartel Office approve the transaction.
   Updating its progress in other aspects of its reorganization
plan, Texaco said Tuesday it expected to generate more than $1.8
billion more in two other upcoming transactions.
   One is a deal to sell 60 million barrels of oil and gas
equivalent reserves, expected to close by the end of this month.
The other involves proposals to establish joint ventures with
Venezuela and Saudi Arabia.
   The ventures, which were ``in advanced stages of review,'' would
involve three Texaco refineries and related marketing facilities on
the East and Gulf coasts.
   Studies are also continuing on what to do with its 78 percent
interest in Texaco Canada Inc., including the possible sale, merger
or joint venture of some or all of the stake, Texaco said.
   In addition, it said it was considering the potential sales of
other domestic oil and gas properites of marginal value to the
company, as well as certain European and African holdings.
   The restructuring program is also expected to yield more than
$50 million in additional savings in overhead from staff
consolidations, Texaco said.
   The latest developments are a result of months of negotiations
that began as Texaco prepared for its April emergence from a year
under Chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection.
   In April 1987, Texaco filed for that protection to avoid having
to post an $11 billion security bond while appealing a $10.3
billion judgment held against it by Pennzoil Co. A jury ruled
Texaco had interfered with Pennzoil's 1984 attempt to acquire part
of Getty Oil Co. so it could buy Getty itself.
   In December, Texaco agreed to settle the suit by paying $3
billion to Pennzoil as part of a restructuring plan that included
sales of $3 billion worth of assets.
   Soon afterward, Icahn, its largest stockholder with 14.8 percent
of the company's shares, stepped up pressure on Texaco's management
to do more to increase the value of its stock.
   In March, he threatened to run his slate of five candidates,
including himself, for Texaco's board, if the company did not take
steps that would raise the price to $55 per share from then-current
levels in the $35-to-$45 range.
   In an apparent bid for stockholder support, Texaco announced the
restoration of its dividend and an expansion of its planned asset
sales to $5 billion a month later.
   But Icahn, unsatisfied, proceeded with his $60-per-share offer
for those Texaco shares he does not already known, and launched his
threatened proxy fight.
</TEXT>
