<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-08 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Recover from Selloff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices bounced back but remain within a
range where the market has hovered recently in anticipation of the
OPEC meeting beginning this weekend.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for July delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at
$17.37 per 42-gallon barrel Tuesday, up 11 cents. The contract had
dropped 24 cents on Monday.
   Among July contracts for refined products, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled up 0.47 cents at 50.20 cents a gallon, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 46.23 cents a gallon, up 0.39 cent.
   Contracts for refined products also had been off sharply in the
previous session.
   Traders said the rebound was simply a reaction to the earlier
selloff and was not based on any significant news development. The
market has been trading in a relatively narrow range, well below
the official $18 price set for oil produced by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``More than anything, the market continues to have a bearish
attitude (about the upcoming meeting),'' said Richard Redoglia of
Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   The regular mid-year meeting, which opens Saturday in Vienna,
Austria, is expected to focus on the cartel's production quotas and
price-support mechanisms.
