<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoRecall     06-08 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Recall,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Ends Challenge to Emissions Recall of 93,000 1981
Vehicles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has agreed to begin recalling and
repairing 93,000 of its 1981-model small cars in August to meet a
1986 Environmental Protection Agency emissions recall order, the
EPA said.
   The federal agency ordered the recall of the Dodge Omni and 024
and the Plymouth Horizon and TC3, all with 1.7-liter engines and
manual transmissions, because tests showed emissions levels
exceeded standards.
   Tests showed emissions levels of 1.4 grams per mile while the
standard for 1981 was 1 gram per mile. The EPA said Tuesday it
believed excess emissions resulted from deteriorating catalytic
converters.
   Chrysler initially chose to contest the order, charging the
tests were not conducted properly. But Chrysler withdrew its
challenge and agreed instead to recall and repair the vehicles.
   The repair will include modifying the vacuum line to the
engine's electronic spark-control computer.
   Chrysler's withdrawal of its challenge was the second since EPA
began recalling vehicles for emissions repairs in 1972.
   In May, General Motors Corp. withdrew a challenge to a 1985
order, and the vehicles involved will be recalled in September, the
EPA said.
</TEXT>
