<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar posted modest losses against most major
foreign currencies in Europe early today in moderately active
trading. Gold bullion fell.
   Market players sold dollars because of uncertainty over next
week's report on the seasonally adjusted U.S. trade gap for April,
traders said.
   But they said concern that central banks would intervene to
prevent a sudden drop in the dollar was providing a floor for the
currency.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7139 West German marks, down from 1.7143; 1.4290
Swiss francs, up from 1.4277; 5.7905 French francs, down from
5.7910; 1.9220 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9245; 1,272.95 Italian
lire, down from 1,273.10; and 1.2238 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2318.
   The dollar fell against the British pound, which was quoted at
$1.8220, compared with Tuesday's $1.8130.
   The dollar weakened in Tokyo, closing at 125.32 Japanese yen,
down from 125.77 yen. In London trading later Wednesday, the dollar
slipped to 125.11 yen.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $458.75 a troy ounce, down from $463.50 late Tuesday.
A trader said gold fell overnight in reaction to a drop in grain
prices. The metal was boosted last week by a rally in the
commodities market.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid of $458.50, down from $463.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $458.98, down
from $464.03.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $7.20, down from
$7.34.
</TEXT>
