<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0739EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-08 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down As Are Stock Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its downward swing against the
Japanese yen in trading in Tokyo today, while stock prices declined
moderately.
   The dollar closed at 125.32 yen, down 0.45 yen from Tuesday's
finish, but slightly higher than its opening level of 125.27 yen.
   ``The dollar was stable, trading between 125.15 and 125.35 yen
throughout the day,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank.
   The dollar has continued to lose ground in Tokyo since it closed
above the 126-yen mark last Friday for the first time in about two
months.
   Another dealer attributed the dollar's narrow range in part to a
wait-and-see attitude of participants awaiting the release of U.S.
trade figures for April, due out next week.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 28.92 points Tuesday, shed another
54.67 points, or 0.19 percent, to end the day at 27,912.65.
   ``Profit-taking eased the Nikkei index a little, but the market
is maintaining its strength without a sense among investors that it
is overheating,'' said Fumihiko Morimoto of First Boston.
   Other traders said the market had been prepared to take a rest,
and a setback on Wall Street Tuesday gave investors one more
incentive to sit out the day's trading.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 1.8
billion shares, down from 2.2 billion shares Tuesday. Activity
slowed in the afternoon, however, with only 700 million shares
changing hands.
   Declining issues included electricals, automobiles and precision
machineries. Chemicals and non-ferrous metal stocks also moved
lower. Advancers included railways and steels.
</TEXT>
