<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Macmillan-Coniston 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan-Coniston, 1st Ld-Writethru,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Rejects Bass Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with Macmillan rejecting Bass offer. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover target Macmillan Inc. today rejected
proposals by Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass to acquire the
publishing company for $1.9 billion or to participate in its
planned restructuring.
   In a statement, Macmillan said its board of directors reaffirmed
its belief that its own restructuring plan is in the best interests
of shareholders.
   The plan would split the company in two and pay shareholders a
special dividend of $52.35 a share. The dividend is scheduled to be
paid Friday.
   But in a lawsuit filed in Delaware Chancery Court, Bass, who
owns about 9.1 percent of Macmillan's roughly 26 million
outstanding shares, is seeking a temporary restraining order to
halt the payout.
   Separately on Tuesday, the investment firm Coniston Partners
disclosed it has accumulated a 4.9 percent stake in Macmillan and
filed an affidavit in support of Bass's effort to block the
dividend payout.
   Augustus Oliver, a principal of the aggressive firm, said
Coniston is not acting in concert with Bass and only wants to see
the publishing and information services company sold to the highest
bidder.
   Oliver would not comment on whether Coniston is positioning
itself to engage in a bidding war with Bass.
   ``We're interested in seeing a full auction for the company and
having it sold to the highest bidder,'' he said. Oliver said
Macmillan's value is more in the neighborhood of $85 to $100 a
share, while many analysts have suggested $85 a share might be a
top price.
   ``We believe that Macmillan's restructuring is an inappropriate
response to Bass's bid, and that it's a flagrant abuse of the
board's fiduciary duty,'' Oliver said.
   As an alternative to his $73-a-share cash bid, Bass proposed a
similar restructuring that also would split Macmillan into two
publicly held companies. But his plan would pay shareholders a
$58-a-share dividend.
   Macmillan said its restructuring ``doubly rewards shareholders
by bringing them significant immediate value and the opportunity to
participate in the future of two high-growth, publicly traded
investment opportunities.''
   In addition to the dividend, shareholders would receive for each
Macmillan share a half-share of common stock in Macmillan
Information Co. and $4.50 in principal amount of Macmillan
Information subordinated debentures.
   The company would be split into Macmillan Publishing Co. and
Macmillan Information.
   In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange today, Macmillan
was up 50 cents a share at $76.
   Analysts have said Bass's initial $64-a-share bid, made last
month, as well as Macmillan's restructuring, still left room for a
third party interested in competing for the company.
   This is the first time Coniston has surfaced since its recent,
unsuccessful proxy battle for four seats on the board of Gillette
Co. The partnership typically purchases a large stake in a company
and then pressures management to restructure or take some other
action to boost the price of its stock.
   Coniston successfully used that tactic last year with United
Airline's parent, which spun off its Westin hotels, Hilton
International and Hertz car rental operations as a result.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0287 </DOCNO>
