<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Say Lifting Of Shuttle Ban No Big Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf with details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appellate court's decision to lift an
injunction barring Eastern Airlines from selling its Northeast
shuttle operation is not a great setback, attorneys for two of
Eastern's unions agree.
   ``There's no emergency here,'' said James L. Linsey, who
represents the Air Line Pilots Association.
   ``Our view is that it comes down to a very narrow procedural
decision,'' said Joseph Guerrieri Jr., an attorney for the
International Association of Machinists, which filed the suit in
which the injunction was issued.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington Tuesday lifted a
contempt citation issued against Eastern but gave the machinists 10
days to seek a temporary restraining order to stop the airline from
selling the popular shuttle to another subsidiary of its parent
company, Texas Air Corp.
   Even if Eastern ultimately wins, it still must face a lawsuit
brought by the pilots union, which has persuaded another federal
judge to halt the transfer of ``work opportunities'' from Eastern
to other companies.
   Lawyers for both sides agreed to a timetable for proceedings
that will keep the shuttle transaction on hold until the company
gives the court 10 days notice of the closing of the transaction.
That notification would not come until August 26, according to
Bruce Hicks, a spokesman for Texas Air.
   In March, U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt, ruling on the suit
filed by the Machinists, said Eastern had flouted a July 1987 order
he had issued barring the carrier from transferring 6,000 ground
crew members to another subsidiary by taking steps to sell the
Eastern air shuttle.
   Tuesday, a three-judge panel directed Pratt to conduct further
hearings if the machinists continue their challenge to determine if
an injunction barring the sale is warranted.
   The court found no basis for Pratt to cite Eastern for contempt
of court and held that the proposed $225 million shuttle sale was
not precluded by Pratt's earlier injunction.
   The panel also concluded unanimously that Pratt had made an
incomplete factual finding when issuing a new injunction against
selling the Boston-New York-Washington shuttle.
   The machinists union, which represents 13,000 Eastern employees,
contends Texas Air is trying to break up Eastern's components to
weaken the power of the unions at the financially troubled carrier.
   Charles Bryan, president of Eastern's machinists local, called
the appeals court ruling ``disappointing because it's going to be
more costly, and it will entail more legal fees and litigation. But
we have absolute confidence in our legal postion.''
   Bryan said the appeals court based its dismissal of the
injunction on procedural matters only, and now that the case has
been remanded to Pratt, the temporary restraining order will be
judged on its merits.
   ``It's difficult to comprehend how a judge who has already held
them in contempt will turn around and go and sell it,'' he added at
a Miami news conference.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said, ``We are pleased with the
decision and are studying its implications.''
   The decision is the latest chapter in a series of bitter legal
battles between Eastern and its unions. Texas Air, headed by Frank
Lorenzo, acquired Eastern in 1986. It also operates Continental
Airlines.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
