<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board of Trade, Open</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade on reports of
some long-overdue rain in western and southern Iowa.
   Des Moines received nearly 1.8 inches of rain overnight, which
helped drought-stressed crops there. But the showers were spotty
and weather forecasts called for a return to unseasonably warm, dry
conditions.
   ``I don't think the drought's back is broken,'' said Richard
Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   Rain was falling in west-central Illinois this morning and light
rains also were expected in Missouri and the Mississippi Delta
region. But most of the Grain Belt was expected to remain dry, and
a return to hot temperatures was forecast for the weekend.
   Grain and soybean futures prices have skyrocketed to four-year
highs in reaction to the dryness in the Midwest, making traders
edgy about even minor changes in the weather picture, Loewy said.
   ``At these price levels, everyone's going to be extremely
nervous,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 4{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.73{ a bushel; corn was 3 cents
to 4 cents lower with July at $2.53} a bushel; oats were { cent to
2 cents lower with July at $2.21 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to
10\ cents lower with July at $8.73 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .50 cent lower with June at 73.10
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .25 cent higher with
August at 76 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .72 cent lower
with June at 52.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.25
cents lower to .13 cent higher with July at 55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed Tuesday.
</TEXT>
