<1ST_LINE>a f BC-OpenOffice Adv13   06-08 0957</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Open Office, Adv 13,0985</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday June 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>World's Largest Office Furniture Company Moves From Desks To
Dynamics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may look more like a coffee klatch
than researchers hard at work on a new product, but that's the
whole idea.
   The concept of group decision-making triggered by spontaneous
encounters is shaping the design of a $75 million research and
development center being built at Steelcase Inc., the world's
leading designer and manufacturer of office furniture.
   Not only does the new seven-story, pyramid-shaped building
represent a shift in Steelcase's own corporate culture; the company
also hopes to market the concept of group creativeness to its
customers.
   ``Buying new furniture and computers won't get people to be more
productive,'' company spokesman Peter Jeff said. ``Customers are
coming to us with a larger agenda. They want to understand how they
can work better and how their people can work better.
   ``But before we can be the office environment company for anyone
else, we have to be it for ourselves.''
   Though teamwork and spontaneous meetings are nothing new, it's
unusual for a company of Steelcase's size to tinker with success.
The 76-year-old company had about $1.5 billion in sales last year.
It controls about a quarter of the office furniture market,
according to Annasses it on to the next person,'' Veneklasen said.
   ``We're taking the rugby team approach. The designers, the
engineers, the manufacturing people, the marketing people and the
corporate communications people will ... pass the ball back and
forth, but all going in the same direction at the same time.''
   The 573,000-foot building will feature state-of-the-art
laboratories for perfecting the office environment, including
research on office acoustics, lighting and temperature control.
   Steelcase has said the center will serve as a springboard for
its future plans: to add 8,000 employees to its worldwide work
force of 17,500 by the turn of the century.
   It sees the consulting service as a natural extension of its
existing business, where single chairs carry price tags of up to
$900 and big orders for major companies can run into the hundreds
of thousands of dollars. Jeff says Steelcase plans no extra charge
to customers for its logistical advice.
   Indeed, such consulting is fast becoming a popular addition to
the industry's sales pitch.
   ``It's not just a question of putting in a desk and a couple of
file cabinets anymore,'' said Simon De Groot, communications
director for National Office Products Association in Alexandria,
Va. ``The aim now is to create an environment that allows office
workers to take full advantage of new technology and be as
productive as possible.''
   But when it comes to advising clients, is Steelcase's open style
for everyone? Some researchers say the concept of group
creativeness, at the heart of Japanese industry, may not work in a
society where individualism is king.
   ``It's like changing somebody's religion,'' said William K.
Redmon, an assistant professor at Western Michigan who has been
studying how well U.S. companies are adjusting to Japanese work
practices.
   Even for Steelcase, the team approach may make some managers
uncomfortable.
   ``It's going to take time for everybody to get used to it,''
admitted Veneklasen.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday June 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
