<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Commodities-Violations     06-08 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commodities-Violations,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CFTC Accuses Refco, Paragon Of Trading Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission has
accused Refco Inc., one of the world's largest trading firms, of 11
commodities law violations.
   In addition to Chicago-based Refco, the federal regulatory
agency's administrative complaint named nine individuals and the
Paragon Futures Association, a defunct company whose trades were
guaranteed by Refco.
   Woodstock, Ill.-based Paragon and four individuals settled the
administrative charges Tuesday without admitting wrongdoing. The
charges against Refco and five other people will go to a formal
hearing.
   The CFTC's complaint alleges that in 1985 the firms and
individuals made unauthorized trades in customers' accounts, failed
to supervise employees and violated record-keeping and disclosure
rules.
   The most serious charge is ``churning,'' which means trading a
customer's account often _ and often unprofitably _ just to
generate commissions for brokers.
   Refco said 12 of Paragon's customers were affected by the
alleged churning.
   Most of the charges involved Paragon and its employees, the CFTC
said. Paragon closed shop in July 1985 after customer complaints of
churning.
   Refco said it refused to settle the charges with the CFTC
because it should not be punished for the wrongdoing of another
firm. Refco also said it ``terminated'' Paragon after hearing
complaints of churning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CatastrophicHealth     06-08 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catastrophic Health,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Set To Approve Catastrophic Health Insurance Measure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped after vote, expected about 6 p.m. EDT. Also on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate scheduled final congressional
approval late Wednesday on a catastrophic health insurance bill
that provides additional financial protection for 29 million
elderly Americans on Medicare.
   The House adopted a conference committee compromise by a 328-72
vote last week and similarly overwhelming Senate approval was
assured.
   With the major debate behind and dozens of compromises long
since reached, the Senate scheduled only 45 minutes for the formal,
finishing touch that was set to send the measure to the White House
for President Reagan's expected signature.
   Although there has been no formal word from the White House,
Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen has said he will
ask the president to sign the measure.
   The major portion of the bill, the first significant expansion
of Medicare since the program was born 23 years ago, takes effect
next Jan. 1.
   However, some parts _ such as the first-ever general
prescription drug benefit under Medicare _ are to be phased in over
four years.
   In addition to the historic nature of the benefit expansion, the
bill has particular significance in the way it is financed.
   The beneficaries are expected to pay all of of the additional
costs. On top of a flat monthly premium to be assessed on every
Medicare beneficiary _ $4.00 a month to start _ the estimated 40
percent of the elderly with enough income to be liable for federal
income taxes will be charged a supplemental premium based on their
ability to pay.
   In general, an individual would have to have an annual income of
more than $10,000 before being subject to the additional premium,
which amounts to a tax surcharge.
   Although expanded considerably as it worked its way through
Congress, the final bill is based on a proposal put forth more than
a year ago by Reagan at the urging of Bowen.
   It provides full hospital coverage after a once-a-year
deductible estimated at $564 in 1989 and indexed to hospital
inflation. Medicare now pays full charges for no more than 59 days
a year and the recipient is subject to a deductible for each
hospitalization.
   The cap on costs for physicians is $1,370 a year. After a $75
deductible, Medicare now pays 80 percent of approved doctor bills
and that part of the program remains intact. Starting in 1989,
however, the $75 deductible and the 20 percent share paid by
beneficiaries counts toward the $1,370 cap. After that is reached,
Medicare pays 100 percent of approved doctor bills.
   However, the beneficiary will remain liable for any portion of
doctor bills that exceed the fees approved by Medicare.
   In a new benefit, Medicare will pay half of outpatient
prescription drug costs in 1991 after a $600 deductible is met. The
government share rises to 60 percent in 1992 and 80 percent in
1993. However, the deductible is expected to rise each year to keep
pace with rising drug costs.
   Medicare now does not cover outpatient drugs except for a
handful of very expensive ones such as anti-rejection medication
for organ transplant recipients.
   The so-called supplemental premium starts at $22.50 a year for
each $150 of income tax owed in 1989, climbing to an additional $42
a year on each $150 of tax liability by 1993. There is an $800 cap
on the supplemental premium in 1989, climbing to $1,050 in 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880608-0293 </DOCNO>
