<HEAD>London Shares Rise 8 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices moved higher Wednesday as early
nervousness was overcome in the last hour of trading by a stronger
showing on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 8
points, or 0.4 percent, to close at 1,828.2, its highest level for
the session.
   The day's low was 6.9 points down, which came in the first hour
of trading.
   Trading volume was a modest 391.8 million shares, compared with
Tuesday's 557.4 million issues.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 22.21
points at 2,076.80 at the close of London trading.
   Dealers said the positive showing on Wall Street helped buoy
sentiment.
   The market ``behaved very well and we're seeing evidence of
institutional buying once again,'' said Anthony Abrahams, managing
director of U.K. equities at Smith New Court in London.
   Charles Larkham, an equity strategist at James Capel and Co.,
said the 100-share index, by remaining firmly above the 1,800
level, was ``building a base from which it can hopefully make a
more determined leap higher in the not-too-distant future.
   ``It's been a quiet day but the flavor is optimistic,'' Larkham
said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index rose 10.1 points to 1,455.2.
   The Financial Times 500-share index gained 4.38 points to close
at 1,030.93.
