<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NewspaperSold     06-08 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Newspaper Sold,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawaiian Company Agrees To Buy Knoxville Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hawaiian company has agreed to buy the
Knoxville Journal, one of the city's two daily newspapers, it was
reported Wednesday.
   Persis Corp., parent company of the Honolulu Advertiser, has
agreed in principle to buy the afternoon newspaper from
McKinney-McMahan Newspapers Inc., the Journal said. The purchase is
expected to close the first of August, the newspaper said. The
price was not disclosed.
   ``The Persis group is a quality news organization that will be a
great asset to Knoxville,'' said Ron McMahan, who is publisher and
editor of the Journal.``They have the financial resources to take
an outstanding newspaper and make it even greater.''
   Bill McKinney, who is publisher and general manager of the
44,000-circulation newspaper, said the purchase was arranged
because ``Ron and I have chosen to go in different directions in
our lives.''
   Persis Corp., based in Honolulu, also owns Northwest Media Inc.
and publishes the Journal-American in Bellevue, Wash., and the
Peninsula Daily News in Port Angeles as well as several weeklies in
the Northwest.
   The Honolulu Advertiser, with a circulation of 95,000, is the
largest newspaper in the Persis group.
   Two years ago McKinney and McMahan bought the Journal from
Gannett Co. for about $25 million. The same year the Journal and
the Knoxville News-Sentinel, currently the city's morning paper,
switched publishing cycles. The News-Sentinel is owned by the
Cincinnati-based Scripps-Howard chain.
   Under a joint operating agreement the Journal is printed and
circulated by the Knoxville News-Sentinel Co.
   In 1981 Gannett purchased majority interest in the newspaper
from the Roy N. Lotspeich family.
</TEXT>
