<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Against Most Currencies, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AM version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most major currencies
in European trading Wednesday, but lost ground against the British
pound. Gold closed lower in dull trading.
   Dealers said uncertainties about upcoming U.S. trade figures for
April, scheduled to be released Tuesday, kept the dollar in a tight
range for most of the session.
   ``The market will continue to be nervous at least until next
week's trade figures,'' said one Frankfurt trade
   The dollar fell against the pound in London late Wednesday. At
the market's closing, it cost $1.8175 to buy one pound, more
expensive than $1.8130 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.45 yen to a closing 125.32 yen from Tuesday's
125.77. Later, in London, it was quoted at a slightly lower rate of
125.23 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.7183 West German marks, up from 1.7143; 1.4350 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4277; 5.7923 French francs, up from 5.7910; 1.9250 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.9245; 1,273.50 Italian lire, up from 1,273.10;
and 1.2220 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2318.
   Gold fell in Europe Wednesday, following Tuesday's drop in New
York.
   ``The price drop happened in New York and we're discovering that
Europe isn't strong enough to make much movement on its own,'' said
a bullion dealer in Zurich.
   Gold's late bid price in London was $458.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $463.50. In Zurich, gold was also
lower, closing at a bid $458.50 compared with $463.50 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.05 to close at a bid $458.98.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $7.15 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $7.34.
</TEXT>
