<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM-Maxwell,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM To Sell Publishing Unit For $150 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Wednesday it had agreed to sell an educational publishing unit
named Science Research Associates for $150 million to a company
headed by British publishing magnate Robert Maxwell.
   Chicago-based Science Research Associates, which IBM acquired in
1963, develops and publishes educational materials, achievement and
vocational tests and industrial training programs. The company,
which has more than 500 employees, is unrelated to IBM's primary
business of computers and other information-handling equipment and
services.
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC, whose chairman is Robert
Maxwell, is based in London and has U.S. headquarters in Greenwich,
Conn.
   The sale includes the unit's subsidiaries in Australia, Canada
and Britain. Science Research Associates, known as SRA, will
operate as SRA-Pergamon, a separate entity within Maxwell Pergamon
Publishing Group, based in Greenwich, Conn.
   The sales price is before any adjustments before closing.
</TEXT>
