<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Murdoch     06-08 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Murdoch,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News International To Launch New European Satellite TV Channels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News International PLC, a unit of Rupert Murdoch's
Australian-based News Corp., announced Wednesday a major expansion
of its European satellite television interests.
   The company said it would launch two, or perhaps three, new
channels early next year to supplement one currently in operation.
   An English-language all-news channel and a feature film channel
are expected to be launched in February 1989, joining News
International's existing general entertainment channel, Murdoch
told a news conference.
   The three channels, collectively known as Sky Television, will
operate 24 hours a day and will be funded from advertising revenue,
Murdoch said.
   Murdoch said he has signed a 10-year lease to rent from British
Telecommunications PLC three of 16 transponders available on an
Astra satellite, due to be launched in November by Societe
Europeenne des Satellites.
   News International also holds an option on a fourth transponder.
   The film channel initially will be available only in Britain,
while the other channels will be distributed in continental Europe
as well.
   Murdoch said he also expects the launch of a multilingual
all-sports channel, known as Eurosport, being set up jointly with
the European Broadcasting Union.
   Murdoch wouldn't provide details of how much News International
was investing in the expansion.
   Also attending the news conference was Alan Sugar, chairman of
Amstrad PLC, a U.K. computer manufacturer, who announced plans to
produce a cheap satellite dish designed to receive the new Murdoch
channels.
   Sugar said he expects to market the new dish in the first
quarter of 1989 at a basic retail price of 199 pounds ($362
dollars) each. Satellite television dishes currently sell in
Britain for at least 1,000 pounds ($1,820, Sugar said.
   Sky Television, which will be based in London, and Eurosport
also will be available through existing cable television hookups.
   Competitors for the European satellite television market include
British Satellite Broadcasting and a consortium including Maxwell
Communication Corp.
</TEXT>
