<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Say Transportation Secretary `Glossed Over' Safety
Problems</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to include name of union. Picks up 4th graf pvs
``We strenuously ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' pilots union says Transportation
Secretary James Burnley ``glossed over'' significant problems when
he talked with reporters last week about a federal report on the
company's safety practices.
   In the report, the Federal Aviation Administration said its
month-long investigation determined that Eastern was fit to fly.
   ``Our preliminary analysis of the ... report shows that the FAA
found significant problems at Eastern which had been identified by
Eastern pilots previous to the investigation, but which were either
glossed over, ignored or buried by Mr. Burnley when he gave his
interpretation of the report,'' the Air Line Pilots Association
said Tuesday in a statement.
   ``We strenuously object to (the) characterization of the report
presented by Mr. Burnley at his press conference,'' the ALPA said.
``Anyone who takes the trouble to read the full DOT report will
discover that the issues of concern are a far cry from those
described by Mr. Burnley.''
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Wednesday the safety
problems alleged by the union are the same type that led to the
federal investigation.
   ``The FAA has thoroughly examined Eastern,'' she said. ``The FAA
and DOT find Eastern to be safe and we're satisfied and pleased
with that report.
   ``These allegations are completely without merit.''
   In support of its statement, the ALPA cited specific safety
deficiencies noted in the report. Among those listed by the union:
   _Unairworthy aircraft were flown in 1987.
   _The maintenance budget is unproductively spent.
   _Eastern's on-time performance overrides maintenance
considerations.
   _On average, the dispatch system handles three times as many
flights as is normal for such airlines.
   _The weather department was dismantled, resulting in inadequate
weather information to pilots.
   However, the union reiterated that Eastern is safe ``because of
the professionalism of its pilots.''
</TEXT>
