<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-08 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean, Grain Futures Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures closed sharply
lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as isolated showers
brought relief to parched cropland in parts of the Midwest.
   But oat futures advanced strongly because the rain missed the
northern tier of states, which produce most of the country's oat
crop, analysts said.
   Soybean futures, which have climbed to four-year highs on fears
of drought damage, posted their steepest decline in two weeks as
bands of showers moved from Iowa into Illinois and Missouri.
   But nobody was declaring an end to the dry weather or to the
bull market for grains and soybeans.
   ``The overall drought-type conditions still appear to be
intact,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``This market has had explosive price action in response to
drought conditions,'' he said. ``Whenever you get into a situation
like that, the first sign of any potential relief brings a lot of
reaction from the market with a lot of profit-taking.''
   At the close, wheat was 6 cents to 10 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.70{ a bushel; corn was 7{ cents
to 9\ cents lower with July at $2.48 a bushel; oats were 7 cents to
12{ cents higher with July at $2.34 a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents
to 25{ cents lower with July at $8.62 a bushel.
</TEXT>
