<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ThirdWorldDebt     06-08 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Third World Debt,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Proposes To Cut Debt of Poorest Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France will forgive a third of its loans to the
world's poorest nations and is urging other big industrial powers
to take similar action, the president's office said Wednesday.
   The plan would not apply to the world's most indebted developing
nations, such as Brazil and Mexico, because they are not among the
poorest, although France believes ways also must be found to help
them, a spokesman said.
   The spokesman declined to put a value on the forgiven debts.
   In a related development, West Germany announced Wednesday that
it would forgive about $50 million in debts owed by five African
nations.
   French President Francois Mitterrand set out his proposal in a
letter sent Monday to the six other leaders attending the economic
summit June 19-21, special counselor Jacques Attali told reporters.
   ``It has never been so urgent and so necessary to act to help
the countries of the Third World, while the gap between rich
countries and poor countries continues to grow,'' Mitterrand wrote,
according to excerpts made public by his office.
   Mitterrand, President Reagan and the leaders of Canada, Britain,
West Germany, Italy and Japan are planning to attend the annual
three-day meeting in Toronto.
   In Bonn, West Germany, a government source said Chancellor
Helmut Kohl also planned to present summit participants with a
proposal for reducing the debt burden of the poorest nations.
   France is proposing that the seven nations agree to take one of
three approaches:
   _Forgive one-third of the total public or government-guaranteed
commercial debt, with the rest consolidated at normal market terms.
   _Consolidate existing debt at market rates of interest, but
extend repayments over 25 years rather than the current norm of 20
years.
   _Consolidate the debt at a preferential interest rate of no more
than half the market rate, but with repayments over about 15 years.
   ``It's a very new procedure,'' Attali said. ``With its menu of
options, it gives us reason to hope for a consensus.''
   Whether or not the summit partners agree, France intends to go
ahead with the first option, wiping out one-third of the debt,
Attali said.
   He refused to specify how much money was involved, beyond saying
the amount is ``not just in the hundreds of millions of francs.''
At current exchange rates, 100 million francs is about $17.2
million.
   Attali declined to identify the countries that would be
eligible, saying only that they numbered about 20. To qualify, a
nation must be extremely poor, deeply in debt and in the process of
improving the management of its economy, he said.
   In Bonn, the government's chief spokesman, Friedhelm Ost, told
reporters that West Germany had forgiven debts totaling 86 million
marks, or about $50.5 million, owed by the Central African
Republic, Togo, Guinea, Sierra Leone and Sudan.
   Ost said the govenment was considering the possibility of
extending partial debt forgiveness to other poor countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
