<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FedIntervention     06-08 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Intervention,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Bought $818 Million In February-April Period</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. monetary authorities cut back their
purchases of dollars to $818 million in the February-April period
as the stability of the U.S. currency lessened the need for
intervention, according to a report Wednesday.
   The dollar purchases, carried out by the Federal Reserve Bank of
New York, were down from the $4.14 billion purchased in the
previous three-month period.
   During the three months covered by the report, the dollar fell
1.5 percent against the currencies of other major industrialized
nations, weighted by the amount of trade conducted with each, the
New York Fed said.
   The dollar purchases are carried out on behalf of the Federal
Reserve and the U.S. Treasury.
   The New York Fed said it bought $318 million with Japanese yen
on March 25, 28 and 29 in coordination with dollar purchases by the
Bank of Japan.
   The U.S. authorities bought $240 million with West German marks
and $260 million with yen on April 14 and 15. Those purchases
followed the April 14 announcement of a widening of the U.S. trade
deficit in February and were coordinated with other central banks,
the New York Fed said.
   The New York Fed does not comment on its current
foreign-exchange operations.
</TEXT>
